<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-ShinBet     01-10 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Shin Bet,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unjustly Imprisoned Moslem Army Officer Sues The State, Shin Bet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Moslem Israeli army officer who spent more
than seven years in prison on false charges of spying is suing
Israel and secret service agents who interrogated him for $800,000,
a newspaper reported.
   Lt. Izzat Nafsu, 33, filed a suit in Nazareth district court on
Sunday seeking the damages from the state, eight agents of the Shin
Bet secret service and a psychiatrist, the Hadashot daily reported
Monday.
   A court spokesman in Nazareth could not immediately be reached
for comment.
   Nafsu was arrested while serving in southern Lebanon in late
1979, and a military court convicted him of treason and espionage in
1981 for allegedly passing weapons and information to the enemy.
   But Nafsu was released from prison in May 1987 after a Supreme
Court ruling that the security service had used illegal methods and
committed perjury.
   Nafsu is a member of Israel's Circassian minority of about 3,000
people, who are non-Arab Moslems. They are descendants of soldiers
who once protected the Turkish sultans, and are among the few
Moslems to serve in Israel's army.
   In his suit, Nafsu says Shin Bet agents questioned him after he
was put under hypnosis by the psychiatrist, Hadashot said.
   Nafsu has said that during questioning by Shin Bet officers he
was deprived of sleep, subjected to hot and cold showers and forced
to stand outdoors in freezing weather wearing only underwear.
</TEXT>
