<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil-Ecologist     01-10 1213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Ecologist,1254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slaying Of Brazilian Ecologist Dramatizes Battle To Preserve Amazon
^Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The murder of ecologist and union leader
Francisco ``Chico'' Mendes on Dec. 22, to which a rancher's son
confessed, focused attention on the struggle between
conservationists and ranchers in the vast Amazon rain forest. An AP
reporter visited the region and filed this report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>XAPURI, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dusk fell on a sultry evening just before
Christmas and Francisco ``Chico'' Mendes invited his two police
bodyguards to share a family dinner of fried fish, urging them to
start while he showered in the stall outside.
   It was a typically friendly gesture by Mendes. It also was a
fatal one.
   The bodyguards had become almost fixtures in the household since
Mendes began getting death threats because of his campaign to save
the Amazon rain forest from destruction by ranchers and land
speculators.
   ``I was nervous and worried,'' his widow, Ilzamar, said later.
``The death threats were getting more frequent. They said he
wouldn't make it past Christmas, but Chico tried to hide it from
me.''
   Mendes made it only to three days before Christmas.
   He was home at noon in the sleepy Amazon town of 5,000 people
2,700 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro, near the border with
Bolivia.
   At 4 p.m. he was engrossed in his favorite pastime: playing
dominoes with friends from the Workers Party and the local rubber
tappers union, of which he was president. As usual, he won.
   His friends left and, at 7 p.m., Mendes stood up and asked
Ilzamar to bring the new blue-and-white towel that was a present for
his 44th birthday a week earlier.
   Stepping to the back door of the four-room wooden cabin perched
on rotting wooden pilings, he peered past the coconut, guava and
cupuacu trees toward the silt-brown Acre River 50 yards away.
   ``It's so dark outside. Those guys could be out there waiting to
ambush me,'' he said, seeming almost to joke. The guards continued
eating.
   At least to men, perhaps three, crouched unseen 15 feet away near
the white concrete outhouse and shower stall.
   With his new towel over his right shoulder and a lantern in his
hand, Mendes cautiously pushed the door open.
   A .20-gauge shotgun boomed. Mendes staggered back, lurched past
the kitchen table to the door of the children's room and collapsed.
The killers fled through the back gate.
   ``I was on the sofa feeding the kids and raced back to the
kitchen,'' Ilzamar said. ``I passed the two bodyguards running the
other way. They jumped out of the window.
   ``Chico had his hands up to his head like he was in a lot of
pain. I just saw a little blood at first and thought, good, it's not
serious; he's going to live. But it was just that the towel was new
and it took awhile for the blood to soak through.''
   The shotgun blast blew a hole in the towel and left nearly 50
pellets in his chest and arms. He died almost immediately.
   ``I wanted to cry but couldn't,'' said Julio Barbosa de Aquino,
who succeeded Mendes as union president. ``Nobody believed they
could kill a man like that, who never hurt anybody.''
   A lifelong battle to preserve the rain forest made powerful
enemies for Mendes.
   He became a rubber tapper as a boy of 10 and believed the jungle
should be exploited for latex and Brazil nuts, not destroyed to make
cattle ranches. In the past decade, a section of rain forest the
size of California has been razed and burned for farms and pasture.
   Mendes helped unionize rubber tappers, and in 1976 was elected
assemblyman for Xapuri.
   With age, his ideas became more radical.
   ``In the beginning he wasn't political,'' Aquino said. ``He just
wanted to help tappers sell their latex and not be kicked off the
land. But ... lately he was talking about defense of the forest and
union of jungle peoples like tappers and Indians.''
   Ilzamar said Mendes admired Augusto Cesar Sandino, the Nicaraguan
revolutionary of 60 years ago, and named their 2-year-old son for
him. Their 4-year-old daughter, Elenira, was named for a Brazilian
communist guerrilla killed by soldiers during the military rule of
1964-85.
   ``He became much more radical,'' she said. ``He said he wouldn't
stand for another tree to be cut down. People called him a
communist. ... He said that if being a communist was defending the
Amazon and the rubber tappers, he accepted the name.''
   One technique Mendes used was the ``empate,'' or stalemate, in
which tappers, usually unarmed, would surround a work gang preparing
to raze a section of forest. They would withdraw only when the owner
signed an agreement to leave the area intact.
   Mendes preached non-violence but gunmen working for landowners
have ambushed and killed many tappers. Few have been brought to
trial.
   ``This is organized crime, and the cattle raisers and land
speculators are behind it,'' said Moacyr Grechi, Roman Catholic
bishop of Rio Branco, the Acre state capital 110 miles from Xapuri.
``They have total impunity, and Chico Mendes was on the firing line,
facing their gunmen every day,''
   Officials generally considered Mendes too rigid in his defense of
the environment.
   ``He wanted the total preservation of the forest, but we think
it's important to have economic development of the area too,'' said
Jose Carlos Castelo Branco, the Acre state secretary of security.
   The union leader's knowledge of the Amazon environment made him a
sought-after consultant to the World Bank and other institutions. He
traveled abroad and often had foreign visitors.
   ``There were teams of gringos here almost every week; they loved
my food,'' Ilzamar said, standing beside a bookcase that held
plaques from the U.N. Environment Program and the Better World
Society.
   Fatima Carvalho Mastub, a neighbor, said she took calls at all
hours from around the world for Mendes because he did not have a
telephone.
   A successful ``empate'' at the Cachoeira rubber grove, which
covers thousands of acres, probably led to his death.
   The owner was Darly Alves da Silva, a feared rancher wanted by
police in southern Parana state in connection with several killings.
   After the confrontation at Cachoeira, the federal government
expropriated the holding and made it an ``extractivist reserve,''
meaning the rubber and Brazil nut trees would remain for tappers and
harvesters.
   Mendes said da Silva vowed to kill him. He reported the threats
and Gov. Flaviano Melo gave him police protection.
   Four days after Mendes was killed, da Silva's 21-year-old son,
Darcy, confessed. He told reporters his father had been forced into
hiding to escape persecution by police and rubber tappers.
   Romeu Tuma, the federal police chief, said police believed the
shooting was ``a family decision'' by the da Silvas.
   Chico Mendes knew he was courting death. Mrs. Mastub, the
neighbor, quoted him as saying: ``I know I'm hanging by a thread,
but I'll keep going to the end.''
   Bishop Grechi said Mendes was ``just one of 89 murder victims in
rural Brazil in 1988, and not one of the killers has been brought to
justice. The solution is land reform, but the government doesn't
have the authority to carry it out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
