<SECOND>PM-BRF--Trident Launch,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trident 2 Missile Launched Successfully</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trident 2 submarine missile hurled
a dummy warhead to an Atlantic Ocean target, its 14th success in 18
test launchings, the Navy says.
   One or two more land pad tests are planned before the Navy begins
test firings from a submerged submarine.
   The $23.7 million missile roared off a land launching pad Monday.
   The 44-foot missile, the Navy's most powerful, has a range of
nearly 6,000 miles. Officials declined to disclose how far the dummy
warhead traveled.
   The first sub designed to carry the Trident 2, the USS Tennessee,
was commissioned Dec. 17 and is due at Cape Canaveral soon for sea
trials. The Tennessee is scheduled to begin test-firing the new
missile within a few weeks.
   The submarine is to go on patrol late this year with the first
operational Trident 2s. It will carry 24 missiles, each capable of
delivering 10 nuclear warheads to different targets.
