<FIRST>r i PM-Emperor-Poll     01-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emperor-Poll,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Majority Of Japanese Support Emperor As Symbol Of State: Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The demise of Emperor Hirohito has made the Japanese
people more aware and sympathetic toward the imperial system and
more than 80 percent support the monarch as the symbol of state, a
poll released today indicates.
   The survey, conducted shortly after Hirohito died from intestinal
cancer Saturday, showed 82 percent of the 1,876 people responding to
a random telephone interview supported the Japanese monarch as the
symbol of state.
   The figure was up 10 percentage points from a similar poll taken
three years ago, said the Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest
newspaper, which conducted the survey.
   Those who support that the emperor be given more power as a
``head of state'' rose 5 percentage points to total 9 percent, while
those who said they were indifferent to the monarch fell by 13
percentage points to 1.7 percent, the Yomiuri said.
   Regarding Akihito, Hirohito's successor to the Chrysanthemum
Throne, 70 percent of the respondents said they feel friendly toward
the new monarch, while 17 percent answered that they respected him.
Less than 1 percent of the people said they disliked the 55-year-old
Akihito.
   The poll also revealed that 50 percent of the people want the
imperial system to be more open, while 40 percent said there is no
need for change. The paper said 3,000 people were surveyed. It did
not give a margin for error.
   Under Japan's Constitution, the emperor, once considered a living
god, has no real political power and is regarded as ``a symbol of
the state and the unity of the people.'' His duties are largely
ceremonial and include meeting visiting dignitaries and fixing his
seal on bills passed by the government.
</TEXT>
