<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-10 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DESTIN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this Panhandle resort are
charging to rescue from developers a 30-foot-tall,
steel-and-concrete Green Knight outside a lounge and liquor store of
the same name.
   The armor-clad statue has been a tourist attraction along U.S. 98
for more than 20 years. Community supporters raised money to repair
the sentinel after a 1985 hurricane took off an arm.
   Now, about 200 fans of the knight have signed a petition urging
City Hall to save the statue from developers who want to take it
down to make way for a shopping center.
   The knight qualifies as roadside architecture, a part of
Americana that is rapidly disappearing, said city Librarian Dooney
Tickner, who is leading the petition drive.
   ``If they don't keep him there, I've proposed that they move him
to a new park ... to serve as a focal point for the children's
playground,'' Tickner said.
   The green warrior has received at least a temporary reprieve
because of a delay in plans for the shopping center, said W.G. Ivey,
owner-manager of the lounge and package store. Ms. Ivey said she has
been surprised by the support because some people had criticized the
statue recently for detracting from the city's appearance.
   ``Now we get people in here all the time who aren't even
interested in buying anything,'' she said. ``They just want to ask
us not to tear it down, and sign a petition if we have one. It's
strange how things change.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FREEMAN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This southeastern Virginia community averages
800 pieces of mail a day, but lately Joseph E. Clark has been
getting more than his share.
   Clark has received more than 3,000 pieces of mail recently from
Exxon Travel Club Inc. in Houston, said postmaster Emmett Raney. A
total of 1,874 pink-and-white envelopes arrived for Clark in the
first batch, followed by 995 a few days later and 300 more soon
after.
   Last week, 400 more arrived, including 50 on Friday, Raney said.
   Clark took time off from deer hunting recently to read one of the
letters and told Raney to throw away the rest, the postmaster said.
   A note on the mailbag advised to contact Bill Cooper of R.L. Polk
&amp; Co. in Berea, Ohio, a Cleveland suburb, if there were problems.
   Cooper, who said he runs a shop mailing thousands of pieces of
mail for corporations, said he had not known of the mass mailing to
Clark.
   ``It's obvious that we had a computer hang-up,'' Cooper said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wisconsin legislator proud of the state's
dairy heritage is urging a national fast-food chain to promote
specials on cheeseburgers as well as hamburgers.
   Democratic Rep. Mary Hubler wrote Burger King officials Monday
that she was concerned that the chain was offering reduced prices
only on Whoppers without cheese and regular hamburgers. She said it
was the second straight year the chain had excluded cheeseburgers
from its specials.
   ``In the Dairy State, Burger King should be promoting their
sandwiches with cheese and taking an active role in the overall
promotion of the dairy industry,'' Ms. Hubler said.
   A Burger King official said his company wasn't discriminating
against cheese.
   ``We try to rotate the specials, and a number of them have
involved Whoppers and cheeseburgers,'' said Tim D. Thorpe, marketing
manager in Burger King's regional office in Minneapolis.
   ``Our franchises in Wisconsin are well aware that they are in the
dairy state,'' Thorpe said.
</TEXT>
