<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-IndividualImpact     01-10 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Individual Impact,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan's Budget: You Pay More, You Get Less</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor old Amtrak. Even in Ronald Reagan's last
shot, his proposed budget for fiscal 1990, the president is trying
to kill off the rail passenger service as a waste of taxpayers'
money.
   Reagan complains that the government pays $30 to Amtrak every
time a passenger gets on a train to anywhere. Without that federal
subsidy of about $600 million a year, Amtrak officials say, the
entire rail network would have to be scrapped. The Reagan
administration favors a regional system instead.
   If Reagan's budget plan succeeds this time, Amtrak's demise would
be one of many ways that Americans would get less from the
government, or pay more for what they get.
   ``On many routes it would be cheaper for the federal government
to buy bus or plane tickets for Amtrak passengers rather than
subsidize train travel,'' says the administration, urging Congress
to just say no to Amtrak.
   ``Amtrak is not economically viable,'' the budget message said
Monday. ``About 85 percent of its routes recover less than 57 cents
on the dollar.''
   Proposed saving: $515 million a year.
   Another cost-cutting measure would require taxpayers to pay 50
cents or $1 to call what currently is the government's toll-free
number for help with their income tax returns.
   The charge would be called ``a user fee.''
   Under Reagan's budget plan for next year, the government would
charge more or provide less to boat owners, veterans with slightly
disabling war injuries, commuters, air travelers, federal retirees,
doctors, people who lose their jobs to foreign competition and
middle-class youngsters who eat subsidized lunches at school.
   Reagan noted that even students at ``high tuition private schools
can get meal subsidies.'' He proposed eliminating all 40-cent
lunches for children from families well above the poverty line. The
price of a lunch would rise about 26 cents, unless state or local
school districts made up the difference.
   The president wants to save $1.2 billion over the next five years
by ending ``trade adjustment assistance,'' which provides weekly
cash benefits, training, job search aid and relocation allowances to
those who lose their jobs because of imports.
   ``It is inequitable for the federal government to provide a
special program to benefit one group of unemployed workers or
uncompetitive firms,'' the budget message says.
   Reagan also would cut down on the 8,000 map makers working in
more than 20 federal departments and agencies at a cost of more than
$1 billion a year. The administration will see whether it's cheaper
to contract some of the work out.
   For the homeless, Reagan proposes a program under which the
government would buy enough food to supply food kitchens and food
banks with 256 million meals.
   He called for ``an aggressive prison building program'' to ease
overcrowding, but would eliminate subsidies that help operate
subways and buses for commuters and a program that assures air
service for many small communities.
   Military veterans with service-connected injuries that give them
disability ratings of 20 percent or less would have to look to
private health insurance for their care in veterans' hospitals,
under Reagan's plan. The government now pays for that care.
   Doctors would have to accept smaller fees for treating the
elderly under Medicare and the poor under Medicaid. Getting
especially less would be radiologists, anesthesiologists and
surgeons.
   Homebuyers would see a nearly fourfold increase _ to 3.8 percent
_ in the current 1 percent fee for VA mortgage loan guarantees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-NuclearWeapons     01-10 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Nuclear Weapons,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Proposes $3 Billion For Cleanup, Modernization of Atomic Arms
Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is proposing a
half-billion dollar increase in spending next year to begin cleaning
up and modernizing the nation's nuclear bomb factories, lately
crippled by environmental and safety problems.
   The proposal, contained in the administration's proposed fiscal
1990 budget for the Department of Energy, was called a first step
toward revitalizing the government's nuclear weapons production
complex, which is administered by the department.
   ``The process is in place ... to address this problem in the long
term,'' said Joseph F. Salgado, the deputy energy secretary. He said
priorities were being developed for a cleanup and modernization
effort that could last 50 years or more.
   Cleanup work is expected to cost at least $81 billion over the
next 20 years.
   The department, in the budget proposals unveiled Monday, said it
would seek $18 billion over the next five years to build new atomic
arms plants and to improve the existing weapons complex of 17 major
factories and laboratories in 12 states.
   For the 1990 budget year, which begins next Oct. 1, President
Reagan asked Congress to approve spending of $3 billion for
modernization, environmental and safety programs at the weapons
plants. That is $478 million more than is being spent on such
programs in the current fiscal year.
   The proposal quickly drew criticism from Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio,
who likened the environmental threat posed by pollution from the
nuclear production facilities _ including a uranium processing plant
at Fernald, Ohio _ to a time bomb.
   The amount proposed by Reagan for cleaning up the plants in 1990
is ``just a token of what is needed,'' Glenn said at a Capitol Hill
news conference. ``The reality is that these ... sites are an
environmental time bomb. It's still ticking.''
   Glenn said he hoped the incoming Bush administration would ask
Congress for much more money _ as much as $4 billion a year for
cleanup and modernization.
   Energy Department officials gave no comprehensive breakdown of
proposed spending on individual nuclear weapons manufacturing
plants, although they said the budget proposal included a request
for $55 million to clean up the Fernald plant. That compares with
$50 million expected to be spent in the current budget year.
   Also, the department asked for $54 million for cleanup at the
Hanford nuclear reservation near Richland, Wash., an increase of $26
million from this year; and $56 million for the Savannah River plant
near Aiken, S.C., up from $19 million.
   The department also requested $303 million to begin developing
two new nuclear weapons facilities to replace three 35-year-old
reactors at Savannah River, which have been shut down since last
April for safety and technical reasons. The Savannah River facility
is the nation's only source of tritium, a highly perishable gas used
to boost the explosive power of nuclear warheads.
   The department has estimated the cost of building the two new
reactors at $6.8 billion. Both would be expected to be in operation
by the turn of the century.
   Among other spending proposals in the overall $15 billion energy
budget are:
   _$145 million for research on energy conservation, down from $156
million in the current budget year.
   _$383 million for fossil energy research and development,
including projects aimed at finding ways of getting more crude oil
from existing wells, and to expand the use of coal. That is down
from $446 million in the current budget for such projects.
   _$322 million on nuclear energy research, a decline from $357
million in the current budget year.
</TEXT>
