<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-SpaceandScience     01-10 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Space and Science,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Space Station Funds Sought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's proposed budget provides
generous support for science and space research next year, with a
boost in total outlays to $14.9 billion and emphasis on developing a
permanently manned space station.
   In the budget plan for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1, space
and science spending would rise by $2.4 billion. The space station
planned by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration would
get $2.1 billion and an unusual advance commitment for billions more
over a three-year period.
   The final budget of the Reagan administration, sent to Congress
on Monday, also supports the $4.4 billion superconducting
supercollider proposed by the Department of Energy, and would
bolster basic research programs of the National Science Foundation
by $2 billion.
   The suggested outlay for the space station is more than double
the current fiscal year's spending ceiling of $900 million.
   The space station, a huge orbiting craft designed to house
astronauts permanently in space, is America's major effort to
reclaim undisputed leadership in space research.
   Spending authority of $250 million was proposed for the
supercollider, a massive project that is to be built in Texas for
the study of sub-atomic particles. The funds would cover early
expenses for the start of construction.
   Money for the space station helps boost the suggested outlays for
NASA by $1.8 billion. In addition to the station, the increase would
finance nine space shuttle flights, compared with five during fiscal
1989.
   It also would help pay for improvements in the current shuttle
fleet and allow continued work on a replacement for the destroyed
space shuttle Challenger.
   Under the Reagan plan, laws would be passed to limit space
station construction costs to $13 billion in 1984 dollars. Allowing
for inflation, that would limit the station project to $16 billion.
   However, this does not include operating costs, which are
estimated to about equal construction spending.
   Two unusual provisions cover the NASA proposal.
   One provides for a three-year advance of $8.5 billion in spending
authority ``to maintain the current schedule of development
activities leading to an operating capability in the mid-1990s'' for
the space station.
   The other, imposed by requirements of the Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction law, would give President-elect Bush the opportunity
effectively to block space station development by ordering funds
withheld.
   If Bush chooses to, he can notify Congress that he does not wish
to spend $515 million appropriated last year for the station, a
powerful signal that he does not approve of a further
much-accelerated effort. If he takes no action the appropriated
money will be spent beginning May 15.
   The proposed 1990 funds would also pay for:
   _ Improvements in the shuttle fleet to allow missions of up to 30
days.
   _ Launch of the Hubble Space Telescope, the Galileo space probe
to Jupiter and collection of data from Voyager II's rendezvous with
the planet Neptune.
   _ Start of development of a flight past an asteroid and a comet.
   _ Upgrading research on sub-atomic particles at the Fermi
National Laboratory and the Stanford (Calif.) Linear Accelerator
Center.
   _ National Science Foundation contributions to a research program
aimed at understanding the Earth-warming ``greenhouse effect'' and
other changes in the Earth's climate and weather. Funds for studies
of climatic changes also would be increased from $9 million to $20
million in the National Oceanographic and Atmospheric
Administration's proposed budget.
</TEXT>
