<FIRST>r i PM-Crash-Survivors     01-10 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash-Survivors,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Pay Tribute To Skill Of Captain In Saving Lives</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>NOTTINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of the Boeing 737 crash
praised the skill and cool nerves of the pilot for guiding the
crippled aircraft over a village as he attempted an emergency
airport landing.
   ``Considering the trouble he was in, he must have nursed that
plane to get so close (to the airport). He must have done a
brilliant job. I pray for him and hope he is OK,'' said Gareth
Jones, 38, who suffered chest injuries.
   Pilot Kevin Hunt, 43, managed to keep the 12-week-old British
Midland Airways jet, with one engine on fire and the second
apparently failing, skimming over rooftops as he made for East
Midlands Airport in central England.
   The Belfast-bound plane plowed into a highway embankment a
half-mile short of the runway on Sunday, killing 44 people and
injuring the 82 others on board.
   David Thomas, a surgeon at Derbyshire Royal Infirmary, one of the
hospitals handling the casualties, said: ``It is incredible to have
this number of survivors from a major accident. That has got to be
down to the skill of the pilot.''
   A radio ham operator was quoted today as saying the crew was so
calm before the crash it was hard to imagine anything was wrong.
   ``Whoever was in cockpit contact with the East Midlands (Airport)
controller sounded so calm it was difficult to image anything was
amiss,'' Richard Whittington was quoted as saying in The Times of
London.
   ``There was no panic or fear detectable in his voice. Instead, he
was precise, as though he was receiving everyday instructions. Only
when I heard the air traffic controller, who certainly did not sound
as calm, did I realize something must be terribly wrong.''
   Hunt, a 22-year veteran with the airline, was seriously injured
with spine and leg fractures. He was trapped for 2{ hours before
rescuers managed to free him from the smashed cockpit.
   Skillfully, Hunt kept the plane from plowing into the
2,000-resident village of Kegworth.
   Village resident Bill Tidy said: ``The pilot hung on until the
last minute. What a man.'' Another resident, Andrew Pendleton, said:
``Suddenly the pilot seemed to pull the nose up and the plane just
glided past.''
   Transport Minister Paul Channon, who visited the crash site
Monday, also praised firefighers who arrived within minutes,
spraying foam over the plane to prevent a blaze. He said their speed
saved many lives.
   Survivor Mary McHugh, 23, said: ``We were only on the ground for
three of four minutes before people started pulling us off. But
first there was the foam. It just hit us. Large amounts of it. I
thought, wow, it was great. It meant we weren't going to get
burned.''
   Jones said he held the hand of a young woman next to him during
the rapid descent. ``When the first engine went she started crying
and held my hand,'' he was quoted as saying.
   ``I tried to joke about how these things could fly on one engine
and glide down. Then the second engine went and she gripped my hand
and I said there was no way we were not getting out of that plane
together. I knew if I showed I had any fear she would have been
worse.''
   Firefighter Eric Moss, who worked more than six hours helping
free survivors and getting out the dead, told a grimmer story.
   ``The conditions inside were very difficult. Very tight and very
hot. We were taking away layer upon layer of wreckage inside the
fuselage ... There were layers of bodies.''
</TEXT>
