<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     01-10 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices topped Monday's record high on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange Tuesday, while the U.S. dollar edged down from
the previous day's close.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which reached a record high
of 30,678.39 Monday, gained another 328.12 points, or 1.07 percent,
to close at 31,006.51, a new record high.
   The dollar closed unchanged from its opening at 125.70 yen, down
0.38 yen from Monday's finish of 126.03. The currency moved between
125.50 yen and 126.00 yen.
   Dealers said trading was fast with institutional investors and
individuals actively buying stocks.
   Foreign securities firms also bought up spot issues to help push
the market's main economic barometer up, added a dealer with a major
securities firm in Tokyo who spoke anonymously.
   On the foreign exchange market, the U.S. currency's lower opening
followed an overnight decline in New York, dealers said. The dollar
closed at 125.95 yen on Wall Street Monday, down from a 126.78-yen
close the previous session.
   ``The sentiment toward the dollar's bearishness has basically
remained in the market,'' said a Bank of Tokyo dealer, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
