<DOCNO> AP890110-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief 1stLd-Writethru   01-10 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief, 1st Ld-Writethru,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Awards First Seawolf Submarine Contract To Electric Boat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``The Electric...'' to CORRECT figure
to $725.95 million; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``The SSN-21...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has awarded the contract to build the
first Seawolf submarine, touted as faster, quieter and having twice
the fire power of the subs it is expected to replace.
   The Electric Boat Division of General Dynamics Corp. won the
$725.95 million contract over the Newport News Shipbuilding Co. of
Virginia, the Navy announced Monday. The two companies compete
annually for SSN-688 Los Angeles class submarine contracts.
   The SSN-21 Seawolf, which has been in the research and design
stage for seven years, had been criticized by some lawmakers who
charged that it was not advanced enough to meet the Soviets' planned
successor to their Akula attack sub. A House subcommittee tried to
delay funding in 1987, but full research funding was later restored
by Congress.
   Navy officials say the Seawolf is faster, quieter and has double
the fire power of the Los Angeles-class subs, which it is expected
to replace as the nation's chief fast-attack submarine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Labor Department Reports Record Low Mining Fatalities in 1988</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of deaths in the nation's mines
dropped to 100 in 1988, a decline of 30 from the previous year and
the lowest number in the 87 years the federal government has tracked
mine fatalities, the Labor Department said.
   Fifty-two of the 1988 deaths were in coal mines, eclipsing a
record low of 63 fatalities in that sector of the mining industry in
1987, the Labor Department's Mine Safety and Health Administration
announced Monday.
   In other types of mines, there were 48 reported fatalities in
1988, a decrease of one from the previous low of 49 in 1986, the
agency reported.
   The overall previous low for mine deaths was 125 in 1985.
   A contributing factor in the 1988 total was a sharp decline in
deaths blamed on roof collapses in underground coal mines. There
were eight such deaths recorded in 1988, down from 18 the year
before and 26 in 1986.
   The Labor Department speculated that use of new temporary roof
support systems, required by the government since January 1988, may
have contributed to the decline in roof collapses. The temporary
supports are used while miners install permanent supports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Book Awards Announced</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Fleischman and Stephen Gammel won the 1989
Newbery and Caldecott medals for the best children's books of the
year, the American Library Association has announced.
   Fleischman, of Pacific Grove, Calif., received the Newbery Medal
for ``Joyful Noise: Poems for Two Voices,'' which celebrates the
insect world in imagery, rhyme and onomatopoeia.
   Gammel, of St. Paul, Minn., received the Caldecott Medal for his
illustrations of ``Song and Dance Man,'' a book written by Karen
Ackerman about a grandfather recreating his vaudevillian past for
his grandchildren.
   The awards were announced at a news conference Monday at the
American Library Association's midwinter meeting. The winners were
chosen by two 15-member committees of its Association for Library
Service to Children division.
   The Caldecott and Newbery prizes often mark books for best-seller
status among both children's librarians and parents. The Newbery
Medal has been awarded annually since 1922 and the Caldecott Medal
since 1938.
   The committees also named six runner-up or ``honor'' books.
   The two Newbery Honor books are: ``In the Beginning: Creation
Stories from Around the World,'' by Virginia Hamilton, and
``Scorpion,'' by Walter Dean Myers.
   The four Caldecott Honor books are: ``The Boy of the Three Year
Nap,'' illustrated by Allen Say, written by Dianne Snyder; ``Free
Fall,'' illustrated by David Wiesner; ``Goldilocks and the Three
Bears,'' illustrated by James Marshall, and ``Mirandy and Brother
Wind,'' illustrated by Jerry Pinknew, written by Patricia C.
McKissack.
</TEXT>
