<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BaseballNewspage     01-10 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baseball Newspage,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bench, Yastrzemski Elected To Baseball Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catcher Johnny Bench and slugger Carl Yastrzemski
were overwhelmingly elected to baseball's Hall of Fame in their
first year of eligibility.
   Bench got 431 votes from 447 ballots cast Monday night by members
of the Baseball Writers Association of America. Yastrzemski, the
American League's only batter to compile 3,000 hits and 400-plus
home runs, received 423 votes.
   To be elected, a player must be named on 75 percent of the
ballots cast. A player needed 336 votes to be elected this year.
   Bench got 96.4 percent and Yastrzemski 94.6. Only immortals Ty
Cobb, 98.2 percent, and Hank Aaron, 97.8, received higher
percentages than Bench. Yastrzemski's percentage was the
seventh-highest.
   ``There's a finality to it all, to reach a level so few people
reach,'' said Bench, the former Cincinnati Reds star.
   ``It's a thrill. It's the culmination of many years of hard work.
It's something, as a player, you don't think about,'' said
Yastrzemski, who played with the Boston Red Sox.
   Only one other player in this year's balloting received as many
as 300 votes. Gaylord Perry, a 300-game winner, finished third with
304, missing election by 32 votes.
   Induction ceremonies at the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown are
scheduled for July 23.
   Only 17 of the 200 current members were elected in their first
year of eligibility. Players are eligible five years after they
retire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
