<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-CentralAmerica     01-10 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central America,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Postpones Summit Over Ortega's Objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over Nicaragua's objections, a
Central American summit scheduled for next weekend in San Salvador
has been postponed until after the inauguration of President-elect
Bush.
   The meeting of five Central American presidents would seek to
advance a stalled regional peace plan. El Salvador's foreign
minister said it could convene as early as Jan. 29.
   Foreign Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto told a news conference in
San Jose on Monday that the presidents of Honduras and El Salvador
had agreed with President Oscar Arias' suggestion that the summit be
postponed.
   Arias proposed the delay on Friday, saying Bush should be given
time to formulate a Central American policy. Bush takes office Jan.
20.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua insisted late Monday that
any decision to delay the meeting should be made jointly by all five
regional presidents.
   Speaking on Nicaragua's state-run radio, he added, however that
if the meeting is not held next Sunday and Monday as originally
planned, ``it must be held as soon as possible.''
   Ortega had said a postponement could ``practically kill'' the
peace plan. His leftist Sandinista government has been fighting
U.S.-backed Contra rebels, who lost Washington's military support
nearly a year ago. The belligerents signed a cease-fire accord on
March 23, but peace talks have stalled.
   Guatemala also objected to the postponement.
   ``We reiterate: it is urgent that the five Central American
leaders converge in one place to analyze the Central Amercian
situation,'' Foreign Minister Alfonso Cabrera Hidalgo said Monday.
   Foreign Minister Ricardo Acevedo of El Salvador said President
Jose Napoleon Duarte believed the summit could be held on schedule
only if the presidents of all five countries agreed.
   He said Jan. 29-30 or Feb. 20 were being considered as alternate
dates.
   Honduras did not comment. President Jose Azcona Hoyo traveled to
Washington on Monday and was to meet today with President Reagan and
Bush.
   Madrigal Nieto said foreign ministers from the five countries
would converge in the Nicaraguan capital on Jan. 17-18 to discuss an
agenda.
   He denied that postponement could jeopardize the regional peace
plan, which was authored by Arias and signed by the five presidents
in August 1987.
   The plan calls for greater democracy, an end to civil wars,
political amnesties and an end to the use of one country by rebels
fighting in another. It has been stalled since the presidents last
met a year ago in Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
