<FIRST>r i PM-Hirohito-Bush     01-10 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-Bush,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bush Heading To Hirohito Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush plans to attend the Feb. 24
funeral of Emperor Hirohito in his first foreign trip as the U.S.
leader, the Kyodo news service quoted the head of Bush's transition
team as saying.
   The Kyodo report from Washington quoted Craig Fuller, the
transition chief, as saying Monday ``our understanding at present''
is that Bush will attend the state funeral.
   Kyodo said the dates of Bush's visit to Japan would be decided in
consultation with James Baker, Bush's secretary of state, and Brent
Scowcroft, the new national security adviser.
   Fuller was quoted as saying the trip to Tokyo would be Bush's
first foreign trip after he takes the oath of office Jan. 20.
   Washington so far has not announced who will be the U.S.
representative at Hirohito's funeral, and an official at the Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita's office said today that he had no
information about a Bush visit.
   Representatives of more than 100 countries are expected to attend.
   The government today announced that it will allocate $61.4
million for the funeral and a mausoleum for Hirohito, who died
Saturday of cancer at age 87. The Cabinet approved the amount at a
morning meeting, Defense Agency chief Kichiro Tazawa told a
briefing. He said the amount will include $25.6 million for the
funeral and $19.2 million for security.
   More than 30,000 police will be mobilized to ensure the safety of
visiting foreign dignitaries and to ward off any disruptive actions
by extremists, Shigenobu Sakano, chairman of the National Safety
Commission, said at the Cabinet meeting.
   Tazawa said $14.4 million will be allotted to constructing the
late emperor's mausoleum in Hachioji, 28 miles west of the capital.
   ``That will be an appropriate amount to make solemn but not showy
(events),'' Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told Japanese reporters.
   Hirohito death ended a 62-year reign. His eldest son, Akihito,
ascended to the throne, which has limited powers.
   In some countries, the issue of attending Hirohito's funeral has
caused controversy because of his role as Japan's titular ruler in
World War II. Historians generally agree that he went along with
wartime decisions by military leaders, but made the decision to
surrender to the Allies in 1945.
</TEXT>
