<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0457EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSSurvey     01-10 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Survey,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Survey Measures Spirit of Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health authorities seeking to learn how many
Americans carry the AIDS virus hope the offer of $50 and a plea for
cooperation will attract people in high-risk groups to participate
in a pilot survey.
   ``That's one of the major problems with which we're wrestling and
which we've spent a lot of time trying to determine how to
evaluate,'' said Dr. James R. Allen, an assistant deputy director at
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control.
   The survey began Monday with the mailing of letters to 350
randomly selected households in Allegheny County asking people to
anonymously reveal their sexual practices and give blood for $50. If
the effort succeeds, the survey could be extended nationwide.
   ``If high-risk individuals avoid the survey, there's no point''
in conducting a national survey, said Dr. Bruce W. Dixon, chief of
the sexually transmissible disease program of the county health
department.
   In August, officials abandoned an attempted pilot survey in
Washington, D.C., after opponents said the effort unfairly targeted
blacks, said Peter Hurley, an associate director of the National
Center for Health Statistics.
   Officials say they learned their lesson and planned the
Pittsburgh-area survey with the unanimous consent of a 21-member
advisory panel drawn from the community.
   ``Every concern that was expressed by members of the advisory
panel was taken into consideration and changes were made,'' said
panel member Leslie Hunt Turner, assistant administrator of the Alma
Illery Medical Center, which is located in a predominantly black
neighborhood.
   ``Everyone was skeptical,'' said Mrs. Turner. ``It wasn't a thing
where we said, `Yeah, this is a great idea. Let's go for it.' ''
   Success here, ideally in the form of 85 percent participation,
will lead to an expanded preliminary survey elsewhere, officials
said. Dallas and San Diego are among the communities on the CDC's
short list for the next round, Allen said.
   If all goes well, the planners could ask Congress as early as
next year for the estimated $25 million needed for a national
survey, Allen said.
   The advisory panel persuaded the planners not to ask for the
individual's day of birth, just the month and year, to ensure
privacy.
   A question on marital status accounts for divorce and same-sex
cohabitation to reflect ``a lot of differences in living
arrangements in today's society,'' Mrs. Turner said.
   The actual results will be meaningless because so few of the
county's 850,000 housholds are to be questioned, Dixon said.
   The effort could, however, define the methods to be used
nationwide. People who decline to participate will be asked why and
their answers will be used to delete objectionable aspects from the
survey, officials said.
   On Saturday, professional interviewers and technicians trained to
draw blood, working in teams of two, will begin the four- to
six-week job of knocking on the 350 doors, asking one person age 18
to 54 in each home to participate.
   Those who agree will be paid $50. They will be asked such
questions as whether they have ever engaged in behavior that risks
exposure to the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency
syndrome. Risky behavior includes sex with an infected partner,
intravenous drug use by addicts and blood transfusions.
   Officials said each participant will complete the questionnaire
out of sight of the interviewer and technician and will seal it in a
tamper-proof wrapper for mailing. Neither the blood sample nor the
questionnaire will be labeled with the person's identity.
   Officials said the interviewer and technician will never see the
answers and they risk being fired and fined $5,000 for opening the
sealed questionnaire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
