<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     01-10 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Another Record High, Dollar Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index climbed
sharply to a record high for the second consecutive day today, while
the dollar fell against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shot up
468.85 points on Monday, gained another 328.12 points, or 1.07
percent, closing at 31,006.51 today.
   Trading was very active with both individuals and institutional
investors participating, dealers said. Volume traded on the first
section was estimated at 1.5 billion shares.
   ``The market was inactive for quite a while until last week,
mainly due to concerns over the late emperor's condition, but I
never thought investors had kept so much money to buy stocks,'' said
one, speaking on condition that he not be named.
   Emperor Hirohito died of intestinal cancer on Saturday at age 87.
He had been seriously ill since Sept. 19, and caution had prevailed
on the stock market, with investors anxious about the effects of a
temporary halt to business for mourning.
   But markets canceled only their half-day Saturday sessions.
   The dealer said foreign securities firms also were buying on
Tuesday, helping to push prices up.
   Dealers said a majority of buyers were interested in stocks newly
issued in the Heisei era, the official name given to the reign of
the new emperor, Akihito, who ascended to the throne when Hirohito
died. The reign name is used on Japanese calendars and official
documents. Hirohito's reign name was Showa.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 125.70 yen,
down 0.38 yen from Monday's close of 126.08 yen and unchanged from
today's opening. It ranged between 125.50 yen and 126.00 yen in
today's trading.
   Traders selling West German marks for yen helped to strengthen
the yen against the dollar too, dealers said.
   He said the dollar-yen rate was likely to stay within a narrow
range until the next U.S. monthly trade figures are announced in
mid-January.
</TEXT>
