<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-McMillan     01-10 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-McMillan,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Character Actor Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth McMillan, a veteran character
actor who appeared in movies, television shows and plays on and off
Broadway, has died. He was 56.
   McMillan, who died Sunday of liver failure at St. John's
Hospital, played Jack Doyle, Rhoda Morgenstern's boss in the hit
1970s CBS series ``Rhoda,'' and appeared in such movies as
``Ragtime'' and ``The Pope of Greenwich Village.''
   The Brooklyn-born actor McMillan appeared on Broadway in the
original production of David Mamet's ``American Buffalo.'' He
received an Obie award for his off-Broadway performance in
``Weekends Like Other People.''
   McMillan also appeared Joseph Papp's productions of ``Henry V,''
``The Merry Wives of Windsor,'' ``Where Do We Go From Here,'' ``Kid
Champion,'' and the original Mike Nichols-directed ``Streamers.''
   The ``Rhoda'' assignment was his first full-time television work,
and his first movie appearance was in 1973's ``Serpico.''
   He also appeared in the movies ``Eye Witness,'' ``True
Confessions,'' ``Reckless,'' ``Dune,'' ``Runaway Train,'' and
``Protocol.''
   He recently completed a leading role in the Disney film, ``Three
Fugitives,'' said his publicist, Frank Liberman.
   He is survived by a wife, Kathryn, a former Broadway dancer, and
a daughter, Allison, an actress.
   Private services will follow cremation. A memorial service will
be held Jan. 29 at the Debbie Reynolds Studios in Burbank, where
McMillan often taught classes. The family has requested that any
donations go to the Actors Fund.
</TEXT>
