<HEAD>Snow in East, West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow or rain fell in the East, the Midwest and the West today
after wet weather in Oregon caused mudslides that closed three
highways and triggered a flood warning.
   Snow fell at higher elevations in Virginia, Tennessee and North
Carolina, and rain stretched from Delaware to Florida, and in
Tennessee, Alabama, Mississippi and Louisiana.
   In New York state's snowbelt, a snow squall warning was posted
east of Lake Ontario. On Monday, Barnes Corners received 20 inches
of snow, Adams got 18 and Lowville got 12 to 14.
   Snow fell today in Michigan and Minnesota and from Montana to the
Idaho Panhandle and the mountains of the Pacific Northwest. Rain
fell from the Pacific Northwest to the northern coast of California.
   Heavy snow warnings were in effect for Idaho and Montana, and
snow advisories were issued for Washington state and Oregon.
Advisories for snow and blowing snow were up in Utah, Wyoming and
Colorado. In Utah, the Highway Patrol closed a state road because of
blowing, drifting snow.
   Three western Oregon highways were closed Monday by mudslides
that followed heavy rains. The National Weather Service issued a
flood warning for the Wilson River near Tillamook about 50 miles
west of Portland. The river was expected to crest 1 foot above flood
stage today.
   In northeastern Oregon, 4 to 10 inches of snow closed most Union
County schools Monday.
   In California, chilly weather gripped inland San Diego County for
the fourth day in a row, prompting a frost advisory and a prediction
of crop damage. Temperatures were expected to drop to 27 degrees in
some areas.
   Today's forecast called for snow from the lower Great Lakes to
New Jersey, and north to southern New England, with snow changing to
or mixed with rain in southern New Jersey, Maryland, Delaware,
northern Virginia and West Virginia. Rain showers were expected from
the rest of Virginia to northern Florida, the central Gulf Coast
states and the western Gulf Coast; show showers from upper Michigan
to eastern Wisconsin; snow from the upper Missouri Valley to the
northern and central Rockies; and rain in the northern and central
Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were predicted in the single digits and teens
from the upper Missouri Valley to North Dakota, most of South
Dakota, the upper Mississippi Valley, northern Wisconsin and upper
Michigan; teens in northern New England; and 20s and 30s from
southern Maine to the Great Lakes and the Virginia and from Ohio to
Iowa, Nebraska and the Rockies. The 60s were expected for northern
Florida and from southwest Texas to Southern California; near 80
degrees in the Florida Keys; and in the 40s and 50s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from minus 27
degrees at Williston, N.D., to 72 degrees at Key West, Fla.
    Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 43 foggy; Boston 27 cloudy; Buffalo 17 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 47 cloudy; Cincinnati 25 fair; Cleveland 24 fair;
Detroit 22 partly cloudy; Miami 68 fair; New York 32 cloudy;
Philadelphia 32 cloudy; Pittsburgh 20 fair; Portland, Maine 22
partly cloudy; Washington 36 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck -27 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 31 fair; Denver 28
fair; Des Moines 31 fair; Indianapolis 22 partly cloudy; Kansas City
32 fair; Minneapolist-St. Paul 1 fair; Nashville 37 cloudy; New
Orleans 55 cloudy; St. Louis 29 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 23 fair; Anchorage 17 cloudy; Las Vegas 32
fair; Los Angeles 52 fair; Phoenix 43 fair; Salt Lake City 36 windy;
San Diego 47 fair; San Francisco 48 foggy; Seattle 40 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 fair; Toronto 16 fair.
