<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DebateChamps     01-10 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debate Champs,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Australian Team Champs In World Universities Debating Contest At
Princeton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Australian students turned society's
love of money into a winning argument to capture debating's most
prestigious tournament for the University of Sydney Union.
   ``Let's look at the real world,'' said Warren Lee, who teamed
with Andrew Bell to win the 9th Annual World Universities Debating
Championship at Princeton University.
   ``People don't say, `Let's all join the Peace Corps and be nice
guys.'''
   That thrust helped the pair defeat the University of Toronto and
win the title Monday for Sydney for the second time.
   Two U.S. teams, from Yale University and the University of
Pennsylvania, were eliminated in the semi-final round Monday
morning. A total of 116 teams of word wizards competed.
   Using a forcible debating style mixed with wit, the Australians
were the clear crowd favorite as Lee and Bell argued that modern
society reveres those who acquire wealth.
   University of Toronto team members Justin MacGregor and David
Conklin, acting as ``the government'' in the British parliamentary
style argument, had the task of proving that ``it profits a man
nothing to gain the world and lose his soul.''
   ``It was a good debate,'' Lee said after the Australians
finished. ``The masses were laughing and hooting and screaming. You
always like to see that.''
   Conklin admitted the subject ``was a tough one. Any value today
involving some notion of justice or injustice is difficult to get
across.''
   In the debate, Conklin argued that figures such as Jesus, Gandhi
and Martin Luther King Jr. shunned the material world for larger
social gains.
   ``Christ, in his death, was far more important than he would have
been had he compromised his values,'' Conklin said.
   MacGregor scored a few points by saying ``justice was served in
the movie `Wall Street.' Michael Douglas did go to jail in the end,
before he won his Academy Award.''
   But it wasn't enough to overcome the Australians' contention
``that the people who get the stuff are not punished, they get the
wealth, the respect, and the happiness.''
   Earlier in the day, the Australians defeated Yale University by
opposing the concept that ``the emperor has no clothes.''
   The University of Toronto advanced to the championship by
defeating the University of Pennsylvania with a successful argument
that the sky is not falling.
   The championship drew a record 232 participants from 18 nations.
   The debaters delivered some spirited arguments during the
week-long tournament.
   For example, Cheryl Strauss of Cornell University last week
suggested that vegetables be the focal point of a new religion.
   ``I think we should all pray to vegetables,'' she said. ``Then we
could all look down and that would make us feel good.''
   Mark Voyce of the University of Maryland had an offbeat response
Sunday when given the topic, ``How to Make Sports More Violent.''
   Voyce said archery should include human targets.
   ``Who wants to shoot an arrow into a bunch of hay?'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
