<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     01-10 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in early European trading
today but traders said the market appeared poised to test how high
central banks are willing to let the currency rise. Gold prices rose.
   Central banks in the United States, West Germany, Switzerland,
Austria and Canada all reportedly intervened in the market on Monday
to slow the dollar's climb.
   ``The intervention has run out of effect,'' said one trader in
Rome.
   ``Europe is clearly inclined to buy dollars for now and it is
waiting for the U.S. to open and see whether the Fed (U.S. Federal
Reserve) will intervene again,'' said another.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.39 yen to a closing 125.70. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 125.93 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8253 West German marks, up from 1.8245
   _1.5580 Swiss francs, up from 1.5555
   _6.2190 French francs, down from 6.2300
   _2.0589 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0575
   _1,338.50 Italian lire, down from 1,339.75
   _1.1995 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7695, slightly more
expensive for buyers than late Monday's $1.7650.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for
gold of $405.50 a troy ounce at midmorning today, unchanged from the
opening bid but higher than $402.75 bid late Monday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $405.25, up from $402.75 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 5 cents to close at a bid
$407.23.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.96 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.94.
</TEXT>
