<FIRST>r i PM-StrandedFamily     01-10 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stranded Family,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Family Stranded In Canada After Niagara Falls Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christmas Eve trip to Niagara
Falls is keeping a Cuban family from returning to the United States
until they can prove they have refugee status to live there.
   Carlos Fajardo Hernandez claims to have refugee status in the
United States and says he owns a home in Miami, but U.S. immigration
officials will not let the family into the country without
documentation.
   ``They have nothing to support their claim of being refugees,''
said Benedict Ferro, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Buffalo.
   Hernandez, his wife and two children have been forced to stay in
a motel in Niagara Falls for the past two weeks.
   ``The kids wanted to see the Christmas lights,'' Hernandez said
from his hotel room Monday night, explaining the family's visit to
the Canadian side at Niagara Falls.
   Ferro said immigration officials in Buffalo and Miami were
searching for information on the family. He said the family may have
been living in the U.S. illegally.
   Hernandez said he has a Florida driver's license and an
immigration document he described as a work permit.
   Hernandez; his wife, Bermaida Zamora-Powers; children Yoandys
Diaz-Zamora, 12, and Yordalys Diaz-Zamora, 9, have received
assistance from a Canadian refugee organization.
   Sister Kathleen Rimar, an immigration lawyer with the
organization, said she's asked U.S. officials to allow the family to
return ``because of humanitarian concerns.''
   ``I don't know what will happen to them if they aren't allow back
into the U.S.,'' Sister Rimar said.
   The family has no legal status in Canada.
</TEXT>
