<FIRST>r a PM-People-JamesBrown     01-10 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-James Brown,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Deluged With Requests for Visits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State corrections officials are being
deluged with requests to visit soul singer James Brown in prison.
But, like the busload of fans who showed up at the prison a week
ago, most have been turned away.
   ``It's not like a hospital, and it's not like some social camp,''
said Department of Corrections spokesman Francis Archibald.
   Brown, 55, is serving a six-year sentence for aggravated assault
and failing to stop for police during a wild, two-state chase last
September.
   Archibald said although dozens of news organizations have asked
to interview Brown since he entered prison Dec. 16, ``We are not
facilitating any interviews at this time.''
   Any reporters wishing to speak with Brown must write him a letter
asking him to call them collect, Archibald said. Brown, who works in
the kitchen of the 275-inmate, minimum-security State Park
Correctional Center near Columbia, is allowed to use the pay phones
in his dormitory whenever he isn't on the job.
   Inmates at the prison can have visitors on Saturdays and Sundays,
but they either must be family members or have their names included
on a list of no more than six people submitted by the inmate.
   Ministers can visit at other times, if they show prison officials
their credentials. ``There have been a couple of people who saw him
in their capacity as ministers,'' Archibald said.
</TEXT>
