and political reforms.
   Havel, who has frequently been harassed by authorities, said by
telephone from Prague that he was questioned for about two hours
Monday after he received an anonymous letter from an unknown
``Committee for Collective Suicide.''
   The letter contained a threat to emulate the suicide of student
Jan Palach on Prague's Wenceslas Square 20 years ago.
   Sunday's rally intends to commemorate Palach's deed. He burned
himself to protest the Soviet-led invasion a year earlier that
quashed a broad-based reform movement supported by then-Communist
leader Alexander Dubcek.
   Human rights activists say the rally will go on despite the ban.
   Havel taped an appeal that was broadcast by the Czech-language
services of Western radio stations Monday night urging the anonymous
committee not to go ahead with the action.
   He said police would today question Dana Nemcova, a spokeswoman
for the Charter 77 humanr rights group, who received an identical
letter, Havel said.
   Palach set himself ablaze Jan. 16, 1969 and died three days
later. Thousands of Czechoslovaks, shocked and moved by his protest,
attended his funeral.
   Havel said representatives of Charter 77 and four other groups
who have called the rally were to meet today with authorities to
discuss the event.
   On Jan. 21, the same five groups plan to hold a vigil at Palach's
grave in his home village of Vsetaty, 18 miles north of Prague.
   Palach's body was secretly exhumed from a Prague cemetery and
reburied in Vsetaty in 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
