<FIRST>r w PM-ScotusRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0436 01-10 1091</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Backer Promises ``Firestorm'' if Court Overturns Roe Vs.
Wade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with quotes from Michelman, Reynolds; picks
up 4th graf pvs, ``Women's lives.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reversal of the Supreme Court's 1973 decision
legalizing abortion would touch off political chaos and social
upheaval across the country, an abortion-rights leader said today.
   The justices said Monday they will study a federal appeals court
ruling that struck down key provisions of a Missouri law regulating
abortions.
   The court's eventual decision, expected by July, could resolve
the Missouri controversy without disturbing the 1973 decision. But
Missouri officials and Justice Department lawyers are urging the
justices to use the case to overturn the landmakr Roe vs. Wade
ruling.
   A reversal of that ruling would ``create political chaos and
social upheaval across this country,'' Kate Michelman, executive
director of the National Abortion Rights Action League, said on
``CBS This Morning.''
   ``There would be firestorms all across this country on the
question of abortion,'' she said. ``... We will mobilize this
country the likes of which you have not seen in a long, long time.
This country, women and men alike, will never accept going back to
the day when women have to risk their lives, their health, their
families' lives in order to seek an abortion.''
   William Bradford Reynolds, who as an assistant attorney general
pushed for a review of Roe vs. Wade, said on the CBS program that
``there is certainly good reason for optimism that the court is
going to differ with the lower court as far as some of the
strictions that have been placed in the Missouri statute on
abortion.''
   He added that he hopes ``it would go further and entertain the
whole question of Roe vs. Wade and reconsider it, and I would hope
that if it did that, it would come to a result that is
constitutionally sound and that we could correct the error that was
made some years ago in this area,'' he said.
   Reynolds maintained that the 1973 decision ``does not stand on
very firm constitutional footing.''
   ``Women's lives are literally on the line'' if the court reverses
its most famous abortion ruling, said Eleanor Smeal, president of
the Fund for the Feminist Majority.
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women,
added: ``We are now declaring a state of emergency for the women of
America.''
   Yard, speculating on a ``worst-case scenario,'' said, ``Women
will not accept an overturn. We will not go back to illegal
abortions. It's going to be like Prohibition. We aren't going to
obey the law.''
   Judith Sewderowitz, executive director of the Center for
Population Options, said her organization is ``deeply concerned that
the court may be preparing to repeal the right to abortion.''
   ``For adult women, retreat from the principles of Roe would be a
major setback,'' she said. ``For adolescents _ for whom too-early
childbearing poses the threat of physical and emotional harm _
retreat from Roe would be a disaster.''
   Eve Paul of Planned Parenthood said, ``We can't predict what the
Supreme Court will do but abortion has become a safe, legal
procedure which millions of women have had.''
   Mark Chopko, a lawyer for the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops, said he was ``cautiously optimistic that today's
development signals the beginning of the court's reconsideration of
Roe vs. Wade.''
   Samuel Lee of the anti-abortion Missouri Citizens for Life,
called the case acted on Monday ``our best shot in a number of years
to undo Roe, really our best shot since 1973 because of changes on
the court.''
   The court is viewed as deeply divided on abortion.
   Although Justices Harry A. Blackmun, William J. Brennan, Thurgood
Marshall and John Paul Stevens have resisted attempts to reverse or
greatly modify the 1973 decision, anti-abortion forces are hoping to
attract five votes for such a result.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Byron R. White
dissented from the 1973 ruling and from several subsequent abortion
decisions.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor in past decisions has questioned the
court's reasoning in its 1973 decision.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, who has not yet voted in an abortion
decision since being named to the high court by President Reagan in
1986, is thought to favor overturning or curtailing Roe vs. Wade.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who joined the court last Feb. 18,
likewise has not voted in an abortion decision. His views on
abortion and the Roe vs. Wade decision are not known in any
significant detail.
   ``We don't know what Kennedy is going to do,'' said the Missouri
anti-abortion group's Lee, ``but I'm more optimistic about him than
Planned Parenthood is.''
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last July struck down,
among other aspects of the Missouri abortion law, these five
provisions:
   _A ban on using public hospitals and other facilities for
abortions not necessary to save a woman's life.
   _A ban prohibiting any public employee from performing or
assisting in an abortion.
   _A ban on using taxpayer money for ``encouraging or counseling''
women to have abortions.
   _A requirement that doctors determine whether a fetus believed to
be older than 19 weeks is capable of surviving outside the womb by
testing for weight and lung capacity.
   _A declaration that ``the life of each human being begins at
conception.''
   Missouri Attorney General William L. Webster, in seeking Supreme
Court review, said the 1973 decision ``should itself be
reconsidered'' if it cannot be squared with the disputed Missouri
law.
   Reynolds, then chief of the Justice Department's civil rights
division, wrote to Missouri officials last summer urging them to
include a challenge of Roe vs. Wade in the state's appeal.
   And in a brief filed two days after the presidential election
Nov. 8, Justice Department lawyers supported Missouri's appeal.
   In its 1973 ruling, the Supreme Court said women have a
constitutional right to abortion, based on the right of privacy. The
court most recently reaffirmed that ruling in 1983, but the court's
membership has changed since then.
   In other action, the court:
   _Agreed to decide whether Congress may outlaw, as it tried to do
in a 1988 law, all sexually explicit telephone dial-up message
services, dubbed ``dial-a-porn.''
   _Let stand, over two dissenting votes, a lower court ruling in an
Alabama case that allows criminal defendants to exclude potential
jurors because of their race.
   _Refused to let the federal government permit Japanese salmon
fishermen off the Alaska coast to use huge nets in which porpoise
and other marine mammals become trapped.
</TEXT>
