<FIRST>r a PM-TornadoCleanup     01-10 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tornado Cleanup,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Towns Start Cleaning Up After Tornado</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIN1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. James R. Thompson has issued a
disaster declaration for four southeastern Illinois counties that
bore the brunt of damage from a tornado that tore through parts of
three states.
   In issuing the declaration Monday, the governor estimated damage
to a four-county area of Illinois at between $10 million and $15
million.
   The twister hit the towns of Mill Shoals, Albion and Allendale
late Saturday afternoon, destroying more than one-third of
Allendale, a town of 600 people near the Indiana border, and leaving
about 300 people homeless.
   It then moved into Indiana, touching down near Vincennes, and cut
a two-mile path through the southern Kentucky community of Franklin.
   No deaths were reported, although 50 people were injured in
Illinois and three in Indiana. Five people in Indiana remained
hospitalized in serious condition Monday.
   Thompson's declaration covered Edwards, Wabash, Wayne and White
counties. But the governor said he did not know whether the counties
qualified for a federal disaster declaration because the damage was
not spread over a large geographic area.
   The Illinois declaration allows local residents to seek property
tax reassessment and to apply for federal assistance.
   In Wabash County, which includes Allendale, the cleanup effort
continued Monday as bulldozers and farm tractors helped clear
debris. About 75 Illinois National Guard personnel and volunteers
from surrounding communities pitched in, and sunny skies aided the
recovery effort.
   ``Things are progressing very well,'' said Sheriff Randy Grounds.
   Grounds said partial water and gas service was available Monday,
but the area remained without electricity and telephone service was
unreliable. Officials set a 5 p.m. curfew to prevent looting.
   Local residents were trying to get over the shock of their
losses, Grounds said.
   ``I think spiritually, they're up,'' he said. ``They're thankful
they have a life.''
</TEXT>
