<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LACrime     01-10 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Crime,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murders In LA Down, But Gang Violence Up In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of murders hit a 10-year low in Los
Angeles last year, but the decline was overshadowed by a sharp rise
in gang-related killings, police said.
   Murders in the nation's second-largest city fell to 734 in 1988,
down from 832 in 1987 and the lowest since 1978, when there were 678
homicides, according to statistics released Monday.
   Gang-related killings escalated to 257 last year from 205 in
1987, while overall gang-related crimes rose to 5,371 from 5,129 the
year before.
   The Sheriff's Department also reported that gang-related slayings
in unincorporated areas of the county rose to 96 last year from 79
in 1987. The department has not completed overall homicide totals
yet.
   Police Cmdr. William Booth attributed the jump to a sharp rise in
the number of gang members. Last year, investigators listed nearly
28,000 known gang members compared with just 15,000 the year before.
   Booth credited the drop in murders overall to the addition of 900
extra street cops provided by extra overtime funds and a greater
willingness by officers to make arrests in domestic disputes.
   The Los Angeles murder rate of 22.9 killings for every 100,000
residents runs lower than that of many other large cities, Booth
said.
   Washington, D.C., lists 59.2 murders per 100,000 persons, the
highest in the country, followed by Detroit with 58 murders per
100,000 and Dallas with 56.7.
   ``In my own view,'' Booth said, ``Los Angeles is what it has been
all along, one of the safest major cities in the United States.''
</TEXT>
