<FIRST>r a PM-Crash-WrongBody     01-10 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash-Wrong Body,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families of Crash Victims Await Switch of Bodies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Pan Am Flight 103 victim Karen
Hunt has been identified as the one mistakenly shipped to a family
in Masschusetts, and the Massachusetts family is convinced the body
sent to Rochester is their daughter's.
   The fathers of Karen Hunt of Webster and Mary L. Johnson of
Wayland, Mass., also a victim of the crash, said Monday that
officials from the FBI and Scotland Yard have told them the two
women's bodies were flown to each other's hometown by mistake.
   ``Karen has definitely been identified,'' said Robert Hunt.
``We're extremely relieved. Hopefully, as soon as we get Karen back,
we can put this episode to rest.''
   Ms. Hunt's body is at the University of Massachusetts Medical
Center in Worcester; Ms. Johnson's is at the Monroe County medical
examiner's office. Each father said he hopes to receive the correct
body shortly.
   ``We're satisfied that she's our daughter,'' Johnson said. ``We
have no feelings at all of anger and bitterness about this. ... It's
one of those simple mistakes that can be made. It seems terrible at
the time, but it's not a big mistake.''
   The two women were among the 259 passengers and crew killed in
the Dec. 21 crash over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Ms. Hunt, who would have turned 21 Saturday, was one of 35
Syracuse University students participating in a study abroad program
who were killed in the crash. Ms. Johnson, 25, had been overseas 14
months when she boarded the plane in London.
   Officials in Rochester determined over the weekend that the body
sent there for burial was not Ms. Hunt's.
   The body reported to be Ms. Hunt's arrived Thursday in Rochester.
But Hunt had become concerned that it was not his daughter two days
earlier when Scottish authorities gave Ms. Hunt's aunt, Judy
Charest, a description in London of the clothing on the body.
   The description included slacks and a blouse unfamiliar to the
family and Ms. Hunt's three London roommates. Also on the body were
a scarf, silver bracelet and ring, items her family said Ms. Hunt
never wore.
   The Johnson family was an hour from burying Ms. Hunt's body in
North Cemetery in Wayland on Sunday when FBI agents arrived at their
home to tell them it was not the body of their daughter.
   How the mix-up occurred was not immediately explained.
   Gregory Jones, an FBI spokesman in Washington, said Scottish
authorities recovering bodies from the crash apparently identified
the bodies of Ms. Hunt and Ms. Johnson correctly but flew the
caskets to the wrong cities.
</TEXT>
