<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg     01-10 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pathologist Says Any Adult Could Have Killed Lisa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical pathologist, testifying for the defense
in the child abuse and murder trial of Joel Steinberg, said it
didn't appear that 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg was hit with full force
by a man Steinberg's size.
   Dr. John Plunkett of St. Paul, Minn., testified Monday that
Lisa's fatal injuries would have been more extensive if she had been
hit forcefully in the jaw and head by a man as large as Steinberg,
who is 6 feet tall and weighs 180 pounds.
   ``I would expect her jaw to be shattered,'' Plunkett said,
observing that Lisa's jaw was small and fragile and she still had
her baby teeth.
   The prosecution contends that Lisa was killed by blows from
Steinberg, and a medical expert for the prosecution had previously
said those blows had the force of a fall from a third-floor window.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with second-degree
murder in the girl's beating death. Steinberg obtained Lisa
illegally from an unwed Long Island teen-ager, and he and his
companion Hedda Nussbaum raised her as their own.
   Lisa was removed unconscious from their apartment Nov. 2, 1987.
She was hospitalized and died of a brain hemorrhage three days later.
   Steinberg has told police he did not hit the child, and his
lawyers are suggesting that Ms. Nussbaum could have struck the fatal
blow.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, a former children's book author and editor,
testified that Steinberg told her he hit Lisa the night she was
fatally injured. Ms. Nussbaum was initially charged along with
Steinberg, but the charges were later dropped after prosecutors
concluded that Steinberg had abused Ms. Nussbaum so severely she
couldn't have acted to save Lisa. She became a prosecution witness.
   In his testimony, Plunkett said he believed small bruises on
Lisa's left jaw and right forehead and an injury to the back of her
head were caused when she was vigorously shaken and thrown against a
wall.
   These ``injuries could have been inflicted by any adult'' strong
enough to pick up a 43-pound child, he said.
</TEXT>
