<FIRST>r w PM-MarineDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0508 01-10 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marine Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Cites Leadership Breakdown in Marine's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 6, No one, to CORRECT date from Sept. 30 to Aug. 31.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a 19-year-old Marine on a training
mission in California was the result of ``misfeasance'' and a
breakdown in leadership, according to a Marine Corps investigation.
   Lance Cpl. Jason J. Rother of Minneapolis probably died 24 hours
before the Marines began searching for him in the California Mojave
Desert last August, the report said. Rother was reported missing 40
hours after he was last seen, and his skeletal remains were found
Dec. 4 _ three months and three major searches later.
   ``The American people ... will not _ nor should they _ accept our
maiming and killing their sons and daughters in so-called training
`accidents.' Neither will I!'' wrote Marine Commandant Gen. Alfred
M. Gray in endorsing the investigative findings.
   ``Rother's death was not an accident ... (but was the result of)
misfeasance,'' Gray wrote.
   Rother had been posted alone as a nighttime guide on Aug. 30 for
trucks that were to carry Marines to a major training exercise.
   No one noticed that Rother didn't climb aboard any of the trucks
as they passed, and the next day platoon sergeants issued an ``all
present'' even though he hadn't been seen, the report said.
Colleagues finally noticed he was missing in late afternoon on Aug.
31, the report said.
   The investigation recommended disciplinary action against a
lieutenant colonel and a major in charge of the training exercise
and against squad, company and platoon leaders involved in the
incident.
   A recommendation is expected this week at Camp Lejeune, N.C., on
whether Lt. Allen Lawson, who was in charge of posting road guides
at the time, should face court-martial, administrative action or if
charges should be dropped. Lawson is accused of dereliction of duty
and willful disobedience of an order to post the road guides in
pairs and to provide a logistics officer with a list of Marines
assigned as road guides.
</TEXT>
