<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0534 01-10 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0534,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Troop Pullout Reportedly To Begin Within Weeks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS details at bottom. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz was
quoted as saying today that Soviet troops will begin withdrawing
from his country within weeks.
   The state news agency MTI quoted Grosz as telling the Japanese
newspaper Nihon Keizai Shimbun the pullout ``is to commence within
weeks.'' No date was given for the start of the pullout.
   The pullout was believed to be the first announced in connection
with a speech by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Dec. 7.
Gorbachev said in the speech at the United Nations that the Soviet
Union would withdraw about 50,000 troops from Hungary, East Germany
and Czechoslovakia over the next two years.
   Defense Minister Col.-Gen. Ferenc Karpati said in an interview
with Hungarian television that preparations for withdrawal of
``major military units,'' including an armored division, were
nearing completion.
   The Soviet Union has about 62,000 troops stationed in Hungary,
according to the Communist Party daily Nepszabadsag.
   ``The withdrawal covers major military units, including an
armored division, which is a major proportion of the armored units
stationed in Hungary,'' Karpati said.
   He said other airborne units also would be withdrawn. Most of the
Soviet trooops going home are stationed in western Hungary, he said.
   Asked whether there might one day be a full pullout of Soviet
troops, Karpati said that question should be discussed at
forthcoming East-West talks in Vienna on reducing conventional
forces in Europe.
   The 16 NATO and seven Warsaw Pact nations have virtually
completed a mandate for those new talks to begin, possibly as early
as next month.
   Karpati also said he hoped the Hungarian army could be trimmed
and defense spending curbed.
   Asked about a possible new law allowing alternative military
service, Karpati said this is ``on the agenda of action to be taken
in the first half of this year.''
   Poland is currently the only Soviet bloc country which allows an
alternative to compulsory service in the armed forces.
</TEXT>
