<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     01-10 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Beach Cleanup Proceeds as Canadians Fear for Otters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCEAN SHORES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Storms have continued to push an oil
spill from Washington state into British Columbia, prompting calls
by the Canadian government for compensation.
   Acting Canadian Environment Minister Lucien Bouchard said
meetings with U.S. officials to discuss compensation were planned
today in Washington, D.C.
   ``We will explore all possible avenues of compensation for
affected parties, including native communities whose source of food
and income have been jeopardized,'' Bouchard said.
   ``It is an acceptable principle that the polluter make
reparations,'' he added. ``It is commendable that the American firm
fully and quickly accepted its responsibility.''
   As many as 231,000 gallons of bunker oil are believed to have
spilled Dec. 22 when a tug ran into a barge it was towing in heavy
seas off Grays Harbor, Wash.
   Oil has come ashore as far south as Newport, Ore., but the worst
damage has been to wilderness beaches in Olympic National Park on
Washington's northern coast and to the west coast of Vancouver
Island, including parts of Canada's Pacific Rim National Park.
   Officials of Sause Bros. Ocean Towing Co. of Coos Bay, Ore.,
owner of the tug and barge, have said the company would pay for
cleanup in both countries.
   The most recently affected shoreline is near Nootka Sound on
Vancouver Island, about 160 miles north of Grays Harbor.
   Bouchard toured the area Monday with his British Columbia
counterpart, Bruce Strachan, and Canadian Fisheries Minister Tom
Siddon. They met later with local and federal officials, Indian
leaders and cleanup volunteers.
   In Washington state, stormy weather and high tides in recent days
have removed oil from some beaches and redeposited it on beaches
farther north, officials said.
   ``This rough weather is definitely causing some movement of the
oil,'' said Ron Holcomb, of the state Department of Ecology. ``We're
keeping an eye on the effect of that.''
   The weather was rainy and windy Monday for the third straight
day, with only a slight easing of conditions expected through
Wednesday.
   ``I can't tell you how long it's going to take to get all of (the
oil),'' Holcomb added.
   Susan Ewing, a spokeswoman for the state Department of Wildlife,
said crews hoped to finish cleaning Washington's southern beaches
within a few days.
   ``The crews are not being pulled out from the southern areas but
are making really good progress toward finishing it off,'' she said.
   Bird-cleaning operations will continue for at least a couple of
more weeks, she said.
   Ms. Ewing said 62 birds were cleaned Monday, with a backlog of
more than 1,300 awaiting a scrub. Only 12 live birds were brought to
the center Monday, while 111 were found dead on the beaches.
   About 4,950 birds are known to have died on the Washington coast,
the most from any oil spill in state history. An additional 1,000
birds have been found dead in British Columbia.
</TEXT>
