<HEAD>Concorde Returns To Heathrow With Mechanical Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways said one of its Concorde jets
flying from London to New York was forced to return to Heathrow
Airport today because of a mechanical problem with one of its four
engines.
   Flaps controlling the flow of air to the engine were not working
properly, meaning supersonic speed could not be achieved, an airline
spokesman said.
   ``There was therefore no point in continuing with the journey,''
said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The
captain returned to Heathrow and landed without any problems.''
   The plane had been airborne about 30 minutes, the spokesman said.
   Flight 001's 62 passengers, including pop star George Michael,
were transferred to another Concorde.
