<SECOND>PM-BRF--BART Manager,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Manager Sentenced For Accepting Kickbacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former transit system manager who said he
resented co-workers who earned more than his $69,000 salary has been
sentenced to five years in prison for accepting kickbacks on
maintenance contracts.
   Arnold J. Flores, 45, also was fined $40,000, ordered to repay
more than $16,000 to the Bay Area Rapid Transit system, and
sentenced to five years on probation after his prison term.
   Last September, Flores, of El Sobrante, pleaded guilty to
accepting about $16,400 in kickbacks over three years. The money was
paid by undercover FBI agents who posed as contractors.
   Flores, who resigned from his $69,000-a-year job as a BART
maintenance manager last summer, told U.S. District Judge Marilyn
Hall Patel that he took kickbacks out of revenge for receiving less
pay than other BART managers.
   ``I am ashamed of what I've done,'' Flores said. ``I've hurt
myself, my family and my community.''
   Patel however, told Flores their was no justification for his
actions.
   Prosecutor Charles Burch said Flores' claims of being underpaid
were unfounded.
