<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ParkSquatter     01-10 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Park Squatter,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>State To Seek Eviction Of Long-time Park Squatter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 71-year-old woman has vowed she will not
be moved from a ramshackle homestead she has lived in for nearly two
decades after her nearby home was razed to make way for a state park.
   The state finally wants to develop the 300-acre park on the shore
of Long Island Sound, but Doris Gagnon ignored a Monday deadline for
leaving the property where she lives in a camper and shacks that sit
among tall marsh grass about 100 feet from the shore.
   ``I'd like to see it a park, but I don't want to have suffered in
vain,'' Gagnon said, arguing that she deserves millions of dollars
in compensation for her ordeal. ``I want to show they can't do this
to an American citizen.''
   The state will begin eviction proceedings once officials in
Milford verify that Gagnon is not leaving, Assistant Attorney
General Grace Dodier said Monday. The process is expected to take up
to two months, officials said.
   Authorities served notice Nov. 28 that they wanted her out of
Silver Sands State Park. They gave her until Monday to leave, even
though the law required only eight days' notice, Dodier said.
   ``As much as we can empathize with her, the woman has no legal
right to be there,'' said Wanda Rickerby, a spokeswoman for the
Department of Environmental Protection, which plans to develop the
park property.
   The Milford health department filed a complaint with the state
after an inspection discovered bags of human sewage piled up behind
Gagnon's living quarters, said Charles Motes, chief of environmental
health.
   ``We all feel she would be better off elsewhere,'' Rickerby said.
   But Gagnon is adamant about staying.
   ``I'm not leaving, not until I get justice,'' she said.
   Chicken-wire fencing surrounds her property, which is also home
to five cats, three dogs, and about 50 chickens, geese and ducks.
   Gagnon said she has propane gas to heat her dilapidated 18-foot
camper, and that friends bring her water and let her shower at their
homes. She said she also has an electric generator.
   ``People are very good to me,'' she said, adding that she is able
to survive on Social Security payments.
   Gagnon's battle with the state began in the mid-1960s when
officials bought and demolished about 100 cottages to expand and
develop the fledgling park. Gagnon refused to sell, but a judge in
May 1969 ruled the state would be able to take her property through
eminent domain. Her beachfront cottage was demolished in 1971.
   Gagnon said she refused to accept a $15,000 payment for the
property. The money was disbursed by the state to satisfy two liens
in 1974, according to state records.
   Part of the beach at the park is used during the summer, but
there are still no permanent facilities at Silver Sands. Funding and
environmental problems held up development of the park, and it won't
be completed for at least three years, officials said.
</TEXT>
