<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     01-10 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed In Attack Blamed On Sinhalese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militants threw bombs and opened fire
on a car today in an attack that killed three people, including two
opposition candidates for next month's national elections, police
said.
   Police blamed the militant Sinhalese People's Liberation Front
for the attack at Waduwa, 20 miles south of the capital, Colombo.
   The victims were identified as Indrapala Abeyweera, secretary of
the Sri Lanka Freedom Party, and Wijeyalal Mendis, also a candidate
for the Feb. 15 polls. The third victim was a bodyguard identified
by police only as Martin.
   The killings came in the wake of a statement by President
Ranasinghe Premadasa saying he would allow emergency rule to lapse
next week.
   ``We have lived under emergency rule for now more than five
years. I feel that is enough for everybody,'' Premadasa told a group
of high-ranking government officials and lawmakers while outlining
an ambitious program to eliminate proverty on this Indian Ocean
island.
   The state of emergency, which expires Sunday, was imposed in May
1983 to curb violence between the Buddhist Sinhalese majority and
the predominantly Hindu Tamils. It has been extended by Parliament
every month since then.
   Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of the country's 16 million
people, claim discrimination by the Sinhalese, who make up 75
percent of the population and control the government. Militant
Tamils have been fighting six years for an independent nation, and
more than 8,500 people have died.
   The People's Liberation Front opposes an accord the government
signed that was aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency and vowed to
kill anyone who supported the government.
   The state of emergency gave police and soldiers broad powers to
arrest and detain a person for up to 90 days without charges,
dispose of bodies without inquests and raid homes without search
warrants.
   Premadasa said everyone imprisoned under the emergency will be
released and that some already have been freed.
   According to government officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, 574 political prisoners were released between Jan. 1-6.
   During his campaign for the Dec. 19 presidential election,
Premadasa said he would work to eliminate poverty and malnutrition.
   His anti-poverty program outlined today would allocate about $75
a month to each of the country's 7 million impoverished people, or
45 percent of the population. The average annual income in Sri Lanka
is about $360.
   Premadasa, who also holds the finance and planning portfolios,
did not explain how he will finance his program.
   In a bid to create harmony on this ethnically divided nation,
Premadasa offered cash incentives to government employees who are
bilingual.
   ``Everyone likes money. So we will pay more to those who speak
more than one language,'' said Premadasa, who speaks the two
official languages, Sinhalese and Tamil, in addition to English. He
did not say how much more a bilingual employee would earn.
   Premadasa served as prime minister for 11 years before he was
elected president last month. One of his two opponents, Sirmavo
Bandaranaike, has asked the Supreme Court to nullify the election,
alleging fraud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
