<FIRST>r a PM-Two-DayLegislator 2ndLd-Writethru a0525 01-10 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Two-Day Legislator, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0525,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker's Lot: Here One Day, Gone The Next</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The Republican...', to CORRECT that he chosen
by five county party chairmen, sted five Hancock County chairmen.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. LeRoy Ufkes' career in the Illinois
House is literally a case of here one day, gone the next.
   Ufkes took his seat in the House for the first time Monday. Today
is his last day.
   The Republican was chosen by five county GOP chairmen in their
western Illinois district to serve out the term of Rep. Kent Slater,
who resigned last month to become a judge. Republicans, who hold a
minority of state House seats, decided not to risk further weakening
their strength by leaving the seat vacant even for a short time.
   Ufkes was sworn in on Dec. 6, shortly after lawmakers concluded
their fall session. The session reconvened Monday to consider extra
spending proposals. The 85th General Assembly session and his tenure
were to end today.
   Democrat Bill Edley, elected in November to succeed Slater, takes
office Wednesday.
   Ufkes, an attorney and former assistant state attorney general,
will pocket nearly $6,000 of the $36,551-a-year legislative salary
for his work.
   ``It's a little different experience than what I have been used
to in the courthouse,'' he said. ``I knew what I was voting on.
That's the main problem, knowing what you're voting on.''
   In his first vote Monday, Ufkes supported a bill extending a
program to help poor people pay utility bills. His vote was hardly
crucial. The measure passed 114-0 vote.
   For his brief Springfield assignment, Ufkes retained Slater's
staff and office and accepted his predecessor's advice to ``just be
my own man.''
   ``I just said `Hi' to him, that's all,'' said Rep. Gene Hoffman,
a 22-year Republican veteran of the House. ``In two days you can't
do much. ... Well you might be able to do some damage, but I doubt
much.''
   Ufkes, a 20-year member of the Hancock County Republican Central
Committee, said the GOP county chairmen gave him no instructions on
how to vote.
   ``They just said they trusted me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
