<FIRST>r a PM-WilsonQuints     01-10 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wilson Quints,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Calls Quints `Beautiful'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billy and Mary Jo Wilson's church is signing up
volunteers to help them care for five new babies, but the couple
hasn't received many offers of material help for their quintuplets,
the new mother says.
   ``We hope we do, because it's hard enough to raise one child,''
Mrs. Wilson said Monday in her first news conference since the three
girls and two boys were born Thursday at Detroit's Sinai Hospital.
   Mrs. Wilson, 30, said she will go home from the hospital
Wednesday or Thursday but doctors tell her the babies can't come
home for about 10 weeks.
   She and her husband, 34, a truck repairman for General Motors,
will bring them home one or two at a time to give themselves and son
Brad, 2{, time to get used to a houseful of new arrivals, she said.
   Brad is expecting company, Mrs. Wilson said.
   ``You've told him that there are babies,'' she said, gesturing
toward her husband, ``but it's not going to sink in until they all
show up.''
   ``They're beautiful,'' she said.
   Mrs. Wilson, a GM reliability analyst, said she never thought of
reducing the number of babies to give the remaining ones a stronger
chance.
   Doctors raised the possibility of ``selective reduction'' after
four babies were detected about six weeks into Mrs. Wilson's
pregnancy and a fifth wachael, Shelby Nicole, Rebecca Irene and Elizabeth
Ashley Wilson.
   Mrs. Wilson took a fertilit drug that produces multiple births up
to 30 percent of the time. She had been hospitalized since Oct. 20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
