<FIRST>r i PM-Angola-Cuba     01-10 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-Cuba,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>First 450 Cuban Troops Leave Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first contingent of 450 Cuban troops
left Angola today, weeks before a deadline set by an accord aimed at
bringing peace to this nation and independence to Namibia.
   The departing troops are part of a group of 3,000 who must be out
of Angola by April 1.
   Their early departure was ``a goodwill gesture on the part of
Cuba and Angola,'' Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos told
25,000 people gathered to say farewell in Luanda's May 1 Square.
   ``The names of those Cubans who fell here will be engraved
forever in our hearts,'' dos Santos said.
   Men and women who survived the fighting marched single file to
strains of a military band between ranks of their Angolan comrades
into three waiting Cuban and Angolan planes.
   U.N. military observers oversaw the beginning of a resolution to
one of Africa's thorniest problems.
   South Africa, which has administered Namibia as South-West Africa
since capturing it from Germany in World War I, agreed to its
independence in return for a Cuban withdrawal from Angola.
   Under a Dec. 22 agreement signed in New York by Angola, Cuba and
South Africa, the Cubans, who first came to the aid of the Angolan
government in July, 1975, are to withdraw 3,000 of their estimated
50,000 troops by April 1.
   All the Cuban troops are to pull back north of the east-west
Benguela railroad by Nov. 1, in time for Namibian elections.
   Cuban Brig. Gen. Samuel C. Rodiles Planas, chief of staff of
Cuban forces in Angola, and Angolan Navy Chief Maj. Gen. Ciel Da
Concessao signed withdrawal agreements on the airport runway today,
then handed them to the chief U.N. observer, Brazilian Gen. Pericles
Ferreira Gomes.
   Norwegian Col. Arvid Geirulv, second in command of the 28-man
U.N. observer force in Angola, said another 1,000 Cubans would leave
the port of Luanda on a Soviet ship late today or Wednesday.
   By Jan. 15, 550 more Cubans will have left by air and another
1,000 by boat, he said.
   The remainder of the U.N.'s 70 military and 20 civilian observers
were to arrive in Angola by March 20.
   South African troops entered Angola in 1975 to support right-wing
rebels who also are backed by Washington.
   Pretoria withdrew its troops to Namibia Aug. 22 following a
decisive defeat by the Cubans in the southern garrison town of Cuito
Cuanavale.
   All but 1,500 South African soldiers are to leave Namibia by Nov.
1.
   Cuba's deputy minsiter of armed forces, Gen. Abelardo Colome
Ibarra, told the flag-waving crowd in May 1 Square, the ``real
authors of this agreement are the men and women who fought here and
destroyed the myth of South African superiority.''
   Cuba and Angola have given no death toll, but Western
intelligence sources estimate 5,000 Cubans died in Angola.
   Luanda has asked the United Nations to pay the estimated $800
million to ship the Cubans home.
</TEXT>
