<HEAD>Man Kills Wife, Self At Travel Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man walked into a downtown travel agency
where his wife worked, shot and killed her, then turned the handgun
on himself, police said.
   James Crowley shot his wife, Patricia, Monday night at her desk
at the Bangor Travel Agency as her horrified co-workers watched,
then shot himself, police Lt. Donald O'Halloran said.
   Mrs. Crowley, 33, was pronounced dead shortly after arrival at
Eastern Maine Medical Center, nursing supervisor Frances Booker
said. Crowley, 40, was dead at the scene, O'Halloran said.
   Police would release no other details about the murder-suicide.
Several travel agency employees present at the shooting refused to
answer reporters' questions Monday night.
   An official at Fleet Bank of Maine, which owns the agency,
described Mrs. Crowley as a well-liked, responsible employee. He
said she had been with the agency three years.
   ``She's just the kind of person you'd expect to find in a travel
agency _ outgoing and very helpful,'' bank spokesman Roland MacLeod
said.
   Delphine O'Brien, wife of travel agency manager Joseph O'Brien,
said her husband was unavailable for comment.
