<FIRST>r a PM-FightingHens     01-10 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fighting Hens,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Will Vote To Change Name Of Mascot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HENRYETTA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fighting Hens is no name for a
football team, say students at Henryetta High School who squawk at
the notion that female fowl can conjure up the right image for their
gridiron boys.
   On Wednesday, students will vote on a new name for their athletic
teams _ something that inspires a little more fear in opponents,
like ``Knights'' or ``Diamond Backs.'' A poll shows that four out of
five favor the change.
   ``Our male athletes object to being named for a female chicken,''
said Willie Wind, student body president. ``And it's redundant to
call the girls' teams Lady Hens.''
   The Hens have been around since the 1930s, when a newspaper
account of a game played in a downpour referred to the team as the
Mud Hens, Wind said. The ``Fighting'' was added later.
   Most alumni have opposed a change in the name, arguing that it
has become a tradition. But Wind said there has always been some
opposition to the mascot.
   ``This is something that has been discussed as long as I've been
in school here,'' said Wind, a senior. ``But there are a lot of
people in the community who didn't want the change.''
   The school mascot has received some national attention recently
because of the success of UCLA quarterback Troy Aikman, a 1984
graduate of Henryetta High who is expected to be a top National
Football League draft choice.
   But that doesn't mean that students are proud to be Hens. A poll
of senior high students conducted last month showed support for a
change in mascots by a 352-81 margin.
   Even if the vote favors a change, it's still possible that the
school board will veto it. The Fighting Hens say they'll cross that
road when they get to it.
   ``If that happens, we'd be disappointed,'' Wind said. ``But we
wouldn't give up. We'd keep working within the system for the
change.''
</TEXT>
