<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Deadline     01-10 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Deadline,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Decides Issue on Suing Government Employee in New York Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in an important decision for
anyone who sues a government employee over alleged civil rights
violations, today clarified how to determine the filing deadlines
for such lawsuits.
   By a 9-0 vote, the justices ruled that a man who says he was
unlawfully arrested and beaten by campus police at the State
University of New York in Albany did not wait too long to sue two
police officers.
   The ruling means Tom Ukure's lawsuit against Javan Owens and
Daniel G. Lessard over a Jan. 27, 1984, incident can proceed to
trial.
   The two police officers had sought a ruling that Ukure, who sued
22 months after his arrest, missed the appropriate filing deadline,
or ``statute of limitations.''
   Ukure's federal lawsuit is based on a much-used civil rights law
in which people whose rights have been violated can collect monetary
damages from government officials and employees.
   But in passing the 1870 civil rights law and in amending it
since, Congresss has never specified what statute of limitations to
impose.
   In a 1985 decision, the Supreme Court ruled that suits filed
under the civil rights law, most often referred to as Section 1983
because that is where it appears in the U.S. Code, must meet the
same deadline as personal injury suits filed in the same state.
   But some states have more than one deadline for personal injury
suits, depending on what type of wrongdoing is being alleged. The
court's 1985 decision, in a case called Wilson vs. Garcia, did not
clarify what deadline should govern in such cases.
   Writing for the court today, Justice Thurgood Marshall said that
in such multiple-deadline situations, a state's catch-all deadline
for personal injury cases should be used.
   In Ukure's case, that means New York's general three-year statute
of limitations for personal injury cases governs _ not the state's
one-year deadline for certain specified personal injuries as the two
police officers had argued.
   ``Our decision in Wilson promised an end to the confusion over
what statute of limitations to apply to Section 1983 actions; with
today's decision, we hope to fulfill Wilson's promise,'' Marshall
said.
   He noted that courts should resort to general filing deadlines
only when state law provides multiple deadlines for personal injury
suits and the general deadline ``embraces, either explicitly or by
judicial construction, unspecified personal injury actions.''
   The case is Owens vs. Okure, 87-56.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
