<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Recess 1stLd-Writethru a0558 01-10 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Recess, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0558,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Defendants' Rights Not Violated in South Carolina Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 19-23, In other action, with other cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today the rights of
criminal defendants are not violated when they are denied the
opportunity to confer with their lawyers during brief trial recesses.
   By a 6-3 vote, the justices upheld the murder, kidnapping and
criminal assault convictions of Donald Ray Perry of South Carolina.
   During a 15-minute trial recess while Perry was testifying, his
lawyer sought to speak to him to advise him about his rights during
cross-examination. But the judge refused to allow them to talk.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, in his opinion for the high court,
said, ``The federal Constitution does not compel every trial judge
to allow the defendant to consult with his lawyer while his
testimony is in progress if the judge decides that there is a good
reason to interrupt the trial for a few minutes.''
   The truth more likely may emerge if a defendant who has been
testifying and is about to undergo cross-examination is denied the
chance to talk to his attorney, Stevens said.
   ``Permitting a witness ... to consult with counsel after direct
examination but before cross-examination grants the witness an
opportunity to regroup and regain a poise and sense of strategy that
the unaided witness would not possess,'' he said.
   Stevens drew a distinction between Perry's case and one in 1976
in which the court ruled that a defendant's right to the assistance
of his lawyer was violated when he was barred from talking with the
lawyer during an overnight recess.
   ``The normal consultation between attorney and client that occurs
during an overnight recess would encompass matters that go beyond
the content of the defendant's own testimony ... such as the
availability of other witnesses, trial tactics or even the
possibility of negotiating a plea bargain,'' Stevens said.
   The Constitution guarantees a defendant will be allowed to talk
to his lawyer about such matters, Stevens said.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, in a dissenting opinion, said the
ruling is ``a lapse in this court's commitment to fundamental
fairness for criminal defendants.''
   Marshall said prosecution witnesses routinely are allowed to
confer with the prosecutor during brief recesses.
   Justices William J. Brennan and Harry A. Blackmun joined
Marshall's dissent.
   Perry was sentenced to life in prison in the killing of Mary
Heimberger, whose body was found on March 7, 1981, in a wooded area
in Richland County, S.C.
   Perry confessed to police that he shot the victim, but said it
was an accident.
   Ms. Heimberger had been raped, shot in both kneecaps and fatally
shot in the chest.
   Perry filed a federal court appeal in 1985 and a judge ruled that
his rights were violated when the trial judge refused to allow him
to talk to his lawyer.
   But the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the
conviction in 1987.
   The appeals court said there must be evidence that denying a
defendant the opportunity to confer with his attorney prejudiced the
case against the defendant.
   The Supreme Court did not adopt that reasoning today. Citing the
case of the overnight recess, Stevens said there are instances when
the defendant must be allowed to confer with his lawyer without any
proof of prejudice against the defendant. But brief recesses do not
qualify for that treatment, Stevens said.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Clarified how to determine the filing deadline for anyone who
sues a government employee over alleged civil rights violations.
   By a 9-0 vote, the justices ruled that a man who says he was
unlawfully arrested and beaten by campus police at the State
University of New York in Albany did not wait too long to sue two
police officers.
   _ Upheld a 5 percent tax Illinois imposes on all telephone calls
charged to in-state numbers.
   The court, in an opinion by Justice Thurgood Marshall, said the
tax does not interfere impermissibly with interstate commerce.
   The case involving criminal defendants is Perry vs. Leeke,
88-6325.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SeditionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0435 01-10 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sedition Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0435,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Of Avowed Revolutionaries Opens In Guarded Courtroom</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with opening arguments; pick up
7th graf pvs, `The defense ...'. SUBS 17th graf, `Manning's wife...', to
CORRECT time she pleaded guilty to last month sted this month.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three self-styled revolutionaries
plotted to bomb courthouses, military offices and corporations in an
attempt to overthrow the U.S. government, a prosecutor said today.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Loucks also told a federal jury
that the three defendants, plotted roberies from Maine to Virginia
and attempted to murder an off-duty policeman ``to further the
conspiracy's personal, political goals.'' They are accused of
seditious conspiracy, or conspiring to overthrow the government;
racketeering conspiracy; and racketeering enterprise.
   Loucks described the 1976 bombing of the Suffolk Superior
Courthouse in Boston, which blew down walls and injured several
people, as an attempt by the group ``to cripple the Massachusetts
penal system.''
   Opening arguments from defendant Raymond Luc Levasseur, 42, of
Maine, who is presenting his own case, and attorneys representing
Levasseur's wife, Patricia Gros Levasseur, 40, and Richard Williams,
41, of Boston, were to follow.
   Loucks maintained that Levasseur and his wife, who joined in
1976, were core members of the group that claimed credit for the
bombings under the names of the United Freedom Front and the Sam
Melville-Jonathan Jackson Unit, while Williams joined in 1981.
   About 50 spectators packed the tiny courtroom. At least 10 U.S.
marshals guarded the defendants and security was tight throughout
the courthouse.
   Attorneys estimate the trial could last a year.
   The defense attorneys say the seditious conspiracy statute is so
broad that it could be used against protesters blocking streets. It
was enacted in 1918 to keep draft resisters from interfering with
the conscription laws.
   ``What's at stake here is not just the rights of the people on
trial, it's the rights of every American,'' William Newman, who
represents Mrs. Levasseur, said Monday.
   The defendants have described themselves in a press release as
``North American anti-imperialists who believe armed resistance is
one of the necessary responses to apartheid, racism, sexism, the
massacres of Native Peoples and capitalist-backed wars.''
   They face up to 60 years in prison and $60,000 in fines if
convicted.
   Selection of a 12-member jury was completed Monday from a
prescreened pool of 45 prospective panelists after 68 days of
questioning that began in April but was delayed by pretrial motions
and wrangling over evidence.
   U.S. District Judge William G. Young reminded the jurors that it
was the prosecutors' responsibility to prove the defendants guilty
beyond a reasonable doubt.
   ``The government has to prove somebody actually did something to
make a conspiracy come about,'' he said. ``On no account can a
person be prosecuted for his political beliefs.''
   The courtroom is outfitted with closed-circuit television
monitors and guarded by about 40 marshals, who have set up two
walk-through metal detectors at the courthouse's entrances.
   The three defendants were among eight people who were arrested in
Ohio, Virginia and Massachusetts in 1982 and 1984. The trial was
moved from Boston to Springfield.
   Charges were dropped in August against two defendants _ Thomas W.
Manning, 42, of Maine, and Jaan Karl Laaman, 40, of East Boston _
because they were already serving long sentences on bombing
convictions in New York.
   Manning's wife, Carol, 33, pleaded guilty last month to the three
charges and was sentenced to a five-year prison term to run
concurrent with her 15-year term in New York on bombing and
conspiracy charges.
   Young decided last week to hold a separate trial for Laaman's
wife, Barbara J. Curzi-Laaman, 31.
   Another defendant, Christopher King, 38, has been tried
separately and found guilty on the single count of seditious
conspiracy. He was sentenced to seven years in prison.
</TEXT>
