<FIRST>u a PM-TeamstersTrial     01-10 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Trial,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teamsters Trial Drawing To A Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government began closing arguments today in
its case against top Teamsters officials, describing for jurors how
the union's late president and two associates allegedly carried out
a $700,000 embezzlement scheme.
   The case was expected to go to the jury late today or Tuesday
following closing arguments by defense attorneys for the two
surviving defendants and instructions by U.S. District Court Judge
George M. White.
   The embezzlement and labor racketeering trial began 2{ months ago
and included testimony from 80 witnesses, many of whom were asked
detailed questions about day-to-day union operations as long as 10
years ago.
   The indictment, issued in May 1986, named the Teamsters
then-president, Jackie Presser, along with Harold Friedman, an
international vice president for the union, and Anthony Hughes,
Local 507 recording secretary.
   Presser died July 9 of brain cancer.
   ``The evidence demonstrates abuse of union office by Harold
Friedman, Anthony Hughes and Jackie Presser for the benefit of their
friends and cronies in the amount of $700,000,'' government
prosecutor Stephen Jigger said during closing arguments today.
   Jigger reviewed in detail the testimony of three of the alleged
``ghost employees,'' who allegedly were paid for doing no work. They
are Allen Friedman, who is not related to Harold Friedman; George
Argie; and John A. Nardi Jr.
   ``We told you up front that these three were unsavory characters,
but it was not the government that paid them up to $1,000 a week,''
Jigger said.
   Friedman, 66, and Presser, who was 61 when he died, were accused
of paying the ``ghosts,'' while Hughes, 52, was charged with being a
no-show employee at the Bakery Workers' Local 19, which is
affiliated with Teamsters Local 507.
   Friedman testified that Hughes worked and that Allen Friedman
often was too ill to work. He said the other two ``ghost employees''
worked for Presser and that it would have been uncharacteristic of
Presser to pay people for doing no work.
   ``Jackie Presser was not the type to pay someone ... and not have
him do any work,'' Friedman said last week. ``If he did, then shame
on Jackie Presser.''
   Court documents have indicated that Presser and Hughes were FBI
informants. Presser's former attorney, John R. Climaco, has said
that resser's defense would have been that the FBI authorized him to
hire the ``ghost employees'' to enhance and protect his status as an
FBI informant status.
   But government prosecutors contend Presser didn't begin working
as an FBI informant until 1977, so he couldn't have been authorized
to hire ``ghost employees'' as early as 1972, when the scheme
allegedly began.
   Friedman's attorney said last week that Presser was a government
informant as early as 1963.
</TEXT>
