<FIRST>r w AM-Carlucci-ASAT     01-10 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carlucci-ASAT,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Anti-Satellite Program Is Crucial To National Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said
Tuesday he approved requests for several anti-satellite projects in
the fiscal 1990 budget because such a weapon is crucial to national
security.
   ``I think it's deplorable that we do not have an anti-satellite
deterrent capability,'' Carlucci said.
   ``The Soviets have an operational system and contrary to some
reports I've read, it is an effective system. I think our lack of an
ASAT (anti-satellite) capability is our single most vulnerable point
if there were to be a conflict.
   ``For us to be deprived of our eyes and ears would gravely weaken
our military capability.''
   According to Carlucci and other Reagan administration leaders,
the Soviets have a crude but operational missile system for
attacking the low-flying U.S. spy and reconnaissance satellites that
would be crucial in a war.
   The United States spent years developing such a weapon _ and
tested it effectively once against an object in space _ before
Congress blocked further development work.
   Congressional Democrats maintain the current Soviet system poses
little danger to modern American satellites, note the Soviets have
stopped all testing of the weapon, and argue that further
development of an American counterpart would set off an arms race in
space.
   Carlucci was asked about anti-satellite work during a breakfast
meeting with Pentagon correspondents Tuesday, one day after the
Reagan administration sent a $315.2 billion military budget request
for fiscal 1990 to Congress.
   Included is a request for $94.6 million to begin development of a
sea-based anti-satellite weapon. The request was surprising, because
it was Carlucci who just last year bowed to the congressional
demands to halt development of an ASAT missile that could be fired
from land-based jets.
   ``That does not mean that I was prepared to give up on developing
an ASAT capability,'' Carlucci said of his decision to scuttle that
Air Force program.
   ``I think it's vitally important that we go ahead with some ASAT
capability. And we have a number of supporters in the Congress.''
   The defense secretary added the Navy effort would be one of at
least three programs to study ASAT applications. The Army and
Strategic Defense Initiative Organization, which oversees ``Star
Wars'' work, also are studying ASAT applications with different
types of lasers, Carlucci said.
   The Navy program will study the potential of a kinetic energy
ASAT missile _ or one that would destroy a satellite through impact
and not explosives.
   On other matters, Carlucci said he had spoken with his designated
successor, former Sen. John Tower of Texas, on Monday and that Tower
expected to recover rapidly from recent surgery.
   Carlucci said Tower now expects to undergo a Senate hearing and
gain confirmation by the end of the month. As a result, Carlucci
said he planned to step down from office on Feb. 1 and seek a job in
the private sector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
