<DOCNO> AP890110-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Press     01-10 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Press,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Against Legalizing Independent Journalists Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it opposes
legalizing a group of independent journalists who reject the
government-backed professional organization set up after the 1981
martial-law crackdown.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said a final decision on whether
to legalize the Association of Polish Journalists will be made by
city administrators in Warsaw, but the central government takes a
firm ``political position'' against it.
   In practice, Urban's statement appeared to doom the application,
drafted at a meeting over the weekend, for the legal revival of the
journalists' association dissolved seven years ago.
   The government is ``decisively against organizational divisions
of the journalistic community by political directions. We speak for
maintaining one professional organization ... gathering people of
various views,'' Urban said at his weekly news conference.
   He said the government especially opposes legalizing this group
because its leaders ``collaborate with Radio Free Europe'' _ the
U.S.-financed radio station that broadcasts uncensored news to
Eastern Europe.
   Asked how the stance could be reconciled with government promises
of greater freedom of association under legislation being drafted
for the parliament, Urban said that ``obviously'' any new bill will
retain ``restrictions of a political kind.''
   The Association of Polish Journalists, with about 7,600 members,
was dissolved in 1982 because its leadership was considered
pro-Solidarity. It was replaced by an ``Association of Journalists
of the Polish People's Republic'' that supported martial law.
   Urban said the new association has 8,700 members, about 80
percent of whom were in the old group. He said 90 percent of Polish
journalists are members.
   Many journalists who refused to join the organization lost jobs
in the state-run press or were shunted aside to obscure publications
during a ``verification'' of political views that followed the
martial-law crackdown. The new organization accepted the
verification campaign.
   About 300 press and broadcast journalists gathered for the
two-day meeting in Warsaw over the weekend and voted to ask for
registration of their old association.
   With the former association's chairman, Stefan Bratkowski,
presiding at the meeting, they said that recent government promises
of political pluralism and reform made it seem the right time to
seek reinstatement.
   While announcing the position, Urban defended the government's
record on the press.
   ``The freedom of expression of various views in Poland has
recently been very broad and is still expanding,'' he said.
``Journalists of opposition character have broader and broader
opportunities for work.''
   Dariusz Fikus, deputy chairman of the Polish Journalists
Association when it was dissolved, said he was disappointed by the
government stance.
   ``I think it is pure nonsense,'' he said. ``If Mr. Urban treats
pluralism in the Polish press seriously and agrees that various
orientations exist ... Why can't there be two journalists'
organizations?''
   He said that the application for reinstatment of the organization
was still being prepared and would be filed ``in the next few days.''
   In a related development, Urban at his news conference said there
was a possibility for future legalization of a banned students'
group, the Independent Students Association.
   Members of the group, which existed legally before martial law,
came to a meeting of young people at Communist Party headquarters
Friday and were thanked by a top party official for offering
criticisms of official policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0118 </DOCNO>
