<FIRST>r a AM-RestaurantShooting     01-10 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Restaurant Shooting,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Report Shows Gunman Killed Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose rampage at a restaurant
left three people dead and two officers wounded died of a
self-inflicted gunshot wound during the incident, police said
Tuesday in a preliminary report.
   Wayne Strozzi, 35, of Loveland shot himself in the head with a
pistol the night of Jan. 3, ending a one-hour standoff at the
Riverhouse Restaurant, Police Chief Bruce Glasscock said.
   The episode began as a domestic dispute between Strozzi and his
estranged wife at her home. He ran to his home after police were
summoned, and shot and wounded a sheriff's deputy there before going
to the Riverhouse Restaurant, where he took 15 people hostage.
   Strozzi wounded a police officer in the restaurant parking lot
before the shootings that left him and two other people dead.
   Glasscock said the preliminary police report showed Strozzi had
announced he would begin killing hostages in the restaurant at 9
p.m. Two minutes before that, a police sharpshooter opened fire on
Strozzi, wounding him, according to the report.
   The report said Strozzi fell to the floor and deliberately shot
waitress Sally Mills, 40, killing her, then placed his pistol to his
head and shot himself.
   The third person killed in the incident was Fenton Crookshank,
45, a restaurant customer who was shot four times by a Loveland
police officer after he went out a restaurant window and failed to
heed orders to stop.
   A preliminary police investigation has ruled Crookshank's
shooting was justified. The prosecutor's office will make a final
ruling on the whether the shooting was justified, with its findings
expected in about two weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
