<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Falklands-Ferry     01-10 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Falklands-Ferry,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentina Opposes First Falklands-South America Ferry Since War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANLEY, Falkland Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina is opposing efforts to
launch the first ferry service between the Falkland Islands and
South America since the 1982 Anglo-Argentine war, shipping sources
say.
   The 777-ton Indiana I is in Stanley harbor awaiting word on
whether a planned Thursday sailing to Montevideo, Uruguay and Punta
Arenas, Chile, will go ahead, according to the sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Several island businessmen have booked passages.
   It would take 3{ days to sail to Montevideo and two days to sail
to Punta. It offers big freight savings over the present trade route
to Britain 8,000 miles away. For example, a prefabricated three-room
bungalow imported from Britain costs $52,000, compared with $21,000
from Uruguay.
   Argentina opposes the venture because it claims sovereignty over
the British colony it calls the Malvinas. Uruguay and Chile
reportedly support Argentina.
   The Nassau-registered Indiana I has a British crew and flies the
Bahamian flag. It is owned by a consortium including British,
Japanese, French and Taiwanese fishing companies.
   Argentinian troops overran the islands March 1982 and were driven
out by British soldiers in a 74-day war.
</TEXT>
