<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     01-10 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,180</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Tuesday by the Supreme Court.
   
   CRIMINAL DEFENDANTS
   
   The court ruled the rights of criminal defendants are not
violated when they are denied the opportunity to confer with their
lawyers during brief trial recesses.
   By a 6-3 vote, the justices upheld the murder, kidnapping and
criminal assault convictions of Donald Ray Perry of South Carolina.
   During a 15-minute trial recess while Perry was testifying, his
lawyer sought to speak to him to advise him about his rights during
cross-examination. But the judge refused to allow them to talk.
   The case is Perry vs. Leeke, 88-6325.
   
   FILING DEADLINES
   
   The court clarified how to determine the filing deadline for
anyone who sues a government employee over alleged civil rights
violations.
   By a 9-0 vote, the justices ruled that a man who says he was
unlawfully arrested and beaten by campus police at the State
University of New York in Albany did not wait too long to sue two
police officers.
   The case is Owens vs. Okure, 87-56.
   
   PHONE TAX
   
   The court upheld a 5 percent tax Illinois imposes on all
telephone calls charged to in-state numbers.
   The court, in an opinion by Justice Thurgood Marshall, said the
tax does not interfere impermissibly with interstate commerce.
   The case is Goldberg vs. Sweet, 87-826.
</TEXT>
