<HEAD>Iran Says Big Drugs Ring Smashed, 46 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian authorities smashed a major drugs
and arms smuggling ring in southeastern Kerman province and arrested
46 people, Tehran Radio reported Tuesday.
   Gang leaders were among those arrested in the operation, which
also netted an an arms cache and 30 stolen vehicles, said the
broadcast, which was monitored in Nicosia.
   It did not say whether any narcotics were seized, but reported
gang members admitted they had smuggled 52 tons of opium into Iran
from neighboring Pakistan.
   Tehran Radio quoted a spokesman for the revolutionary committee
that is the region's main law enforcement agency as saying the gang
operated a network stretching from the southern gulf states to
Pakistan.
   The raid was part of a burgeoning nationwide crackdown that
includes new laws giving mandatory death sentences to drug smugglers
and people caught with more than an ounce of narcotics.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
has reported more than 900 people were arrested last month on
narcotics charges and 19 drug smugglers convicted by Islamic courts
were hanged in Tehran and other cities in two days last week.
