<SECOND>AM-BRF--Macao,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Crowd Lines Up For Illegal Immigrant Amnesty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACAO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20,000 parents and their children lined up
outside Macao's security police headquarters Tuesday after the
government announced an amnesty for children living illegally in
this Portuguese territory.
   Security Force Commander Col. Proenca de Almedia announced Monday
the amnesty covers children under 18 years whose parents have a
Macao identity card or who were born in this tiny south China
enclave.
   Police said the turnout surprised them as an official survey last
year indicated there were only 3,500 illegal child immigrants at
Macao schools. Many were smuggled in by illegal Chinese immigrant
parents.
   Police said they will open a new registration center Wednesday,
the last day of the amnesty, to process the large numbers.
   They also said they detained Chinese school principal Dr. Wun
Kin-wah on charges of selling school ID cards to people not
attending his school so they could register under the amnesty.
Thirty parents and students also were arrested.
   Macao, the oldest European settlement in Asia, has a population
of 450,000 and will revert to Chinese sovereignty in 1999.
</TEXT>
