<DOCNO> AP890110-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   01-10 0916</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets May Not Complete Afghan Withdrawal Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's top envoy to Afghanistan said Tuesday
there is ``serious danger'' the Soviets won't resume their troop
pullout in time to meet a Feb. 15 deadline for a total Red Army
withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   The statement from Yuli M. Vorontsov was the plainest yet from a
Soviet official that the Kremlin may delay or freeze its military
withdrawal from Afghanistan, which by U.N.-brokered accord is to be
completed by the middle of next month.
   However, it was not clear whether Vorontsov's comments to
Moscow-based reporters signaled a change in Soviet intent, or were
designed to pressure Moslem guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's
Moscow-backed government to accede to peace proposals floated by the
Kremlin, including talks between the insurgents and the government
of President Najib.
   The Soviets announced last fall they had completed the first half
of the withdrawal of their more than 100,000 soldiers from
Afghanistan. They have not yet announced when the pullout of the
remaining 50,000 troops would begin.
   Five weeks from a U.N.-set deadline that the Soviet Union agreed
in April to observe, Vorontsov said it was still ``too early to talk
about the schedule.''
   Asked if the Soviets might delay or suspend the pullout of the
remaining troops, Vorontsov, who is also Soviet first deputy foreign
minister, said: ``It's a serious danger. Things might shape up in
such a way that the Soviet Union will be unable to do what, in
principle, we've decided to do.''
   The diplomat blamed the continuation of hostilities in
Afghanistan on ``die-hard elements'' among the resistance and
continued military support from the United States.
   ``We don't see from the United States any indication of its
genuine desire to work for an Afghan settlement,'' Vorontsov told
the government news briefing. ``U.S. arms continue to be shipped to
(guerrillas in) Afghanistan.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the U.S.
administration expects the Soviets to hold to the Feb. 15 pullout
date.
   ``We still expect them to meet the deadline,'' Fitzwater said.
``I don't believe we've had any official notification to the
contrary.... The last thing they officially told us was that they
would be out.''
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said the Soviets had
taken preparatory steps a few days ago to resume a troop withdrawal.
   ``I am not going to go into specifics in terms of what that means
in actual units or of people crossing borders, other than to say we
have indications that it has resumed,'' he said. ``There certainly
is no reason they cannot be out by Feb. 15.''
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, in Stockholm,
Sweden, said he was sure the Soviet Union would pull all of its
troops out in time to meet the U.N.-arranged deadline.
   As well as brandishing the threat of a continued Soviet military
presence in Afghanistan, Vorontsov used his appearance before Moscow
reporters to make political overtures to the guerrillas, saying his
talks last week with Afghan opposition figures in Pakistan and Iran
convinced him a political settlement to Afghanistan's 10-year-old
civil war is possible.
   ``The main issue now is the formation by the Afghans themselves
of a broad-based government where all opposing groups and basic
political forces of the country would be represented,'' Vorontsov
said. ``This is something that's quite logical, and this is a
conclusion that those who are directly involved are coming very
close to now.''
   Guerrilla leaders, who ended talks in Pakistan with Vorontsov on
Saturday, refused Monday to resume direct talks with the Soviet
Union, contending the Kremlin was trying to secure a place for its
communist allies in a postwar government.
   ``Because the Soviets use threats, look for war rather than
peace, and disrespect Afghans' right of self-determination, we
believe that negotiations are unproductive and unnecessary,'' said
Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, a spokesman for the U.S.-backed guerrillas
based in Pakistan.
   Mojaddidi said the Soviets were trying ``to impose a government
of their choice'' on Afghans, and said the Soviets threatened to
supply Najib's government with new weapons if their terms were not
accepted.
   Vorontsov said the Kremlin is seeking the formation of a national
Afghan assembly, called a jurgah, to represent all parties in the
country. He indicated Moscow will continue to insist on inclusion of
Najib's government and People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan in
the assembly.
   ``If it just brings together the Alliance of Seven, the Alliance
of Eight, or some new Alliance of 15, then there could be no use
that could be derived from that council,'' Vorontsov said, referring
to various coalitions of Afghan insurgent factions.
   He said the Soviets had not received a reply from Afghan
insurgents about the creation of a national assembly, but added, ``I
think they have understood that it's only diehard fanatics who
proclaim their wish and intention to continue the bloodletting....
we keep the door to negotiations open.''
   Vorontsov said that since Jan. 1, Soviet troops had joined Afghan
government forces in a cease-fire, and ``will not fire unless
attacked by the armed opposition.''
   Mojaddidi on Monday ruled out participation by the guerrillas in
the cease-fire, which had been sought by Vorontsov, but said they
would not attack departing Soviet soldiers.
   The Soviets intervened military in Afghanistan in December 1979
to prop up its battle-weary communists with more than 100,000 Red
Army troops. But in April 1988, after U.N.-sponsored talks in
Geneva, the Kremlin agreed to bring all its troops home by
mid-February 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
