<SECOND>PM-Espionage Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0612,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Naval Officer Arrested on Espionage Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, Steinmetz said, with more
details of the arrest. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Kunkle, a. ^By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Navy chief petty officer was arrested
today on charges he tried to sell highly classified information
about anti-submarine warfare tactics to the Soviet Union, the FBI
said.
   Craig D. Kunkle, 39, of Virginia Beach, Va., was arrested by FBI
agents from the Norfolk, Va., field office on charges of espionage,
gathering or delivering classified information to a foreign
government and disclosure of classified information, said FBI
spokesman Charles W. Steinmetz.
   Steinmetz said the arrest resulted from an undercover
investigation by the FBI and the Naval Investigative Service that
began last month. ``We did stop him from providing the information''
to the Soviets, he said.
   The suspect was arrested while trying to sell classified
information to an undercover agent posing as a Soviet spy, according
to a source familiar with the case.
   The investigation was triggered when the suspect telephoned the
Soviet Embassy in Washington with an offer to pass along secret
information, said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Telephone calls to the Soviet Embassy are routinly monitored by
U.S. counterintelligence agencies.
   Kunkle, a 12-year veteran of the Navy who was discharged in 1985,
could be given a life sentence if convicted.
   A private investigator and security guard in the Norfolk area,
Kunkle had served in anti-submarine squadrons in the Pacific and
Atlantic fleets during his Navy career, Steinmetz said. Kunkle held
a secret clearance, the spokesman said.
   Kunkle's activities were unrelated to the Norfolk-area spy ring
spearheaded by former naval officer John Walker, who is serving a
life sentence for selling valuable Navy secrets to the Soviets,
Steinmetz said.
</TEXT>
