<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TiresShredded     01-10 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tires Shredded,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Million Tires Shredded In War on Mosquitos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since June, a million tires have been
shredded and hauled away from a tire dump here. The shredding ends
this week, completing destruction of a major mosquito breeding
ground.
   The tires had been home to the dreaded Asian Tiger mosquitoes,
which were thought to have been imported from Asia inside used tires
brought to Jacksonville for recapping.
   Mayor Tommy Hazouri tossed a ceremonial last tire in the shredder
Monday, although 3,000 to 4,000 still remain to be shredded. The
work is being done by the Oxford Tire Co. of Buffalo, N.Y.
   ``I'm extremely happy to see that our city has taken the
necessary steps to eliminate a serious health and fire hazard. It's
wonderful to see this 12-acre site become usable land again,''
Hazouri said.
   Night foreman Norm Park said the work would be finished by
Wednesday, and grass will be planted on the site later this week.
The site was called the Frasier Tire dump after the retreading
company that first began dumping unusable tires there.
   Ann Shorstein, an aide to Hazouri, said she is optimistic the
city will be able to recoup the $538,000 it paid for the project
through a new exise tax on tires. The law, which took effect Jan. 1,
adds 50 cents to the price of a new tire this year and $1 next year.
   Workers at the Frasier Tire dump had been shredding since June
21, six days a week, up to 20 hours a day.
   The shredded tire chips, about the size of charcoal briquets, are
sold by Oxford to a Greek firm, Titan Cement Co., which uses the
rubber for industrial fuel in a cement plant in Athens.
   Oxford hired an entomologist to ensure that neither the
mosquitoes nor their eggs could survive the shredding.
   The Asian mosquitoes are more aggressive than native mosquitoes
and can withstand lower temperatures, officials said. They also have
been known to carry dengue fever, which in rare cases can be fatal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Upside-DownTree     01-10 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Upside-Down Tree,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia O'Keeffe's Tree Turns Topsy-Turvy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exhibition planners went out on a limb in
hanging a familiar painting by Georgia O'Keeffe upside-down from
what her fans are used to, but a curator says that was what the
artist wanted.
   At the Wadsworth Atheneum, which owns the 1929 painting ``The
Lawrence Tree,'' the work was hung with the tree extending from the
lower right-hand corner of the canvas. The painting depicts a
ponderosa pine O'Keeffe encountered on D.H. Lawrence's Taos, N.M.,
ranch.
   But since the painting has been part of a traveling retrospective
of O'Keeffe's work organized by the National Gallery of Art in
Washington, D.C., it has been hung with the base of the tree at the
top left corner.
   The position was changed because of a 1930 photograph and a 1931
letter by the artist that were made available to exhibition planners
by O'Keeffe's longtime companion and the manager of her estate, said
Elizabeth Kornhauser, the Wadsworth's curator of American painting,
sculpture and drawing.
   When O'Keeffe sold the painting to the Wadsworth, ``she indicated
to us that it could be hung in any direction,'' Kornhauser said
Tuesday. ``Of course, you have to keep in mind that ... a lot of
time had elapsed betwen 1929 and 1979, when we bought the painting.''
   The artist died in 1986 at age 98.
   However, the new evidence shows the artist cared very much about
the position at the time she did the work.
   A photograph of a 1930 exhibit of the painting hung by O'Keeffe
herself shows the tree with its trunk extending from the top. Also,
in a letter from O'Keeffe to a friend written in 1931, she
complained that in a later exhibition the work was hung the opposite
way and that was not what she had in mind.
   When the painting was first exhibited in the new-old position at
the National Gallery, ``there was quite a big outcry,'' Kornhauser
said.
   ``People do know the picture and have gotten used to it the other
way,'' said Katie Ziglar, the National Gallery's public information
specialist. ``They blinked and said, `What's this?'''
   Kornhauser said she is convinced that the retrospective is
correct in the way it is displaying the painting, and the atheneum
will follow suit when the painting is returned later this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
