<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His fans thought James Brown might be a
captive audience. But they've found imprisonment hasn't much
improved their odds of seeing the ``Godfather of Soul.''
   Officials say they have turned away many requests to visit Brown
in prison. ``It's not like a hospital, and it's not like some social
camp,'' said Department of Corrections spokesman Francis Archibald.
A busload of fans was turned away last week.
   Brown, 55, is serving a six-year sentence for aggravated assault
and failing to stop for police during a two-state chase last
September.
   Brown, who works in the kitchen of the 275-inmate,
minimum-security State Park Correctional Center near Columbia, is
allowed to use the pay phones in his dormitory when he isn't working.
   And inmates can have visitors on weekends, but they either must
be relatives or have their names included on a list of no more than
six people submitted by the inmate. Ministers can visit at other
times.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. soprano Carol Vaness finally got to sing in
``Die Fledermaus'' from start to finish at the Royal Opera House.
   ``I've sung all the famous bits before but this was the first
time I had to put them together,'' she said after plaudits Monday
from a crowded house for her Rosalinde in the first Covent Garden
production of the new year.
   ``I was surprised it got moving so well because there's so much
talking in it, but there's a lot of care in this opera house,'' she
said in a dressing-room interview.
   The production has an English libretto, rewritten with wit and
topical jokes about Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and glasnost by
John Mortimer, who adapted for television Evelyn Waugh's
``Brideshead Revisited'' and his own ``Rumpole of the Bailey.''
   Ms. Vaness, who lives in New York but regards Los Angeles as her
hometown, is the only foreigner in the cast. She said she tried a
British accent.
   ``But the producer shouted at me, `No, no.' He said I sounded
like a cross between Batman and Mae West. So I went original and was
just myself _ no problems. Everyone seemed to enjoy it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock and soul duo Hall and Oates and child
television star Fred Savage will be grand marshals of one of New
Orleans' major Carnival parades, the annual procession of the Krewe
of Endymion on Feb. 4.
   Daryl Hall and John Oates will perform at the krewe's annual
party in the Louisiana Superdome following their ride in the parade
float.
   Savage will be the latest of several young television stars to be
featured in the parades. He plays Kevin Arnold in ``Wonder Years,''
ABC's comedy about growing up in the 1960s.
   Endymion is one of the splashiest _ and longest _ of the more
than 50 parades during the days leading up to Mardi Gras. Mardi
Gras, or Fat Tuesday, falls this year on Feb. 7.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar was awarded the Olof Palme Prize for public service Tuesday,
and said he would set up a scholarship for peacemakers with the
$16,000 prize.
   Perez de Cuellar accepted the award from Lisbet Palme, widow of
the four-term Swedish prime minister and U.N. mediator who was
assassinated nearly three years ago.
   The U.N. chief said the award would go toward building a trust
fund to establish ``a scholarship for students interested in
peacemaking and peacekeeping.''
   In a speech, he said the focus of his efforts this year would be
to consolidate the ``very favorable trends which have emerged and
bring them to bear on the quest for a solution of all major
international disputes.''
   Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson told the audience of dignitaries
that Sweden had set aside money in next year's budget, submitted
Tuesday to Parliament, to contribute soldiers to the U.N. peace
force being created to monitor Namibia's transition to independence.
   The Palme Prize was first awarded last year to Cyril Ramahosa,
leader of the South African National Union of Mineworkers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. chief Michael Eisner
earned $40.2 million last year, mainly in profits from a
stock-option plan, to remain among the nation's highest paid
executives.
   Eisner, Disney's chairman and chief executive officer, realized a
$32.6 million profit from the company stock options program last
year and a $6.8 million bonus in addition to his $750,000 salary, a
proxy statement shows.
   The studio executive was given the option to purchase up to 2
million Disney shares at $14.54 per share when he joined the company
in 1984. At the close of trading Monday, Disney stock was selling at
$68 a share.
   Eisner's bonus, up from about $6 million in 1987, is calculated
using a formula calling for a bonus equal to 2 percent of the amount
Disney earnings exceed a 9 percent return on shareholder equity.
   Proxy material disclosed Monday that Eisner purchased 683,857
shares of Disney stock last year. Of that, he sold 330,390 for a
profit of $32.6 million. He still holds options to purchase n
additional 948,143 shares.
   Eisner now holds 353,467 Disney shares directly, or less than 1
percent of outstanding shares. His wife and children hold an
additional 28,800 shares.
   Under Eisner, Disney has had a string of hit movies and increased
revenues at its theme parks.
</TEXT>
