<FIRST>r p AM-CampaignViolation     01-10 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campaign Violation,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty In Campaign Scheme To Help Cranston</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An insurance broker has pleaded guilty to
making illegal campaign contributions in a scheme to help re-elect
U.S. Sen. Alan Cranston because of his outspoken support for Israel.
   Michael B. Altman of the Sherman Oaks area faces a maximum of one
year in prison and a $360,000 fine when he is sentenced March 27 by
U.S. District Judge Ronald Lew.
   Altman pleaded guilty Monday to a single misdemeanor count of
aiding pro-Israel activist Michael R. Goland in making illegal
campaign donations during the 1986 election narrowly won by
Cranston, a Democrat. He also agreed to testify against Goland and
two other men charged in the case.
   Authorities said Cranston was not involved in the scheme.
   Goland and two associates plotted to support Cranston, who was
outspokenly pro-Israel in the campaign, by illegally contributing
$120,000 to the campaign of American Independent Party candidate Ed
Vallen, the indictment alleged.
   Goland and the two associates have pleaded innocent to four
felony counts in the same case. The others charged are Lyle R.
Weisman, 31, of Beverly Hills, and Sandor E. Habalow, 45, of West
Los Angeles.
   Prosecutors said the aim of the scheme was to win some support
for Vallen through a television campaign that would siphon votes
away from Republican challenger Ed Zschau, thus improving Cranston's
chances for victory.
   After paying for production of the advertisement, the defendants,
in order to circumvent federal election laws limiting the size of
individual donations, sought $120,000 in contributions from 55
individuals who were later reimbursed for amounts ranging from
$1,000 to $4,000, prosecutors said.
   Vallen wound up getting 109,916 votes in the election _ about
5,000 more than Cranston's slim victory margin over Zschau.
</TEXT>
