<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-US     01-10 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-US,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Round Of Talks Begin Following Expiry of Former Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and American officials on Tuesday
began a new round of bases talks, the first since an accord
governing their operation expired last month.
   The round of talks, the 13th since negotiations began in November
1987, are not expected to make much headway toward a new agreement
on the four installations.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos would not comment on the
talks. He said a statement would be issued after negotiators brief
Premier Andreas Papandreou at their conclusion Thursday.
   A five-year agreement giving the United States access to the
bases _ two near Athens and two on the southern Aegean Sea island of
Crete _ expired Dec. 20.
   Under the old accord, the United States has 17 months to
dismantle the bases or negotiate a new agreement.
   A major obstacle blocking a new agreement is Papandreou's
insistence that the United States help solve Greece's disputes with
neighboring Turkey over military control of the Aegean, its seabed
mineral rights and the Cyprus problem.
   U.S. officials have said they don't want to involve regional
disputes in the bilateral bases talks.
   Papandreou, who has said he will hold a national referendum on
the installations, is expected to use the bases issue to attract
leftist votes in the June elections.
   Popular support for the ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement has
eroded in recent months after scandals implicated senior government
and party officials.
   The premier has already said his government plans to scrap one of
the U.S. installations _ Hellenikon Air Force base adjacent to
Athens Airport.
</TEXT>
