<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DrugTesting     01-10 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Testing,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Test Accuracy 97 Percent in Test of Selected Labs, Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-one laboratories following the
guidelines of an association of lab professionals and researchers
had an overall accuracy rate of 97 percent in testing urine samples
for narcotics, the director of a new study said Tuesday.
   ``After today, inaccuracies should not be used as an argument
against drug testing,'' said Christopher S. Frings, director of the
study conducted by the American Association of Clinical Chemistry
   Another expert said a problem of accuracy still exists among the
150 to 200 American laboratories that test for drugs.
   However, Frings said, ``The AACC does not extrapolate these
findings to say that all labs do good drug testing. We maintain that
labs that follow key procedures can test at a very high accuracy.''
   Frings, a professor at the University of Alabama, Birmingham,
said the overall error rate of 3 percent in the association's study
included no findings of false positives, meaning that none of the
drug-free samples was inaccurately identified as showing evidence of
drug use.
   The study involved sending urine samples that had been
adulterated with drugs to 31 selected laboratories that agreed to
the accuracy test. The test specimens were disguised so the
labortories could not identify them, and they were included with
other samples that were to be routinely tested.
   ``The laboratories had no way of knowing when they received the
(test) specimens,'' said Frings.
   Each of the samples was tested for evidence of five different
drugs _ cocaine, marijuana, opiates, amphetamines and phencyclidine
(PCP).
   Frings said 29 percent of the laboratories scored an accuracy of
100 percent; 64 percent had an accuracy of 97 percent or higher, and
the lowest score was 89 percent. He declined to identify the
laboratories or to give a numerical breakdown of the findings.
   All of the laboratories included in the study had participated
earlier in an open proficiency test by the association, and Frings
said the labs that participated in the new study all complied with
the standards approved by the association.
   Kenneth H. Davis Jr., senior research chemist at the Research
Triangle Institute in North Carolina, and a co-author of a federal
study on laboratory accuracies published last September in the
Journal of the American Medical Association, said in a telephone
interview that results in the association's study could be biased by
the pre-qualifying of the test laboratories used in the blind test.
   Davis said his survey of 50 laboratories showed 69 percent of the
samples were tested accurately in blind surveys. About 82 percent of
the tests were accurate in open surveys, when the laboratories knew
which samples were being tested. He said the false positives in his
study ranged up to 1.6 percent.
   ``A problem does still exist'' in the accuracy of testing for
drugs, Davis said. However, he agreed with the association that with
proper facilities, personnel and techniques, ``I see no reason why
drug testing canot be extremely accurate.''
   Drug-testing accuracy has become a subject of rising interest,
partly because of President Reagan's 1986 order calling for a
drug-free federal workplace. A federal program calls for the random
testing of workers, and an estimated 50,000 federal employees were
tested last year despite court challenges. The number to be tested
this year could pass 200,000, officials say, and there are plans
later this year to require testing of millions of transportation
workers in private business.
   Many cases challenging the constitutionality of drug testing are
on appeal in federal courts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CatTale     01-10 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cat Tale,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Library Disinherited for Evicting Cat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUTNAM VALLEY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a library evicted Muffin the cat
from its corridors and crannies after seven years' residence, a
93-year-old animal lover was so miffed she wrote the library out of
her will.
   ``Everybody loved that cat,'' Marjorie Horton, who had planned to
leave the Putnam Valley Library as much as $30,000, said Tuesday.
``I was furious. I wrote them a nice letter. I'm not some young
snotnose. But no one listened. Now, not one penny will go to the
library.''
   Muffin appeared on the doorstep of the privately run library as a
kitten one cold February night seven years ago and settled
comfortably among the volumes of Chaucer, Shakespeare, Tolstoy,
Eliot and the rest.
   But her fate took a Dickensian turn last year.
   Amid allegations that Muffin had swatted some children without
provocation and, more importantly, that one of the library trustees
was allergic to cats, the facility set about finding the tabby a new
home.
   Muffin was formally evicted by a trustees' vote in September,
although she stayed on for a few more months while a new home was
found and her supporters wrote letters and gathered petition
signatures.
   ``We had to make a decision,'' said Peter Grosewald, library
board chairman. ``The only issue is access. We have to assure access
to everybody.''
   Grosewald said the unidentified trustee, a volunteer like the
rest, complained that she could not work in the library despite
taking allergy shots and efforts to confine the cat to an upstairs
room.
   The trustee offered to resign, he said, but the board decided
that in light of other complaints about allergic reactions and the
alleged swipes at children, it was Muffin who had to go.
   The September vote, which was confidential, prompted threatening
phone calls, Grosewald said.
   Former trustee Kathleen Devlin, who gathered 300 signatures to
keep Muffin, pointed out that the cat had earned her keep as a
mouser.
   ``I feel so badly about that cat,'' said Mrs. Horton, who had
split her time between Putnam Valley and Manhattan for more than 80
years before moving permanently to Manhattan with her own cat last
year.
   She said Grosewald didn't even answer her letter on the cat's
behalf and that a new will has been drafted directing that whatever
money remains after her death be divided among three animal shelters.
   Grosewald emphasizes that Muffin now has a good home and that
access to the library has been opened to everyone.
   He said the library relies on contributions and donations, but
that Mrs. Horton's money wasn't everything: ``Even if it were a
million dollars, it would still be a hard choice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EhrlichSentencing     01-10 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ehrlich Sentencing,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biaggi's Former Law Partner Sentenced In Wedtech Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former law partner of ex-Rep. Mario Biaggi
was sentenced Tuesday to six years in prison and fined $220,000 for
his role in the Wedtech racketeering case.
   Bernard Ehrlich, 59, who has admitted to having mental problems,
cried intermittently during sentencing.
   ``I feel terrible about the employees and shareholders of
Wedtech, especially the employees who I've worked closely with,''
Ehrlich said. ``I feel sick over what I've done.''
   Ehrlich, who was found guilty of 11 counts of racketeering,
conspiracy, extortion and bribery, remains free on bail pending
appeal.
   He was convicted last summer with Biaggi and three other people
of turning the Wedtech Corp., the now-defunct South Bronx military
contractor, into a racketeering enterprise for their personal gain.
   ``You played a major and extensive role in this criminal
enterprise,'' U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley said. ``You
weren't only doing the bidding of Biaggi, but you corrupted your
co-defendant John Margiotta (a former Small Business Administration
official).''
   Also convicted in the scheme, which charged the defendants
received $1.8 million in cash and stocks from Wedtech, were Biaggi's
son, Richard, and former Bronx borough President Stanley Simon.
   Ehrlich was a former major general of the National Guard, where
he served as commander of the Rainbow Division. He was stripped of
his National guard rank at an administrative hearing in 1986.
   He was acquitted in December 1987 of state charges that he bribed
a former National Guard general to win favored treatment for Wedtech.
   Ehrlich's attorney, Peter Driscoll, asked Motley for leniency.
   ``He has both an overwhelming and relentless guilt about the
wrong he has caused,'' Driscoll said, adding that Ehrlich is
receiving counseling and had been hospitalized twice for mental
problems.
   Biaggi, who resigned after serving as congressman of the district
that included the Bronx for almost 20 years, was sentenced to eight
years in the Wedtech case. He is appealing the conviction.
</TEXT>
