<HEAD>Investigators Say No Leads In Slaying Of Priest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators had few clues to the
killing of a Roman Catholic priest whose body was burned atop a
trash fires, officials said Tuesday.
   ``We have no idea who did it or why,'' Tuscaloosa County Homicide
Chief Warren Miller said.
   The burned body of the Rev. Francis Craven, 53-year-old pastor of
St. Williams Catholic Church in Guntersville, was found Saturday on
a dirt road by a man taking his daily walk. The body was identified
Monday through dental records.
   He died of head injuries, said Kenneth E. Warner of the Alabama
Department of Forensic Sciences. Warner said it appeared that more
than one person was involved.
   Capt. Shirley Fields of the Sheriff's Department said authorities
were looking for Craven's blue and silver van, which he had picked
up that afternoon at the airport after returning to Birmingham from
Fort Myers, Fla., where he was visiting friends.
   Craven had called the friends to tell them he had arrived in
Birmingham and was going to return to Guntersville, where he was to
say afternoon Mass, said Lacy Galloway, chief deputy with the
Marshall County Sheriff's Department.
   He never made it home, prompting colleagues to report him missing.
   A funeral was scheduled Fridday in Birmingham.
