<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1842EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Commerce-Space     01-10 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commerce-Space,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary: Let Private Business Work in Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing Commerce Secretary C. William Verity
likened the nation's space agency to ``a glorified trucking
operation'' Tuesday and said government is not stepping aside fast
enough to allow private enterprise to flourish in space.
   ``Our interest in space, quite simply, has outgrown the space
agency,'' Verity said. ``Consequently it's time to rethink that
agency's mission. I suggest we recognize that NASA should do what
was envisioned in its original charter 30 years ago; NASA should be
responsible for promoting space science, research and exploration.''
   Speaking to the Space Business Roundtable, whose members include
representatives of companies doing business in space, Verity said
government must quit competing.
   ``There can be no real private sector space commerce if
government is intimately involved in the planning, ownership, and
operation of the underlying infrastructure,'' he said. ``By
exercising restraint in purchasing new hardware and facilities and
instead purchasing services from you, government can make way for
private capital to be invested in the national space
infrastructure.''
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has financed
the space shuttle and the space station ``at the expense of space
science and exploration,'' Verity said.
   Only Monday, the Reagan administration proposed to back the space
station with $2.1 billion construction startup funds this year.
``Can we really justify spending 30 billion taxpayer dollars on
something we aren't sure how we're going to use?'' Verity asked.
   According to the commerce secretary, ``NASA still seems to
believe that the drama of humans in space is needed to win attention
and congressional support, but an unmanned space program could put
the U.S. back into front-line technology _ at far less cost.''
   He said he speaks not only as a government official but also as a
grandfather who sees space as a place where his grandchildren will
live and work.
   ``Will the future Columbus study space science, only to discover
on graduation that his career options are limited to a government
bureaucracy that runs a glorified trucking operation, or a cost-plus
contractor that just fills orders?'' Verity asked. ``I hope that
person finds a system with room for entrepeneurs and explorers.''
</TEXT>
