<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     01-10 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam, Thailand Report Progress in Talks on Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam and Thailand reported progress
Tuesday in talks on how to end the decade-long Vietnamese occupation
of Cambodia and a guerrilla war that has filled refugee camps inside
the Thai frontier.
   ``I'm satisfied with the result of the talks,'' Foreign Minister
Nguyen Co Thach said after two days of meetings with the Thai
foreign minister, Siddhi Savetsila, who cautiously described them as
``good.''
   Referring to Cambodian guerrilla factions, Thach said: ``The two
sides are moving closer ... but to say no more gap is not yet
realistic because the gap is not yet solved by the Kampuchean
(Cambodian) parties.''
   Asked where the gaps existed, the Vietnamese official said: ``You
must ask Sihanouk and Hun Sen.'' Prince Norodom Sihanouk, former
ruler of Cambodia, is nominal leader of the guerrilla alliance and
Hun Sen is premier of Hanoi's client government in Phnom Penh.
   Siddhi and Thach said a joint statement would be issued Wednesday.
   Thach, who also is also deputy premier, said Monday both
countries agreed the Cambodian question could be resolved by
September. When asked if peace was near, he said it would ``be at
hand during the first six months of 1989.''
   Jetn Sucharitkul, spokesman for the Thai Foreign Ministry, said
after Siddhi arrived Monday that new approaches would be discussed.
He said a Thai proposal to resume a 1978 agreement on cooperation in
aviation, ocean commerce, telecommunications posts and trade also
was on the agenda..
   Siddhi is the most senior Thai official to visit Vietnam since
1976. Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan also has announced plans
to visit Vietnam.
   Since taking office in August, Chatichai has said he would
improve ties with communist Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos and increase
trade, provided all Vietnamese forces leave Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 to oust the Khmer Rouge
regime of Pol Pot, under which hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
were killed or starved to death in less than four years.
   Thailand backs the three-party Cambodian guerrilla alliance,
which includes the Khmer Rouge.
   Fears of a Khmer Rouge return to power have grown as Vietnam
withdrew some of its troops. The Vietnamese say the pullout will be
completed this year.
   Last week, the government of President Heng Samrin in Phnom Penh
suggested an earlier withdrawal target of September 1989 if Thailand
denied sanctuary to Cambodian guerrillas and supplies of weapons to
the rebels were halted. Vietnam put Heng Samrin in power in January
1979.
   One round of informal talks on ending the Cambodian conflict has
been held in Indonesia by the Phnom Penh government, guerrillas,
Vietnam, Laos and members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations: Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines
and Brunei. ASEAN is trying to arrange a second meeting for next
month.
</TEXT>
