<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Lord,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>New VP Picks Security Adviser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle said Tuesday
his national security adviser will be Carnes Lord, a former Reagan
White House aide and college professor.
   Lord, 44, has been director of international studies at the
National Institute for Public Policy in Fairfax, Va., since 1985. He
was a staff member of the National Security Council from 1981 to
1984.
   The Alexandria, Va., resident holds doctorates in government from
Cornell University and classics from Yale, and is the author of
several books, including ``The Presidency and the Management of
National Security.''
   Prior to serving in the Reagan administration, Lord was a
professor of government and foreign affairs at the University of
Virginia and worked for the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
