<FIRST>u i AM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0609 01-10 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0609,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Group of Cuban Soldiers Leaves Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, ``No official ...'' to make it about 5,000 dead.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LUA1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola sent 450 Cuban soldiers home
Tuesday, several weeks early, as part of a plan to remove foreign
forces from the country after a decade of war and bring independence
to neighboring Namibia.
   South African soldiers withdrew from southern Angola into
Namibia, also known as South-West Africa, last summer.
   A U.S.-mediated agreement signed Dec. 22 by Angola, Cuba and
South Africa, which controls Namibia, requires 3,000 Cuban soldiers
to be out of Angola by April 1 and all 50,000 to be gone in 27
months.
   U.N. military observers looked on while Cuban soldiers _ men and
women _ strode between ranks of Angolan troops and into three
waiting passenger aircraft at the airport in Luanda, capital of
Angola. An Angolan military band played marches.
   Brig. Gen. Samuel C. Rodiles Planas, commander of the Cuban
forces, and Maj. Gen. Ciel da Concessao, Angola's navy commander,
signed the withdrawal agreements at a table on the runway and handed
them to Pericles Ferreira Gomes, the Brazilian general in charge of
U.N. observers.
   The 450 soldiers were accompanied by a dozen ranking military
officers who came from Cuba for the occasion.
   Col. Arvid Geirulv, second in command of the 28-man U.N.
observers in Angola, said another 1,000 Cubans would be taken out on
ships by Wednesday, and 550 more would leave by air and 1,000 on
ships by Jan. 15.
   Geirulv said the rest of the 70 U.N. military and 20 civilian
observers would be in Angola by March 20.
   In a farewell speech in May 1 Square to a crowd of about 25,000,
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos said the first 3,000 Cubans were
leaving ahead of the deadline as ``a goodwill gesture.'' He said
``the names of those Cubans who fell here will be engraved forever
in our hearts.''
   No official figures are available for the number of Cuban
casualties in Angola, but most estimates put the number at about
5,000 dead.
   Cubans troops arrived in July 1975 to help the Marxist government
that won control after independence from Portugal fight rebels
supported by South Africa and the United States.
   All Cuban forces remaining are to be north of the 15th parallel
by Aug. 1 and north of the 13th parallel, beyond the east-west
Benguela railroad, by Nov. 1 in time for elections in South-West
Africa. South Africa agreed to Namibian independence in return for
Cuban withdrawal from Angola.
   The South Africans captured South-West Africa from Germany in
World War I and governed it under a League of Nations mandate. The
U.N. General Assembly abrogated the mandate in 1966 but South Africa
had refused to leave.
   South African soldiers entered Angola in 1975 to support the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola rebel group,
known by its initials UNITA. South African forces also raided bases
in southern Angola of South-West Africa People's Organization
guerrillas fighting for Namibian independence.
   Neither guerrilla group was involved in the peace agreement, but
SWAPO indicated willingness to go along with it.
   Alcides Sakala, UNITA spokesman in Lisbon, said in a telephone
interview Tuesday the Cuban withdrawal was ``a show ... theater.
It's too early to say the Cubans are really going to leave.''
   He said U.N. observers found in rebel-controlled territory would
be attacked.
   After a cease-fire agreement, South African forces withdrew from
southern Angola on Aug. 22. All but 1,500 South African soldiers are
to be out of Namibia by election day Nov. 1.
   Gen. Abelardo Colome Ibarra, Cuba's deputy army minister, told
the chanting crowd the ``real authors of this agreement are the men
and women who ... destroyed the myth of South African superiority in
this part of the world.''
   He said his soldiers would ``do their duty'' until they depart.
   Geirulv said he foresaw no serious problems in monitoring the
withdrawal. ``We shall go to the locations where they have been and
verify that they are empty,'' he said.
   Angola has asked the United Nations to pick up the cost of
shipping the Cubans home, which it estimates at $800 million.
   Lt. Gen. Antonio Santos Franca, the armed forces chief of staff,
attributed the high cost to temporary housing for the departing
Cuban troops and the need to build two airstrips in the south.
   Most Cubans will leave from the ports of Cabinda in the north and
Lobito and Namibe in the south.
</TEXT>
