<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Roosevelt     01-10 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Roosevelt,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Remembers FDR's Words, Says He Never Dreamed He'd Hold Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a young man, Ronald Reagan was stirred by
President Franklin D. Roosevelt's declaration that ``the only thing
we have to fear is fear itself.'' On Tuesday as he neared
retirement, Reagan acknowledged that upon hearing those words, he
never dreamed he'd hold the same office.
   Reagan and supporters of the FDR library in Hyde Park, N.Y.
gathered at the National Archives for a 50th anniversary fund-raiser
and to hear recordings of Roosevelt's first inaugural address in
1932.
   ``He really did convince us that the only thing we have to fear
is fear itself,'' Reagan said.
   The luncheon commemorated the anniversary of a similar gathering
on Feb. 4, 1939, when Roosevelt brought together 50 people to have
lunch and become trustees of the FDR library, which became the first
in the presidential library system.
   Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, the Senate majority leader, who
introduced Reagan, said, ``Roosevelt's legacy was to empower all
Americans to act through their government for the common good. Today
that principle is deeply engrained in our political and social
thought.''
   In one of the best-remembered passages in the recorded excerpt
from his inaugural address, Roosevelt said, ``First of all, let me
assert my firm belief that the only thing we have to fear is fear
itself _ nameless, unjustified, unreasoning terror which paralyzes
needed effort to convert retreat into advance.''
   Mitchell, recalling Roosevelt's struggle with poliomyelitis, told
the audience, ``He had known personal fear for his own future, so he
knew what he was talking about'' as he addressed the nation in the
grip of the Great Depression.
   Introducing Reagan, the majority leader drew parallels with the
32nd president, saying, ``Like President Roosevelt, President Reagan
possess a legendary ability to inspire in Americans pride in their
nation and faith in its future.''
   Reagan, a former Democrat turned Republican, said Roosevelt was
the first president he voted for and the first he ever saw, at a
campaign rally in Des Moines in 1936 while he was working as a radio
announcer.
   ``He really did convince us that the only thing we had to fear
was fear itself,'' he said. ``And it was that ebullience, that
infectious optimism, that made one young sportscaster think that
maybe he should be more active as a citizen.''
   ``I assure you, though, he never tied that to one day holding
public office and certainly never dreamed that destiny would take
him to the same office FDR held.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
