<FIRST>r a AM-NextGeneration     01-10 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Next Generation,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Task Force Told Adolescents Want to Be Listened to, Taken Seriously</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national task force on youth meeting for the
first time got some expert testimony Tuesday from a high-school
sophomore:
   ``Don't look down on me. Give me a challenge before you assume
it's too hard. I don't want easier schools. I want harder schools,
so that I can have pride in myself,'' Sarah Karp, 15, told the Task
Force on the Next Generation.
   Miss Karp said she is not proud to be a student in the Chicago
school system, called the worst in the nation by former Education
Secretary William Bennett.
   ``A lot of times I feel like I'm nobody because I have to go to
this school. Give me an outline for success. Let me learn from
teachers who love to teach,'' said Miss Karp, a sophomore at Lincoln
Park High School and school affairs editor of New Expression, a
citywide high-school publication.
   Creation of the privately funded 19-member task force, which
includes leaders from business, labor, government, religion, sports
and ethnic organizations, was announced last week by Chicago Mayor
Eugene Sawyer, who chaired Tuesday's hearing.
   ``We are standing in the wings watching our children stumble
toward the future when we should be taking them by the hand, showing
them the way,'' said Sawyer.
   More should be done to combat such adolescent problems as drug
abuse, teen-age pregnancy, delinquency and failure in school, said
Dr. Arthur B. Elster, director of the department of adolescent
health of the American Medical Association.
   ``The interval from 11-13 years of age appears to provide an
especially promising opportunity for prevention of later problem
behavior,'' Elster told the panel.
   Successful youth programs have staff members who know how to
listen and express concern, said Nancy M. Abbate, executive director
of Chicago's Youth Service Project Inc.
   She told the task force that troubled young people often complain
of being ignored by parents and other adults, saying things like,
``I'd like my mom to listen to me more,'' or ``I got mixed up with
this guy because at least he listened to me.'
   ``Unfortunately , we don't program money for caring,'' said Ms.
Abbate.
   She called for a national youth council, made up of young people
in and out of school, to ``draft guiding principals for the next
generation.''
   The panel, which organizers hope will find ways to better serve
young people, plans hearings in Los Angeles, Atlanta and the East
Coast before presenting recommendations this spring to U.S. House
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, who has promised a congressional review.
</TEXT>
