<FIRST>r a AM-GangCrime     01-10 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gang Crime,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Murder Rate Drops, But Gang Deaths Up in '88</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's murder rate dropped to its lowest
level in 10 years, but gang slayings and gang-related crimes rose in
Los Angeles last year, police said.
   Murders in the nation's second-largest city fell from 832 in 1987
to 734 last year, the lowest total since 1978, when there were 678
homicides, according to police statistics released Monday.
   ``In my own view, Los Angeles is what it has been all along, one
of the safest major cities in the United States,'' said Cmdr.
William Booth, department spokesman.
   Los Angeles' murder rate of 22.9 killings for every 100,000
residents is lower than that of many other large cities, Booth said.
   Washington, D.C., the nation's murder leader, lists 59.2 murders
per 100,000 people, followed by Detroit with 58 murders per 100,000
and Dallas with 56.7.
   Booth attributed the murder drop to 900 extra police officers on
the street and a greater willingness by officers to make arrests in
domestic disputes.
   There were 257 gang killings in the city in 1988 compared with
205 in 1987, an increase Booth said was caused by a near-doubling of
the gang population.
   Investigators listed 27,795 known gang members last year compared
with 15,000 the year before.
   Gang-related crime increased from 5,129 reported incidents in
1987 to 5,371 in 1988.
   The Sheriff's Department also reported an increase in
gang-related slayings in unincorporated areas of the county, up from
79 in 1987 to 96 last year. County totals were incomplete because
smaller city police departments have yet to compile year-end
statistics.
</TEXT>
