<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ForcedLabor     01-10 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Forced Labor,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daimler-Benz Dedicates Memorial To Forced Laborers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto giant Daimler-Benz on Tuesday
unveiled a sculpture at its headquarters in memory of thousands of
workers forced to toil at company plants during Nazi domination in
World War II.
   The iron sculpture was commissioned from Berlin sculptor Bernhard
Heiliger.
   Daimler-Benz officials announced last year that the company would
pay $11 million in reparations for the use of forced labor under
Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler.
   Hundreds of thousands of people from countries occupied by the
Nazis were forced to work under poor conditions to help fuel the
German war effort.
   According to figures compiled for Daimler-Benz, more than 29,000
forced laborers were working at company facilities in 1944.
   Daimler-Benz's reparation payments were divided into several
parts.
   About $5.5 million was paid to the Conference on Jewish Material
Claims Against Germany in New York. About $2.7 million went to the
Red Cross and another $2.7 million went to organizations in Poland.
   The money was earmarked for medical and elderly care facilities
that treat victims of the Holocaust and former forced laborers.
</TEXT>
