<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     01-10 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Ending State of Emergency; Militants Kill Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa
announced Tuesday he will end the 5{-year state of emergency and
free all political prisoners.
   Also Tuesday, Sinhalese militants killed three people, including
two candidates for parliamentary elections.
   Premadasa promised he would never again impose a state of
emergency, but did not say whether he thought it had been effective
in curbing ethnic violence between the Buddhist Sinhalese majority
and mainly-Hindu Tamil minority.
   The state of emergency, which expires Sunday, had been reinstated
every month since it was imposed in May 1983.
   ``We have lived under emergency rule for more than five years
now. I feel that is enough for everybody,'' Premadasa told a publiic
meeting of top government officials and legislators.
   Police said Sinhalese militants Tuesday firebombed and opened
fire on a car, killing opposition candidates Indrapala Abeyweera and
Wijeyalal Mendis of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party, and their
bodyguard, identified only as Martin. They were to contest Feb. 12
national elections.
   A police spokesman blamed the Sinhalese People's Liberation Front
for the attack at Waduwa town, 20 miles south of the capital,
Colombo. The front is an extremist Sinhalese group that opposes
government efforts to give more autonomy to Tamils.
   A military spokesman said at least 12 people have been killed
since Monday, including three Sri Lankan soldiers ambushed by Tamil
rebels in the north.
   Other victims, all civilians in the Sinhalese-dominated south,
included three members of the ruling United National Party and a
Buddhist priest. The spokesman said all the civilians were killed by
the People's Liberation Front.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of the country's 16 million people and
claim they are denied jobs and education by the Sinhalese majority.
More than 8,500 people have died since militant Tamils started
fighting six years ago for an independent nation.
   Premadasa told the meeting everyone imprisoned under emergency
regulations would be released.
   The emergency gives police and soldiers broad powers to arrest
and detain people for up to 90 days without charges, to dispose of
bodies without inquests, and raid homes without warrants.
   ``If those arrested cannot be charged, they should be released,''
he said.
   Government officials who asked not to be identified said
authorities released 574 political prisoners between Jan. 1 and Jan.
6. But they did not say how many others still are in detention. The
exact figure is not known, but is estimated at 2,200.
   Premadasa said he has asked authorities to examine particularly
the case against Sinhalese students held for staging anti-government
riots that forced the closure of 10,400 schools and seven
universities last year.
</TEXT>
