<FIRST>r w AM-Budget-Cities     01-10 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Cities,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Ask Bush to Reject Reagan Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's mayors want President-elect Bush
to reject President Reagan's proposed cuts in domestic spending, the
president of the U.S. Conference of Mayors said Tuesday.
   Arthur J. Holland, head of the group and the mayor of Trenton,
N.J., said cities and their residents would be hurt by proposed
reductions in programs ranging from school-lunch subsidies to grants
for community development projects.
   ``We have come to the end of a decade that has seen a dramatic
shift toward defense spending, away from discretionary domestic
spending,'' Holland said at a news conference.
   ``Let us hope the end of this decade is also the end of an era,
and that the 1990s will produce a federal budget that is balanced in
every sense of the word,'' he said.
   Holland, a Democrat, commented at a news conference called to
react to Reagan's proposed fiscal 1990 budget. He said the cities
have suffered cuts in urban programs throughout the Reagan
administration and called the budget ``nothing new. It's what we've
come to expect.''
   He said he was pleased with proposed increases in spending for
AIDS programs, the Superfund waste cleanup program and education.
   But he said the proposal would reduce money for state and local
enforcement, treatment and education programs on drugs, even while
increasing the total appropriation for federal anti-drug efforts.
   Holland also pointed to proposed cuts in mass transit assistance,
reductions in child nutrition spending and school lunch subsidies,
elimination of the Economic Development Administration and a cut
from $3 billion to $2.8 billion in the Community Development Block
Grants program.
   Questioned by reporters, Holland said there is enough money now
going to waste and fraud in the Defense Department to pay for urban
needs.
   ``You say, where will the money come from? It's there, without
increasing the budget,'' he said.
</TEXT>
