<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     01-10 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Party Meeting on Solidarity Scheduled for Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party plenum to consider the
stance toward the banned trade union Solidarity will begin Monday.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban, revealing the date, said he did
not know yet if the assembly of the 230-member party Central
Committee would last one or two days.
   The meeting will be the second part of a plenum that began Dec.
20-21. Its first session was highlighted by Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski's speech instructing Central Committee
members to poll the party rank-and-file for their current attitude
toward Solidarity and toward union chairman Lech Walesa.
   Members were directed to come back to the plenum in mid-January
with their answers and specific suggestions for action.
   The Rakowski speech was the strongest signal to date that
authorities are considering dropping the seven-year legal ban on
Solidarity, which is the condition that Solidarity has set for
entering talks with officials on negotiating a pact to attack
pressing economic and political problems.
   In the past two weeks, there have been signs of division among
the authorities with regard to Solidarity.
   Articles favorable to Walesa and the ``constructive opposition''
have appeared in the official press, alternating with thinly veiled
attacks.
   Urban said the party weekly Polityka plans to publish the program
of an anti-Walesa faction of Solidarity led by activist Andrzej
Gwiazda, which is on record as seeking greater confrontation with
the authorities.
   The unusual action appeared likely to spur fresh charges that
Solidarity is splintered and riddled with radicals who cannot be
trusted to engage in dialogue.
   Asked if the government is ready to change its stance toward
Solidarity, Urban declined to answer, saying the question likely
would be addressed at the plenum.
   ``I can only tell you that the results are unpredictable,'' he
said of the meeting.
</TEXT>
