<FIRST>r w AM-InsuranceCampaign     01-10 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Campaign,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drive to Amend State Laws Opened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organization Citizens Action announced
plans Tuesday to campaign for changes in insurance laws in 14
states, patterned after the successful ballot initiative in
California.
   Robert M. Brandon, vice president of the federation of statewide
citizens organizations called Citizens Action, said a ``consumer
revolt against skyrocketing insurance rates'' has been spreading as
a result of the passage of Proposition 103 in California, which
ordered rollbacks in auto insurance rates.
   Brandon said the campaigns varied, but that in general they seek
tougher regulation, lower rates, full disclosure of financial
information and elimination of anti-trust exemptions for insurance
companies.
   He said campaigns were planned or underway in Connecticut,
Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Maine, Maryland, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New York, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, West Virginia and
Wisconsin.
   Citizens Action is a federation of statewide citizens and
consumer organizations representing 1.75 million members.
