<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     01-10 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla, White Suspected in Attacks on Church Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla and a man accused
of mass murder are suspects in separate attacks on anti-apartheid
church groups last year, the government said Tuesday.
   Minister of Law and Order Adriaan Vlok said he was releasing the
names of the suspects because the ``police were being maliciously
accused by certain people of being lax and unwilling to solve the
cases.''
   Anti-apartheid groups have said they suspect government security
forces of the attacks.
   Vlok said Shirley Gunn, who is white, and two unidentified men
were suspected in the Aug. 31 bombing of a building in Johannesburg.
   The bombing injured several people and destroyed the building,
which contained the offices of the South African Council of Churches
and several other groups opposed to the government.
   Vlok described Ms. Gunn, 33, as a member of the outlawed African
National Congress who had received ``terrorist training'' in Angola.
He said police believed the bomb went off prematurely when Ms. Gunn
and the others brought it into the house to work on it for use as a
car bomb.
   He said Hendrik Strydom, who is in custody and is accused of
killing seven people in a shooting spree in Pretoria, was a suspect
in a fire Oct. 12 that damaged the headquarters of the Southern
African Catholic Bishops Conference, also a government critic. No
one was injured.
   Police have said they saw a van with 11 people of both races
driving past the building in Pretoria just before the fire broke
out. Vlok did not refer to this in his statement.
   Strydom, 23, was apprehended Nov. 15 just following the shooting
spree, in which 15 people were injured. All the dead and injured
were black, except for one man of Indian descent.
</TEXT>
