   King Hussein told visiting U.S. lawmakers
Tuesday that he was optimistic about a solution to the Arab-Israeli
conflict, the official Jordan news agency reported.
   Hussein met with Republican Sens. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas and
John McCain of Arizona, and then with Reps. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio;
James Hansen, R-Utah; and James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis.
   Hussein said Jordan's renunciation in July to claims to the
Israeli-occupied West Bank has led to stronger relations between
Jordan and the Palestine Liberation Organization, according to the
news agency.
   Kassebaum, a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
said in an interview before meeting Hussein that she favored ``a
little more even hand'' in balancing U.S. support for Israel and
Arab nations.
   But she said the senators told Israeli and Jordanian officials
that U.S. budget problems ``are not going to make any changes easy.''
   Kassebaum said she supported the U.S. decision to open talks with
the PLO after chairman Yasser Arafat's decision to renounce
terrorism and accept Israel's right to exist.
   But renewed terrorist activity ``would mean everything was off
again in terms of recognizing the PLO,'' she said.
   Kassebaum also said Israel's tough response to Palestinian
protests in the occupied territories has weakened U.S. public
support for Israel.
   ``Constituent mail comments back home clearly reflect that
Americans want not just to unquestioningly provide major amounts of
money to Israel without saying, `Just a minute now, you have some
problems, too.'''
   Kassebaum and McCain, a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, planned to arrive in Syria Wednesday night and in Egypt
Thursday.
