<FIRST>r w AM-People-Retton     01-10 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Retton,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mary Lou Retton Sues Over Loss of Bowling-Promotion Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic gold medal-winning gymnast Mary Lou
Retton and her family are suing two bowling industry trade groups
for $250,000, alleging the organizations terminated a promotional
agreement due to changes in Retton's physical image ``caused by her
maturing as a woman.''
   The suit filed in U.S. District Court says that Retton, her
parents and a brother began representing the two trade groups in
July 1985 under a four-year agreement, with Retton to be available
for personal appearances and the other family members to be
available for the preparation of promotional material.
   The Rettons were to promote bowling as an activity for families,
young people and senior citizens under the arrangement with the
National Bowling Council Inc. of Washington and the Bowling
Proprietors Association of America of Arlington, Texas, the suit
says. The groups represent bowling alley operators.
   Last June, the trade groups notified Retton and her family that
the agreement was being terminated, the suit says, ``on the ground
that Mary Lou Retton, due to changes in her physical image caused by
her maturing as a woman, was no longer a suitable spokesperson.''
The court papers did not elaborate.
   The suit, filed Monday, alleges breach of the agreement and says
there was no provision in it permitting the trade groups to
terminate it for such a reason.
   Retton, of Fairmont, W.Va., as a 16-year-old captured the
all-around gold medal in women's gymnastics at the 1984 Summer
Olympic Games.
   A secretary at the bowling council said Tuesday that the group's
spokesman was out sick for the day. A spokeswoman for the
Proprietors Association, Connie Kerr, said she wasn't aware the suit
had been filed and had no other immediate comment.
</TEXT>
