<FIRST>r i AM-India-Film     01-10 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Film,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Film Festival Opens Amid Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12th International Film Festival of
India opened Tuesday amid political protests by participating stars.
   At least 200 films from more than 45 countries will be screened
at eight theaters in the city in the next two weeks.
   The start of the festival was marked by protests against the
killing last week of Safdar Hashmi, a director and writer of street
plays.
   Shabana Azmi, a leading Indian actress, said Hashmi, a member of
the Marxist Communist Party, was ``murdered in broad daylight'' by
the followers of a member from the ruling Congress Party.
   The actress made the remarks while being introduced to the
audience during the function. Information and Broadcasting Minister
H.K.L. Bhagat, who inaugurated the festival, rebutted the allegation
and said strict deterrent action would be taken against those found
guilty.
   Hashmi was attacked Jan. 1 in the town of Sahibabad, on the
eastern outskirts of New Delhi, and died of his injuries two days
later. He was staging a play critical of the government when he was
attacked.
   Ms. Azmi co-stars with Shirley Maclaine, Dame Peggy Ashcroft and
Twiggy in John Schlesinger's film, ``Madam Sousatzka,'' which was
screened after the opening ceremony.
   The annual festival has broken away from the practice of holding
a competition section. The director of the festival, Urmila Gupta,
said the move was intended to attract ``a better quality of
cinema,'' since the competition section precluded screening films
that had been shown at other festivals.
   ``The quality of films this year is high and critics and
(movie-goers) will not have to take chances with unknown films which
may or may not prove good,'' Mrs. Gupta said.
   But many critics saw the move as self-defeating. The Indian
Express newspaper said the festival ``could have become important as
an alternative festival'' and ``held out hopes'' for cinema from the
Third World.
   The festival also will show retrospectives on the films of
Schlesinger, Vera Chytilova of Czechoslovakia, Lina Wertmuller of
Italy, West German-born Fritz Lang and India's Raj Kapoor.
   Special sections on Chinese films and black cinema from the
United States also are scheduled.
</TEXT>
