<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Libya     01-10 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Libya,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Defends Pilots' Actions as `Justified'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday defended the Navy
pilots who shot down two Libyan jets over the Mediterranean last
week, insisting the Americans ``were justified in doing what they
did.''
   Reagan, in a photo session with President Jose Azcona of
Honduras, was asked about a published report that the two Navy
pilots who downed the Libyan MiG-23s fired after their commander had
informed them they were in a cautionary ``warning yellow''
situation, rather than in the ``red'' condition reserved for
fire-at-will encounters.
   Asked if he believed the two pilots were ``trigger-happy'' and
had fired at the Libyan jets before they should have, Reagan
responded:
   ``No, I think to speculate on that is ignoring the facts. I have
said from the very beginning, I've never asked people to go any
place without the right to defend themselves against attack,''
Reagan said. ``All the evidence that we have, photographic, sound,
everything ... they were justified in doing what they did.''
   The president told his listeners, ``Remember, we're not dealing
with an earlier day with machine guns, ... today if a plane persists
in keeping you in line, when you are avoiding it, you have to assume
they are getting ready to push the button.''
   Spokesmen at both the White House and Pentagon disputed the
report, published in the Washington Post on Tuesday. The spokesmen
said the ``condition yellow'' issued by the commander on the scene
allowed the pilots to take defensive actions and to fire if
necessary.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked about the report in
the Post, said, ``The yellow warning indicates that pilots can take
defensive actions to defend themselves ... the fact is that under
the yellow caution, they have the right to defend themselves and to
fire, and they did.''
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard echoed Fitzwater's comments,
saying, that the ``warning yellow, weapons hold'' command issued by
the airborne warfare commander was intended to tell all of the
pilots ``to be careful; that there was a probability of hostilities,
and that they could shoot in self defense.
   ``I cannot go into the rules of engagement. ... But the actions
taken by the crews of the F-14's met the most rigorous
interpretation'' of the rules. ``They behaved prudently in
protecting themselves, their aircraft and their ship.''
</TEXT>
