<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan knows he has a job
waiting once he leaves the White House.
   Reagan on Monday made a courtesy telephone call to businessman
Dale Cain _ he's used Cain's electrical contracting company in
speeches as an example of how hard work can pay off _ and got the
offer.
   ``By the way,'' Cain said he told the president, ``if you don't
have anything to do after Jan. 20, you always can have a job with
Cain &amp; Abell.''
   Reagan ``laughed and laughed,'' Cain said.
   Cain first wrote Reagan in early 1985 telling him about his
company and how it had grown since it was started in 1981 with
$1,000. Last year, Cain &amp; Abell Inc. had sales of more than $2
million.
   Cain was invited to the White House and met Reagan in March 1985
and has written the president several times since then. He said he
has had phone calls from Reagan at Christmas in 1986 and one
checking on his progress in mid-1987. Cain last wrote the president
on Dec. 17.
   Cain said that during the phone call on Monday Reagan apologized
for not getting back sooner. ``He said, `Things have been very, very
hectic around here' and laughed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A renegade rooster sentenced to the city
dog pound has been eating dog food and then crowing about it.
   ``He starts that, and every dog in here howls,'' said Larry Cole,
dog pound director.
   ``He acts like he's in charge of the dogs. He's not scared of
anything. He eats all of his food every day _ I guess because it's
got grain in it.''
   The rooster was picked up Dec. 27 by dogcatchers after it was
spotted darting in and out of traffic.
   The law directs the ``fowl at large'' be taken to the city pound,
and the owner _ after ``briefly'' describing the bird _ must pay 25
cents per day for his release.
   Cole said to his knowledge, the pound has never kept a rooster
before.
   ``One of the guys said we had a horse once,'' Cole said.
   ``And we've had some calls about hogs running loose and goats,
but we never caught any.''
