<FIRST>r w AM-Mansfield     01-10 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mansfield,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mansfield Praises Reagan, Shultz for Pacific Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retiring U.S. Ambassador Mike Mansfield praised
President Reagan and Secretary of State George Shultz on Tuesday for
their interest in the Pacific region, which he said holds the key to
future world relationships.
   Mansfield, at a ceremony marking his retirement as ambassador to
Japan, said of Reagan and Shultz, ``For the first time, people in
your official positions ... have shown a continuing, a sustained, a
personal interest in the Pacific basin as a whole, in the Far East
in general and in Japan in particular.''
   ``I think that the future relationships in the world will be
decided by what happened in the 20th century (which) I look upon as
the century of the Pacific,'' he added.
   ``We are witnessing just the beginning of a new era; we are
building the foundation blocks for that era in the last years of
this century,'' Mansfield said, noting that U.S. trans-Pacific trade
has swelled from $42 billion to $250 billion since 1975.
   Mansfield spoke at a State Department gathering attended by
Shultz and by Japanese Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga.
   Japan is currently in official mourning for Emperor Hirohito, who
died last Saturday.
   Mansfield said in a brief interview that as a junior congressman
in the last days of World War II he had been among those
recommending consideration be givento allowing the emperor to stay
on in order to promote earlier surrender and orderly reforms. The
recommendation proved correct, he said.
   Mansfield, 85, was presented his ambassadorial flag and a plaque
marking 50 years of public service at Tuesday's ceremony. He had
been a U.S. Marine, copper miner, University of Montana professor,
congressman and finally Senate majority leader for 14 years when
President Carter named him ambassador to Japan in 1977.
   He said credit for successes in U.S.-Japan relations should go to
Shultz and to countless State Department foreign service specialists
``who have manned the ramparts year after year, decade after
decade,'' often at a cost of earlier promotions they might have won
by staying in Washington.
</TEXT>
