<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan-Economy     01-10 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Economy,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Sends His Final Economic Message To Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Deficit Commission Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tax cuts helped produce peacetime prosperity in
America, and ``all that is required to reduce the deficit is to
halt, or moderate, the increase in expenditures,'' President Reagan
said Tuesday.
   In his last economic message to Congress, Reagan said success in
dealing with problems of unemployment, inflation and taxes resulted
from his strategy of curbing the federal government's role in the
life of private business.
   ``I leave office secure in the knowledge that these policies have
worked, and confident that this great nation will continue to lead
the way toward freedom and prosperity for all mankind,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan said the high inflation and slow growth of the 1970s gave
way during his term in office to a long economic expansion and a low
unemployment rate.
   ``By reducing taxes and regulatory bureaucracy, we have unleashed
the creative genius of ordinary Americans and ushered in an
unparalleled period of peacetime prosperity,'' Reagan said.
   After ticking off economic gains over the past eight years,
Reagan said that ``as proud as I am over these and many other
accomplishments, I will be the first to admit that the agenda is not
yet completed. First and foremost is a need to reform the budget
process and to bring federal spending under control.''
   The president said that ``the large budget deficit that this
nation faces is not a result of too few taxes, but too much
spending. ... All that is required to reduce the deficit is to halt,
or moderate, the increase in expenditures.''
   Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers,
told reporters at a White House briefing that gains ``were not due
to Reagan luck, but rather due to specific policies of this
administration to reinvigorate the private sector.''
   In projections in the report, Sprinkel predicted continued gross
national product growth of 3.2 percent this year and at least that
each year through 1994.
   During his briefing for reporters, he noted that some critics
have described the administration's economic growth and revenue
forecasts as ``a rosy scenario.''
   Sprinkel said the forecasts were based at least in part on ``the
assumption that the basic thrust of policy in this administration
will be continued'' in the Bush administration.
   Reagan sent his last budget to Congress on Monday, recommending a
$1.15 trillion spending plan, bearing a $92.5 billion deficit, for
the fiscal year opening Oct. 1.
   President-elect Bush has said the Reagan budget generally
reflected his own views about fiscal policies but indicated he will
offer alternatives shortly after taking office next week.
   Sprinkel said he did not think it unrealistic to formulate
projections about the nation's business health on the assumption
that a Bush administration will employ the same Reagan
administration emphasis on a free market-oriented economic strategy.
   ``I listened to the (presidential) campaign,'' he said. ``I read
the lips. I have worked with Vice President Bush rather closely.''
   ``At this stage of the game, it seems sensible to us to assume
that, yes, there will be some new priorities, but, no, we're not
moving away from market orientation,'' Sprinkel said.
</TEXT>
