<HEAD>Precede FRANKFURT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with violent clashes in West Berlin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Students Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking students protesting overcrowding and a
lack of government aid on Tuesday threw rocks and bottles at police,
who used truncheons to disperse them at West Berlin's Free
University, officials said.
   Seven police officers were injured, officials said.
   The police officers were trying to escort students to classes
past demonstrators, who staged a boycott and tried to block an
entrance to the university, officials said on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier Tuesday, about 200 students in Frankfurt marched through
the city's center carrying banners protesting the use of police
force in West Berlin.
   The students, most in their late teens and early 20s, marched
from Frankfurt's main train station to the city's large
``Hauptwache'' shopping area. Police in squad cars and on foot
followed the marchers. There were no incidents.
   The protest came one day after police in West Berlin were
summoned to the Kreuzberg area of the city to quell a reported
disturbance.
   When four policemen entered the foyer of an apartment building to
check on the report, about 20 young people in black leather jackets
attacked them with clubs and tear gas, police said in a statement to
the news media.
   Four policemen were injured in the attack, which broke off only
after police reinforcements arrived and a warning shot was fired in
the air.
   The four injured police were hospitalized for treatment.
   Five of the youths involved in the attack were arrested and face
assault charges, the statement said.
