<FIRST>r w AM-US-Honduras     01-10 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Honduras,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Assures Honduran Leader of Continuing Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush told Honduran President
Jose Azcona on Tuesday that he will work to keep relations between
the two countries ``strong as they are today.''
   Azcona said they talked as friends but that the discussion
included ``the difficult situation Honduras finds itself in''
because of U.S.-backed rebels using Honduras as a staging ground for
opposition to Nicaragua's government.
   Bush, talking briefly to reporters after he met with Azcona at
the White House, said, ``I told him I felt that relations between
Honduras and the United States were good, excellent.''
   ``We know there's enormous pressures, regional pressures,'' the
president-elect said of economic and social conflicts in Central
America. ``I told him that we needed some time in the new
administration to formulate our policies. I also told him that there
would be no surprises and that the relationship between Honduras and
the United States under the new administration would be strong as
they are today.''
   Before meeting with Bush, Azcona met with President Reagan in the
Oval Office, and the Honduran president told reporters he believed
Reagan had been ``a good friend'' of his country.
   Bush did not answer directly when asked whether he had discussed
with Azcona the level of U.S. support for the Contra rebels
resisting the leftist Sandinista government in Nicaragua.
   ``We discussed almost every subject you can think of,'' Bush
said, when asked that question.
   Honduran officials have spoken out against the presence of Contra
forces which have massed inside their borders.
   Azcona, speaking through an interpreter, said he discussed with
Bush ``the difficult situation that Honduras finds itself in because
of the problem of the Nicaraguan counterrevolutionaries.''
   ``We said, and we have always said, that this is the product of
the lack of internal democracy inside of Nicaragua,'' he said. ``But
in any case ... we said that we felt ... a solution should be
hastened, should be pressed for and hastened inside of Nicaragua.''
   ``President Reagan and President Bush always have expressed their
concern about the Central American problem,'' he said. ``They have
also said that they were worried about it. We understand that both
of them are interested in a political situation inside of Nicaragua.
They are interested in having a democratic solution pushed for.''
   Of his meeting with Bush, he said, ``We had a very frank
conversation and a friendly one. It was a conversation without
reservations and of the kind of frankness that we like when we have
talks with friends.''
</TEXT>
