<FIRST>r w AM-JusticeCuts     01-10 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice Cuts,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Fires 21 Employees in Cost-Cutting Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department, in an effort to cut
expenses, fired 21 employees Tuesday from its public affairs and
legislative affairs staffs.
   Of the 11 people laid off from the public affairs office, six are
spokesmen, including two with more than 20 years of service.
   Three of the four spokesman who will be on the payroll after the
cuts take effect Feb. 10 will be political appointees.
   ``It was like a bomb went off,'' said one fired spokesman, Brad
Marman. ``Stone shock.''
   Also being laid off are 10 employees from the Office of
Legislative Affairs, said Thomas Boyd, assistant attorney general in
charge of that office. Those workers include professional and
support staff, career and political appointees, he said.
   The reductions are ``being done to allow the department to beat
its budget requirements,'' Boyd said.
   The 21 people being laid off receive total annual salaries of
$955,983, said Deborah Burstion-Wade, deputy director of public
affairs.
   Loye Miller, public affairs director, said the decision by
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh's staff to lay off 11 people in
his office ``came as a surprise, although I did know ... that OMB
(the Office of Management and Budget) had undertaken to cut us back.
... I knew something was brewing, but I didn't anticipate anything
of this severity.''
   ``In these times of severe budgetary constraints and concern
about ensuring adequate law enforcement, the focus of our attention
and resources must necessarily be on direct law enforcement
programs,'' Deputy Attorney General Harold G. Christensen said in a
memo to Harry H. Flickinger, assistant attorney general for
administration.
</TEXT>
