<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Hand     01-10 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Hand,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Hand Feels Fine, Soon To Get Splint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, waving his bandaged hand for
the television cameras, said Tuesday that it feels fine and he
expects to get a splint on it soon.
   ``Isn't it pretty?'' Reagan said with a laugh as he waved his
left heavily bandaged hand for photographers during a picture-taking
session with President Jose Azcona of Honduras in the Oval Office.
   On Saturday, Reagan underwent 2{ hours of surgery at Walter Reed
Army Medical Center to have a curvature of his left ring finger
corrected. The ailment is known as Dupuytren's Contracture and
caused his finger to curve inward.
   The president returned to the White House on Sunday, after
spending two nights at the hospital for the operation, which is
considered routine.
   Asked how he felt after a day back at work, Reagan said, ``I feel
just fine.''
   The president went on to lavish praise on the team of physicians
who worked on him at the hospital, saying he wanted to ``give great
credit'' to his military doctors.
   ``I was very fortunate to have this operation here because this
is a specialty of the military,'' Reagan said of the operation.
   Dr. Stephen Shaffer, a specialist in hand surgery, said the field
of hand surgery first developed in the Army during World War II, but
has since moved actively into the civilian medicine. Extended
fellowship training and extra examinations are now required before a
surgeon can become a certified hand specialist.
   ``The guys I know at Walter Reed are all good surgeons,'' he
said, but added that such expertise is now also commonly available
in the civilian medical community.
   Reagan said he expects to have his hand put in a splint on
Wednesday.
   The president is expected to wear what is known as a ``dynamic''
splint, which allows the finger to flex _ and thereby be
strengthened with exercise _ so that the finger does not return to
the curved position caused by the ailment.
</TEXT>
