<DOCNO> AP890110-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0666 01-10 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Opens Way for U.N. Peace Role, 10 Wounded in Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with settlers to strike, details;
CORRECTS timing of Shamir's statement. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Tuesday for the
first time opened the way for a United Nations role in the Middle
East peace process, but he again rejected the PLO as a negotiating
partner.
   In the occupied territories, an alleged Palestinian collaborator
was killed, reportedly by other Arabs, and 10 Palestinians were
reported wounded in clashes with Israeli troops.
   Shamir told representataives of the European Parliament that
Israel would accept U.N. involvement in Middle East peace
negotiations. The Parliament has been pressing Israel to negotiate
with the PLO.
   Shamir said any peace talks must be held directly with Arab
parties to the conflict and ruled out the Palestine Liberation
Organization's sitting at the bargaining table.
   ``Such negotiations can be launched under the auspices of the
great powers (the United States and the Soviet Union) or the United
Nations, providing they refrain from any involvement in the
substance of the talks,'' Shamir said.
   Shamir has contended until now that a U.N.-sponsored forum would
be biased against Israel and force concessions from the Jewish state.
   The Arab states want an international conference attended by the
five permanent Security Council members _ the United States, the
Soviet Union, China, Britain and France _ who would play an active
role in negotiations.
   European Parliament Speaker Lord Plumb addressed Israel's
Parliament after Shamir's statement, saying the European Community
supported an international conference under U.N. auspices with the
PLO as a negotiating partner.
   He said European Community members also believe the conflict
could not be resolved unless Israel withdrew from the occupied
territories and recognized the Palestinians' right to
self-determination.
   ``It is clear that without the recognition of the legitimate
rights of the Palestinians there cannot be any prospect of a durable
peace for any country in the region,'' Plumb said.
   Jewish settlers in the occupied West Bank, meanwhile, appeared to
adopt the tactics used by Palestinian protesters and declared a
one-day general strike in at least 32 settlements for Thursday.
   Their leaders said the strike was to protest the death of three
Israelis in the West Bank last month and Palestinian stone-throwing
attacks.
   At least 10 Palestinians were shot and wounded Tuesday in clashes
with Israeli soldiers in a half dozen towns and refugee camps in the
occupied territories, Arab reports and hospital officials said.
   Arab hospital officials said a 12-year-old girl was shot in the
head and wounded during a confrontation between troops and
stone-throwing youths in Shati refugee camp in the Gaza Strip.
   They said a 17-year-old youth was shot in the head with a rubber
bullet in another Gaza refugee camp and a 23-year-old man was hit in
the chest with a live round in the West Bank village of Beit Lit.
   The army confirmed nine wounded and said they included a girl
from Shati taken in serious condition to an Israeli hospital.
   Arab reporters said Palestinians who collaborate with Israeli
authorities shot and killed a 27-year-old man in the West Bank
village of Idna Monday night after he refused to feed them
information.
   An Arab reporter quoted family members as saying the victim,
Kayed Muhammad Tmaizi, acted as an informant for Israeli security
forces until the Palestinian uprising began. They said he recently
was pressured to renew his cooperation.
   An army official, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed
Tmaizi's death and maintained Tmaizi was killed in a dispute among
Palestinians. He did not elaborate.
   The death brought to 349 the number of Palestinians killed in the
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
Fifteen Israelis also have died since the uprising began Dec. 8,
1987.
   Shamir and the European delegates exchanged sharp words Tuesday
about Israel's peace stance and a possible European role in the
Mideast conflict.
   Shamir accused the European Community of ``adopting positions on
the substantive issues of the conflict ... which lack balance,
supporting the PLO and accepting the concept of a Palestinian
state.''
   Marco Pannella of Italy accused Shamir of refusing to make
concessions to the Palestinians. ``We're beginning to get fed up
with the fact that when you talk about peace, you do so in very
bellicose tones,'' he said.
   ``Continuing in this way, you'll be a kind of dinosaur head of
this very monolithic state of intolerance,'' Pannella said.
</TEXT>
