<FIRST>u i AM-East-West 1stLd-Writethru a0655 01-10 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0655,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats Scrambling For Agreement by Jan. 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with talks adjourned until Wednesday.
Pick up 4th pvs, `The dispute...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats on Tuesday tried to resolve a
deadlock between Greece and Turkey that threatens to block new
East-West arms talks and a landmark human rights accord before
President Reagan leaves office.
   Weary delegations from the 16 NATO and seven Warsaw Pact nations
adjourned Tuesday after five days of trying to remove the
last-minute hitch.
   They agreed to resume at 11 a.m. Wednesday, a U.S. delegation
source said on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier Tuesday, a Western diplomat said, ``If we don't have
anything this afternoon, we get very close to the time when we will
not be able to finish'' before the U.S. administration leaves office
on Jan. 20.
   The dispute between the two Balkan nations, traditionally
suspicious of each other, emerged after delegates from the East and
the West thought they had wrapped up two long years of negotiations
on new arms control talks and human rights guarantees in Europe.
   Diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Greece
surprised everybody last week by insisting that more of eastern
Turkey be included in the area covered by the new talks on reducing
conventional troops and weapons across Europe.
   Turkey had finally won agreement from the Soviet Union last week
that the port of Mersin and other parts of eastern Turkey should be
excluded from the new arms talks.
   This seemed to open up prospects for what U.S. ambassador Warren
Zimmermann in a Dec. 30 interview billed as potentially ``the most
important Europe-wide arms control negotiations ever held.''
   The talks are designed to reduce Warsaw Pact and NATO troops,
tanks and airborne forces from the Atlantic to the Ural mountains
deep inside the Soviet Union.
   They could begin as early as March, according to diplomats from
NATO and Warsaw Pact nations.
   But if the Greek-Turkish dispute is not solved by the end of this
week, the new East-West arms talks cannot be set before the Reagan
administration leaves office, diplomats say.
   The overall agreement at the 35-nation Helsinki review conference
on security and human rights in Europe also would be at risk.
   The mandate for the new arms control talks is supposed to be part
of the final document agreed on by the 35 nations at the conference,
which began work in November 1986.
   A draft of the final document was presented last week, a day
before the United States and Britain removed a major obstacle by
announcing they are willing to attend a 1991 human rights meeting in
Moscow.
   Zimmermann hailed the human rights provisions in the draft
document as ``historic,'' and indicated only minor changes were
needed.
   But the agreement would be on hold _ probably subject to U.S.
review _ if it is not adopted before Reagan leaves office and Bush
takes over, he said.
   Canada still has not agreed to the Moscow conference, and Romania
also presented 17 major objections _ rejected by diplomats
responsible for the draft _ to the human rights provisions.
   The Vienna conference includes the Soviet Union, the United
States, Canada and all European nations except for Albania. All 35
nations must agree to the final accord by consensus for it to take
effect.
   Austria has invited the foreign ministers of all 35 participating
nations to a concluding session Jan. 17-19.
</TEXT>
