<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-NaziProbe     01-10 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Nazi Probe,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hesse State Prosecutor Opens 670 New War Crimes Investigations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have begun Nazi war
crimes investigations of 670 people who the United Nations says
allegedly committed atrocities in World War II, a prosecutor said
Tuesday.
   Chief Prosecutor Christoph Schaefer told reporters at a news
conference in Frankfurt that the names were obtained from the U.N.
by West German officials who track suspected Nazi war criminals.
   Schaefer said the U.N. records, which were not made avaiable for
nearly 40 years to West German officials, contained names of people
who were not investigated previously by the West German government.
   Jochen Schroers, a spokesman for Schaefer, said authorities first
will determine ``among other things, how many of the people being
investigated are still alive.''
   ``As you know, most of them are quite old by now, and many have
probably died,'' Schroers said.
   ``Until the investigations are complete and it is determined
there is cause to file charges, I cannot release any of the names,''
he said.
   Schroers said the list included no prominent names.
   He said he did not know when the investigations would be
completed.
</TEXT>
