<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Lithuania     01-10 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Lithuania,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>50,000 in Lithuania Allowed to Rally Against Hitler-Stalin Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50,000 people in Vilnius on Tuesday freely
protested the Hitler-Stalin pact, which led to Soviet annexation of
Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia, activists reported from the
Lithuanian capital.
   In September, paramilitary forces in armored personnel carriers
attacked a similar demonstration in Vilnius.
   Tuesday's two-hour rally had government approval, and authorities
even publicized it with a brief newspaper announcement, Valdas
Analauskas, correspondent in Lithuania for the unofficial journal
Ekspress-Kronika, said by telephone from Vilnius.
   ``Police were not even visible,'' he said.
   Lithuania's conservative Communist Party chief was replaced in
October with a reformer, Algirdas Brazauskas, who attended a
conference of the grass-roots political organization People's Front
later that month.
   He also returned the Vilnius Cathedral, which had been used as a
museum since the 1950s, to the Roman Catholic Church.
   At Tuesday's rally, 20 speakers demanded Lithuanian independence
and withdrawal of ``the Soviet occupation army,'' calling the 1939
Hitler-Stalin pact a ``shameful lie,'' Analauskas said. The Baltic
nations were independent from the end of World War I until Soviet
annexation in 1940.
   The 1939 agreement ostensibly was a non-aggression treaty between
Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union, but a secret protocol provided
for the Soviets to annex Baltic states and Germany to invade Poland.
   Speakers at the demonstration Tuesday represented the League for
a Free Lithuania, the Lithuanian Democratic Party and the National
Council of Young Lithuanians, Analauskas said.
   At the September rally, police and soldiers shoved demonstrators
and beat some with rubber truncheons. They charged four times to
disperse the tens of thousands of people singing Lithuanian songs
and carrying the flag of the former independent republic.
</TEXT>
