<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Protests     01-10 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Protests,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union-Backed Workers Call for Wage Hikes After Price Increases ^With
AM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union-backed workers demanded higher pay
after consumer prices rose in the first of four waves of price
increases the government plans to impose this year, official media
reported Tuesday.
   In an open letter on Monday to Premier Miklos Nemeth, the
presidium of the Csongrad County council of trade unions in southern
Hungary protested the increases taking effect the same day, the
state news agency MTI said.
   MTI said the trade unions made it clear to the government that
``the tolerance of the population has reached a critical level.''
   On Monday, tens of thousands of workers in Szabolcs-Szatmar
County in northeastern Hungary staged a 10-minute warning strike to
protest the price increases decreed by the government.
   The price rises were caused partly by cutting state subsidies of
a vast number of consumer goods, a condition set by the
International Monetary Fund for governments seeking credits or
rescheduling arrangements.
   Hungary's total Western debt is now believed to total about $17
billion, the highest per capita in the East bloc.
   MTI also said conservative estimates indicate about one out of
every four Hungarians is poor _ nearly 2.6 million out of a
population of 10.6 million.
   In 1987, 1.9 million people, or 18 percent of the population,
lived below subsistence level, MTI quoted the Central Statistical
Office as saying.
   No figures were given for last year, but government austerity
measures, new taxes and several price rises have worsened the
problem.
   MTI said that in Budapest, the capital, 25,000 families or 6
percent had rent arrears in 1987, with their total debt amounting to
an equaivalent of $2.4 million.
   Electricity in Budapest has been cut off to an average 150
apartments a week because renters were behind on their utility
bills. The total annual debt in utility fees was $15.4 million, MTI
said.
   The news agency also said that according to figures released by
the Central People's Control Committee, up to 400,000 elderly people
in Hungary had no pension or other regular income last year.
   Regular social support is given to only 48,000 of them, the
report said, indicating that the remainder must rely on relatives or
friends.
</TEXT>
