<FIRST>u w NewPresidenttoAttendTokyoFuneral     01-10 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>New President to Attend Tokyo Funeral</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush will lead the U.S. delegation to
the funeral of the late Japanese Emperor Hirohito on Feb. 24, five
weeks after Bush is inaugurated as president, the president-elect's
spokesman announced Tuesday.
   Bush will be accompanied by his wife, Barbara, spokesman Steve
Hart said. He had no other details on the itinerary, composition of
the delegation or other travel planned by the incoming president.
   Hirohito died last Saturday of intestinal cancer at the age of
87. He was succeeded as emperor by his son, Akihito.
   The Japan trip is the first foreign travel announced for Bush,
who will be inaugurated Jan. 20.
   The announcement confirmed that the incoming administration will
continue to stress the importance of U.S. ties with Japan, described
at the State Department earlier Tuesday as the most important U.S.
bilateral relationship in the world.
   The late Japanese monarch is now known as the Emperor Showa,
using the historical name of his reign, which covered 62 years
marking Japanese military expansion, the nation's defeat in World
War II, reconciliation, reconstruction, dramatic economic growth and
new prosperity.
</TEXT>
