<FIRST>u i AM-TroopPullouts     01-10 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Troop Pullouts,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets, Cubans Withdraw</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola, AM-Afghanistan, AM-Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The departure Tuesday of the first contingent of Cuban soldiers
from Angola was the latest in a series of steps by the East bloc to
reduce some military commitments abroad.
   Here is a summary of developments Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ANGOLA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The first contingent of 450 Cuban soldiers left Angola as part of
a U.S.-mediated agreement to remove foreign forces from that African
nation and bring independence to neighboring Namibia.
   The agreement requires 3,000 Cuban soldiers to be out of Angola
by April 1 and all 50,000 to be gone in 27 months. South African
forces withdrew from southern Angola into Namibia on Aug. 22. All
but 1,500 South African soldiers are to be out of Namibia in time
for that nation's elections Nov. 1.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUNGARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In Hungary, Defense Minister Col.-Gen. Ferenc Karpati said
preparations for withdrawing some of the 62,000 Soviet Red Army
troops in Hungary were nearly complete.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev promised in a speech to the
United Nations last December to reduce military forces by half a
million in two years and pull 50,000 troops and 5,000 tanks out of
East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
   Neither Karpati nor Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz gave a
specific date, but Grosz said the Soviet pullout ``is to commence
within weeks.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>AFGHANISTAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's top envoy to Afghanistan, Yuli M. Vorontsov, said
there is ``serious danger'' the Soviets will not resume their
pullout of 50,000 soldiers remaining in Afghanistan in time to meet
the negotiated Feb. 15 deadline.
   In April 1988, the Soviets agreed to withdraw all troops and
announced last fall they had withdrawn the first half of their more
than 100,000 soldiers.
   Vorontsov's statement indicated the Kremlin may delay or freeze
its military withdrawal, but it was not clear whether it signaled a
change in Soviet intent, or was designed to pressure Moslem
guerrillas to accede to peace proposals floated by the Kremlin.
</TEXT>
