<FIRST>r i AM-PygmyFighting     01-10 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pygmy Fighting,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twenty Killed in Fighting between Pygmies and Other Tribes</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0726 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 20 people were killed in fighting
between pygmies and other ethnic groups in southwestern Uganda, the
government newspaper New Vision reported Tuesday.
   It said pygmies, complaining of discrimination, set up roadblocks
in the forest southwest of Rukingiri town and shot at non-pygmies
with bows and arrows, killing five people.
   They vanished into the forest when soldiers arrived, and members
of other tribes, angered by the army's failure to capture them,
pursued the pygmies and killed 15 with machetes, spears and clubs,
the paper said. Its report said the fighting occurred three weeks
ago.
   New Vision quoted a pygmy spokesman identified only as Mushoro as
saying: ``A pygmy living in this part of the country cannot have
land on which to settle. A pygmy cannot go to the bar and have a
beer.
   ``When someone's goat gets lost, they claim it was stolen by us.
Aren't we people like others? Why do they hate us when even some of
them have married our daughters?''
   Pygmies arrived in the 1970s from Rwanda, Uganda's southern
neighbor. Like kinsmen in neighboring Zaire, their height averages
about 3 feeet and they usually live in forests, eating meat, roots
and wild fruit.
   The paper said Mushoro was hired by the Forestry Department
because of his knowledge of the bush.
   He was quoted as saying the pgymies had called upon kinsmen in
Zaire to help fight ``enemies'' in the area about 280 miles
southwest of Kampala, capital of Uganda.
</TEXT>
