<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-10 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brutal Cold in Minnesota, Springlike in Denver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arctic air dropped temperatures to 45 degrees below zero in
Minnesota on Tuesday, the cold mark for the nation so far this
winter, while parts of the central Rockies had springlike weather.
   In northwest Minnesota, readings included 45 degrees below zero
at Roseau and 43 below zero at Warroad. As late as 11 a.m., the
temperature at Roseau was only up to 34 below zero.
   In North Dakota, the temperature fell to 32 below zero at Devils
Lake and to 31 below zero at Williston and Bismarck.
   The arctic air prevailed over the upper Mississippi Valley and
northern Plains Tuesday, but relatively mild temperatures dominated
Tuesday afternoon in western portions of the northern and central
Plains. Readings included 46 degrees at Douglas, Wyo., and 54
degrees at Denver.
   Along the eastern slopes of the Wyoming Rockies, winds gusted to
64 mph at Casper and to 52 mph at Douglas.
   A small tornado touched down just south of Salt Lake City Tuesday
morning, causing minor damage to houses, uprooting fences and
toppling trees. There were no injuries reported.
   Rain fell in southeast Virginia and eastern North Carolina, with
scattered rain from Georgia to the central Gulf Coast region.
   In the Pacific Northwest, 2 inches of snow fell at Mount Vernon,
Wash., but most coastal sections had rain. Inland, 11 inches of snow
fell overnight at Rendezvous Peak in Wyoming and more than a foot
was reported in Snoqualmie Pass in Washington's Cascades.
   Snow also fell in the northern Great Lakes region. Heaviest
snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST was 4 inches at
Pellston, Mich.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 24 below
zero at Roseau, Minn., to 83 degrees at Fort Myers, Fla. The low in
the nation Tuesday morning was 45 degrees below zero at Roseau.
   For Wednesday, the National Weather Service forecast light snow
over much of the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern half of the
Great Plains, the central Rockies and the central Plateau region.
Snow showers were predicted to be scattered over the northern
Rockies and rain showers were to be scattered across southern
California. Showers and thunderstorms should reach from eastern
Texas across Louisiana to southern Arkansas. Rain was forecast to
occur over much of Missouri and from Mississippi to portions of the
Carolinas. Widely scattered rain showers were forecast over Florida.
   High temperatures will be in the single digits and teens from
northeast Montana across much of the Dakotas and Minnesota to
northern portions of Wisconsin and Michigan. Temperatures should
reach the 50s and 60s from portions of California across the desert
Southwest, much of New Mexico, the southern Plains, lower
Mississippi and Tennessee valleys to Georgia and the Carolinas.
Temperatures should reach the 70s and 80s over the Florida
peninsula. Over much of the rest of the nation highs were expected
in the 20s, 30s and 40s.
</TEXT>
