<FIRST>r i AM-Nazi-Refugee     01-10 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazi-Refugee,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadians in Furor Over Refugee Plea of Ex-Nazi Mouthpiece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His lawyer said Tuesday that Vladimir Sokolov
faced death if denied refugee status, but a major Jewish
organization argued Canada should not be a haven for ``Nazi
collaborators ... fleeing U.S. justice.''
   Sokolov, 75, a former Yale University lecturer, was found this
week to have fled to Canada after being stripped of U.S. citizenship
in 1986 and threatened with deportation when his World War II Nazi
propagandist background was uncovered.
   Immigration authorities reported that Sokolov arrived in Canada
last March and later applied for refugee status, claiming his life
would be in danger if he was forced to return to his native Soviet
Union.
   Roger White, a spokesman for the federal Immigration Department,
said in a phone interview from Ottawa that Sokolov ``appeared at an
immigration center in Montreal in August and indicated he wished to
make a refugee claim. ... He'll be processed as a backlog claimant
and he'll eventually appear before a panel which will hear his
case.''
   Sokolov's lawyer, Julius Grey, said his client cannot be sent
back to the United States because he is no longer an American
citizen. U.S. authorities said Sokolov concealed his Nazi past when
he entered the United States in 1951 as a displaced person.
   ``The United States doesn't want him,'' Grey was quoted by the
Canadian Press as saying in an interview. ``I'm sure they'll say no.
And if they say yes it'd only be for the purpose of removing him to
the Soviet Union,'' where he could be executed.
   ``According to their law he collaborated with the enemy in
wartime so it's a serious matter. But we just don't return people
for that reason. ...
   ``Treason is not something that we can allow other countries to
enforce within Canada.''
   The news agency quoted Jack Silverstone, national executive
director for the Canadian Jewish Congress, which represents over
300,000 Jews in Canada, as saying in an interview, ``Canada cannot
continue to be a haven for Nazi collaborators who are fleeing U.S.
justice.
   ``Had he indicated that (Nazi) activity to the U.S. authorities
when he applied he would not have been eligible for a visa.
   ``We regard this as an abuse of the refugee process and ... we
obviously would hope that the Canadian authorities would take prompt
action and have him returned to the United States where he faces
U.S. proceedings.''
   Sokolov failed to appear at a U.S. deportation hearing in July in
Hartford, Conn.
   From 1942-44, Sokolov was a writer-editor on a Russian-language
newspaper published by the German army in his hometown of Orel, 210
miles south of Moscow. Anti-Semitic articles appeared under his name.
   He went to the United States in 1951, became a citizen in 1957
and in 1959 began lecturing on Russian language and Soviet dissident
literature at Yale. Yale's student paper later found out about his
wartime activities and he quit his job. U.S. officials later began
proceedings against him.
   Grey said Sokolov is in poor health and is staying in a house in
Montreal. He would not reveal the address.
</TEXT>
