<DOCNO> AP890110-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AlteredResume     01-10 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Altered Resume,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials: City Manager Got Hired With Phony Resumes, Bogus References</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Donald James said he was suspicious
of Carl Keyser Jr. shortly after Keyser took over as city
administrator of the southeast Alaska town of Kake.
   ``I could never trust him,'' James said Tuesday. ``I even told
him myself. I told him there's something there that's just not
right.''
   James' suspicions proved correct.
   ``Nearly every aspect of his resume was not true,'' District
Attorney Mark Ells said.
   Officials filed a first-degree theft charge against Keyser last
week, alleging Keyser falsified his resume and obtained about
$28,000 in salary, moving, travel and other work-related expenses
from the town.
   Keyser, a Huntington, W.Va., native, was being held Tuesday in
lieu of $10,000 bail at the jail in Petersburg, south of Kake.
   The City Council hired Keyser in early October based on glowing
recommendations from references on his impressive, four-page resume.
   Two months later, officials learned Kake was just the latest and
most remote stop in Keyser's cross-country government career, a
career officials say was based on phony resumes and bogus reference
calls.
   Kake is a fishing and timber town of 665 residents, mostly
Tlingit Indians, about 75 miles south of Juneau on the northern tip
of Kupreanof Island. It is about as far as Keyser could have gone
from his last job, a six-day stint as city manager of Pikeville,
Ky., and remain in North America.
   Keyser left the Kentucky post in August after the news media
uncovered discrepancies in his resume. Kake officials hired him in
October, unaware he was wanted on a fugitive warrant from Pikeville.
   They also did not know Keyser had pleaded guilty last January to
a misdemeanor perjury charge for lying in sworn statements while
applying for police chief in Oak Hill, Fla.
   Among the references Keyser listed on his resumes was Al Haines,
city manager of Beaumont, Texas. Haines said he knew little about
Keyser and did not recall Keyser asking him to be a reference, nor
did Kake officials call him.
   James said he called the references listed on the resume, but he
now thinks the people answering the calls were impostors arranged by
Keyser.
   ``It seems like it was set up,'' he said.
   Keyser, 34, declined a request for an interview. However, in a
tearful interview two weeks ago with Petersburg radio station KFSK,
he maintained his innocence and suggested he was a victim of a
conspiracy in Pikeville.
   ``It's a situation where the press and some of the officials
there want to make some type of example of me,'' he said.
   Pikeville charged Keyser with theft by deception for failure to
reimburse the city for $697 in travel expenses. He said he would
have returned the money had officials asked.
   Keyser's resume listed master's and bachelor's degrees in public
administration from La Salle University in Philadelphia. He also
listed experience as a consultant to the International City Managers
Association and the International Association of Chiefs of Police.
   Officials say there is no record that Keyser attended the
university or worked for the associations. In October, the city
managers' group issued a warning about Keyser in its newsletter,
urging members to investigate applicants' resumes.
   It was that warning that led Kake officials to investigate. He
was fired and arrested on theft charges in December.
   James said many were suspicious soon after Keyser took the
$44,000-a-year administrator's job. After the City Council
authorized Keyser to buy a residence for him, his wife and four
daughters, he bought a luxurious $66,000 double-wide mobile home
that was more than the council expected.
   He aroused further suspicions by buying two rifles and ammunition
with city funds and refusing to publicly release his resume,
authorities said. More than 200 residents signed petitions asking
for his removal.
   ``Carl just seemed to be living beyond our means,'' resident Mike
Jackson said. ``A lot of people were concerned about that because
the city has had real financial problems.''
</TEXT>
