<DOCNO> AP890110-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HepatitisDetection     01-10 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hepatitis Detection,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher Says Hepatitis Strain Eludes Screening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to a third of those who contract non-A,
non-B hepatitis may be infected with mutant strains of hepatitis B
that elude blood donor screening, an expert on the virus reported
Tuesday.
   Girish N. Vyas, professor of laboratory medicine at the
University of California at San Francisco and head of the
Transfusion Research Program, based his finding on a study of blood
donors on the Italian island of Sardinia.
   Non-A, non-B is a catch-all term for any hepatitis that can't be
identified as A or B. Officials at blood banks around the country
say at least 3 to 5 percent of blood product recipients in the
United States get hepatitis; 90 percent of the post-transfusion
hepatitis is non-A, non-B.
   Chronic hepatitis is primarily B and non-A, non-B. It is the
major cause of liver disease around the world and the main reason
for liver transplants.
   The study showed two of 618 donors had no immunologic or other
markers to indicate hepatitis B infection, although they had genes
from the virus in their blood. Only one of them had antibodies to
hepatitis B core proteins and would have been screened out in the
United States.
   The research was detailed in Tuesday's edition of the journal
Blood.
   Vyas said the mutant hepatitis B strains apparently make altered
surface proteins that can't be recognized by the body's immune
system and so they don't stimulate production of antibodies against
it.
   Current blood screening tests for hepatitis B don't recognize the
altered proteins and can't detect the B-like virus.
   American blood banks also screen for the presence of antibodies
to proteins in the core of the virus, and for high levels of the
enzyme ALT for signs of liver damage. But some mutant hepatitis B
viruses also fail to stimulate antibodies to core proteins, so they
can be detected only by time-consuming DNA analysis tests looking
directly for hepatitis B genes.
   Doctors quoted in last month's journal Lancet said there was a
test to screen for the non-A, non-B hepatitis, but it takes at least
12 hours.
   UCSF spokesman Robert Sanders also said there are other tests
that look for indications of related problems. But he said the test
mentioned by doctors in Lancet are too expensive and time-consuming.
   Vyas is working on developing a test for the mutant strains,
Sanders said.
   Sanders said that all the evidence points to the mutant strains
seen in the Sardinian study also existing in the United States.
   Vyas participated in the Sardinian study along with colleagues at
the University of Cagliari. The study was supported by a Transfusion
Medicine Program project grant by the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute of the National Institutes of Health.
   Vyas first suggested in 1981 at the International Symposium on
Viral Hepatitis in New York that genetic mutants of hepatitis B
could be responsible for some cases of non-A, non-B.
   He and Dr. Herbert Perkins, director of San Francisco's Irwin
Memorial Blood Bank, originally observed non-A, non-B
post-transfusion hepatitis in San Francisco as early as 1973. Their
observations were published as preliminary evidence in 1982 and in a
definitive report involving a Sardinian study in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
