<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-Chemicals 1stLd-Writethru   01-10 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Chemicals, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0764,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germany, Italy Say Evidence Lacking; Expert Says Time Running Out
To Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs to ADD that export laws are for chemical
and nuclear technology, quote. Pick up 14th pvs, `The Italian...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chemical Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday said it
lacked evidence backing U.S. allegations West German companies
helped Libya build a chemical weapons plant, but it proposed tougher
export laws for chemical and nuclear techology.
   Italy, Libya's biggest trading partner, said it still has no
proof the Libyan plant can make chemical weapons. Libya says it will
make pharmaceuticals.
   But an Israeli expert said the plant in Rabta, 60 miles southwest
of the Libyan capital of Tripoli, is near completion and time is
running out to destroy it before it starts producing poison gas.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, in an interview with a
leading West German newspaper, Die Welt, was quoted as saying
Tuesday that he was disturbed by the handling of the U.S.
accusations.
   ``I think it's unbearable if someone puts the Germans in the
defendant's docket without us having the possibility of seeing the
evidence. That is not how friends treat each other,'' Die Welt
quoted Kohl as saying in an interview to appear in the paper's
Wednesday editions.
   Kohl told his Cabinet on Tuesday the government will continue to
pursue any evidence linking West German firms to the Libyan plant,
said chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost.
   Ost said a group of German experts will fly to the United States
on Wednesday to ``exchange information over this issue with American
experts.'' He released no details on the participants or the planned
talks.
   Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann unveiled a new package of
measures aimed at cracking down on anyone who tries to evade the
country's export control laws.
   ``In the sensitive areas of chemical and nuclear technologies we
will be strengthening our control methods with more qualified people
and through the doubling of penalties,'' Haussmann told reporters.
   ``No German should be allowed to participate in activities in
other countries that are an endangerment to peace.''
   The new package, subject to approval by Parliament, calls for
raising the maximum fine for violations of the export law from
$277,000 to $555,000 and the maximum prison sentence from three
years to five.
   In a related development, a high-ranking government official
indicated a West German company had planned to export chemical
equipment ``components'' to Libya but that the deliveries would not
be allowed if deemed illegal.
   ``It has been ensured that there will be no rash deliveries
without examination,'' said Lorenz Schomerus, head of foreign
economic policies at the Economics Ministry. He refused to name the
company or identify the ``components.''
   West Germany says Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr and the Hamburg-based
Pen Tao medical material company have been cleared of any wrongdoing.
   The Italian government said Tuesday it has not yet received
conclusive evidence that the Libyan plant can produce chemical
weapons.
   Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti and Defense Minister Valerio
Zanone said the government is still seeking ``all the elements''
about the nature of the factory in the former Italian colony.
   Andreotti stressed that if the U.S. accusations are true, ``We
will not hesitate to condemn (Libya) and take the necessary
consequent steps in our relations (with Tripoli).''
   An Israeli expert said Tuesday the United States will have to
bomb Libya's Rabta plant soon if it wants to stop leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi from stockpiling chemical weapons.
   President Reagan in December said he was considering bombing the
plant.
   ``They will have to do it as soon as possible because the plant
now is reaching a critical situation. It is on the eve of starting
production,'' Aharon Levran, a former deputy chief of military
intelligence told a government-sponsored briefing.
   Once production started, the Libyans could begin storing the
weapons in despersed locations that would make it harder to knock
out Libya's chemical weaspons stock, said Levran, co-author of The
Middle East Military Balance, an annual study produced by Tel Aviv
University's Jaffee Center For Strategic Studies.
</TEXT>
