<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan-Farewell 1stLd-Writethru a0758 01-10 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Farewell, 1stLd-Writethru, a0758,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to show that networks will carry Reagan speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan to Make Final Speech Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will deliver his farewell
address, billed as a ``very personal'' review of his presidency, by
television from the Oval Office on Wednesday night.
   The speech is scheduled for 9 p.m. EST and will be carried live
by the television networks. It is expected to last about 20 minutes,
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday.
   He said Reagan has spent several hours working on it this week.
   ``We expect it to be a very personal kind of look at what
President Reagan tried to do, and what he sees as his
accomplishments, and the problems ahead,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``It will be an opportunity for him to talk directly to the
American people as he has done so often in the last eight years.''
   A few of Reagan's notable previous speeches from the Oval Office
included:
   _ July 27, 1981, in which he used charts and a pointer to make
his point that the administration's tax reduction plan was more fair
than that proposed by the Democrats in Congress. He prevailed, with
Congress passing a plan along the lines he had proposed.
   _ March, 23, 1983, in which he took some of his own key advisers
by surprise by announcing he was ordering a study of the then
little-known concept of building a system to defend against missile
attack. The idea came to be known as Star Wars and became a subject
of domestic dispute and of contention with the Soviet Union.
   _ Jan. 28, 1986, often cited as one of his most memorable, in
which, within a few hours of the explosion that killed the seven
members of the space shuttle Challenger crew, he mourned their loss
but vowed that the U.S. space program would go on.
   _ Nov. 13, 1986, generally regarded as one of his least
persuasive, in which he tried to deflect criticism of his
administration's sales of arms to Iran, denying they represented an
attempt to swap arms for American hostages.
   Reagan, a former movie actor and radio announcer, came to the
White House better equipped with television-related skills than any
of his predecessors.
   In addition to his career as an entertainer, he had made a splash
in 1964 with a speech on behalf of Republican presidential candidate
Barry Goldwater that set him on the way to a new career in politics.
   Wednesday night's speech will follow a tradition of farewell
addresses that has included many previous presidents, from George
Washington to Jimmy Carter.
   Washington's farewell address, attacking ``the spirit of party''
and warning against foreign entanglements, has become a classic
which is still read annually in Congress on the first president's
birthday.
   The most celebrated previous presidential address of the
television era is Dwight Eisenhower's on Jan. 17, 1961, warning
against ``the acquisition of unwarranted influence, whether sought
or unsought, by the military-industrial complex.''
   Lyndon Johnson and Gerald Ford, both former congressional
leaders, chose to make their final speeches in the form of State of
the Union addresses to Congress, as some other presidents have done.
   Carter spoke from the Oval Office on Jan. 14, 1981, six days
before Reagan took office, promising his successor his support ``to
the very limits of conscience and conviction'' and warning of the
need to reduce the ``horrifying danger'' of nuclear arms stockpiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
