<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0722 01-10 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0722,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Finds One Engine Burned, Other Shut Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to ADD that left engine remained in operation
before crash. Pick up 3rd pvs, `Aviation experts...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators said Tuesday that one engine of a
crashed Boeing 737 had fire damage, while the other was inexplicably
shut down before the aircraft plunged into a highway embankment,
killing 44 people.
   The pilot of the British Midland Airways jet told ground control
the fire was in the undamaged right engine, which was shut off,
Transport Secretary Paul Channon said. The fire was in the left
engine, but it remained in operation before the crash.
   Aviation experts thought it unlikely the captain could have
confused the two engines, and one pilot said the fire warning system
may have been at fault.
   Asked on Independent Television News whether pilot error might be
involved, Channon said: ``I don't rule that out, but ... it would be
unwise of me to speculate on that until we've got more information.''
   He also said he would not rule out sabotage, but he said it was
not ``very likely.''
   The jet, flying from London to Belfast, Northern Ireland, crashed
beside England's main M1 north-south highway Sunday night after
reporting engine trouble. It undershot the runway while attempting
an emergency landing at East Midlands Airport in central England,
but 82 passengers and crew, including pilot Kevin Hunt, survived
with injuries.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said investigators believe they
know what caused the disaster, but were not yet ready to publish
their conclusions. There was no word on what caused the fire.
   Reporting to Parliament and then speaking on TV, Channon said the
pilot reported an engine on fire, and when asked by ground control
which one, replied ``starboard.''
   But when the engines were examined at the crash site, it turned
out that the starboard engine had been shut down before the crash
and investigators found no evidence in it of a fire or mechanical
flaw.
   The port engine did contain fire damage, said chief investigator
Eddie Trimble.
   He told reporters the starboard engine had been shut down not
shortly before the crash but ``at a previous point in the flight.''
He said it would be premature to speculate about the reason before
the engines were stripped down for laboratory scrutiny.
   Capt. John Guntrip of the Guild of Air Pilots said it was
``highly improbable'' that the pilot confused the two engines
because the pilot and co-pilot ``are trained very carefully to
monitor each other's actions.''
   Asked if the system could go wrong, Guntrip said: ``It is
possible. It has been known in the past. There have very
occasionally been false fire warnings on aircraft.''
   Another guild member, Group Capt. John Tritton, said, ``I find it
unbelievable'' that the pilot identified the wrong engine on fire.
   ``When a fire occurs in an engine, the master caution light comes
on, there is audio warning and there is a light in the handle, the
fire handle for that particular engine, indicating which engine it
is,'' he told BBC-TV.
   Ham radio operator Mervyn Solloway, who picked up cockpit
transmissions shortly before the crash, has said he heard the pilot
report engine trouble, then say it was under control.
   But later, he says, he heard a frantic voice say, ``We've got
problems with the other engine.''
   Aviation experts say the odds on double engine failure on a
two-engined Boeing are astronomical. They theorized blame could lie
with impure fuel, faulty maintenancing, an explosion in the engine's
combustion chamber or a mechanical fault.
   The plane broke into three main sections. Heavy lifting equipment
was moved to the site to remove debris.
   The ``black boxes,'' which record cockpit flight data and
conversations, were taken on Monday night to the government Air
Accidents Investigation Branch at Farnborough, outside London, for
analysis.
   Police and soldiers scoured the area for wreckage fragments.
Boeing officials flew here and joined British investigators.
   A 20-foot-high scaffold and tarpaulin were erected to screen the
wreck from highway traffic.
   Investigators will interview the crew members, who survived.
   Pilot Hunt, 43, broke his back and it was uncertain whether he
would walk again, doctors said Tuesday. He has been hailed as a hero
for managing to miss the town of Kegworth and avoid landing on
highway traffic.
   Channon said the three other Boeing 737-400s operated by British
airlines were grounded.
   In the United States, Cincinnati lawyer Jim Helmer is suing the
airplane engine's maker, alleging the engine contains improperly
tested parts. Helmer identified the parts as timer valves, but told
The Associated Press he didn't know if they could have caused the
crash.
   The CFM56 engines were made jointly by U.S.-based General
Electric and SNECMA of France. GE spokesman Dwight Weber said Monday
night that timer valve failure would not have caused an engine to go
out.
</TEXT>
