<FIRST>u i AM-Greece-Terrorism     01-10 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Terrorism,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>DA Issues Arrest Warrant In Cruise Ship Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district attorney issued an arrest
warrant for an Arab accused of taking part in a cruise ship attack
in July that left nine dead, a spokesman for his office said Tuesday.
   Piraeus District Attorney Giorgos Vlassis issued the arrest
warrant for Mohammed Adnan Zozad, 21, on Monday, said the spokesman.
   But a report drafted by port authority officials and submitted to
the district attorney on Dec. 23 said Zozad, a Lebanese national,
was killed by an explosion aboard the liner, the City of Poros.
   Police said after the attack that they found remains of a leg
they believe belonged to Zozad.
   The spokesman did not explain why the district attorney issued an
arrest warrant for a person believed dead.
   Ninety-eight others were injured in the July 11 gun and grenade
attack as the ship steamed toward a suburban Athens marina after a
one-day cruise through the Saronic Gulf islands.
   A Frenchman who died in the attack and was later implicated in
the assault against the passengers is not mentioned in the arrest
warrant, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The port authority report said Laurent Vigneron, 23, was one of
two men identified by witnesses as firing a weapon on the ship. It
did not include any other evidence linking Vigneron to the attack.
   Greece's merchant marine minister said eight eyewitnesses
testified the Frenchman was one of the attackers.
   The charge triggered a diplomatic row with France, which denied
Vigneron was a terrorist and said he had been on vacation.
   Greek police have identified four Arab terrorists involved in the
attack. They named the ringleader as Hejab Jaballa, a Libyan
passport holder later identified as Mohammed Khadar.
   Khadar, 40, the alleged operations chief for the Abu Nidal
terrorist organization, is said to have died in a car bomb that
apparently detonated prematurely at an Athens suburban marina a few
hours before the cruise ship was to dock.
   Authorities believe the attackers wanted to free an alleged Abu
Nidal terrorist held by Greece and deported to Libya last month.
Abdel Osama Zomar was to have been extradited to Italy for his
alleged involvement in an October 1982 attack against Rome's main
synagogue that killed a 2-year-old boy.
   Zomar had been jailed in Greece since his November 1982 arrest at
the Greek-Turkish border driving a car loaded with explosives.
</TEXT>
