<SECOND>AM-Israel-Mossad,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Says Head Of Intelligence To Be Replaced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Israel's Mossad intelligence agency
will be replaced within several days after more than six years in
the post, Israel radio reported Tuesday.
   The director, whose name was not given in keeping with security
regulations, will be replaced by another senior Mossad official or
by a ``senior personality from outside that organization,'' the
radio reported.
   It said that during his years in service the intelligence agency
suffered some failures, among them the discovery of false passports
used by Mossad operatives in West Germany and the expulsion of
Mossad agents from Britain several months ago.
   Before taking effect, the new appointment must be approved by
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of the hard-line Likud bloc, and
Finance Minister Shimon Peres of the left-leaning Labor Party.
   It was one of the conditions in the agreement between the two
parties to form a coalition government, the radio said.
   The report followed a Supreme Court ruling Tuesday allowing an
Israeli newspaper to publish an article that criticized the outgoing
Mossad chief and stated that he is to be replaced in the near future.
   But the Supreme Court upheld the military censorship order that
the Tel Aviv-based weekly Ha-Ir (The City) cancel all descriptions
of the Mossad chief in person.
   The article, to be published on Friday, was first submitted to
the military censor last August and has since been rewritten four
times, the local news agency Itim said.
