<DOCNO> AP890110-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     01-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>`For Dear Life,' A New Play by Susan Miller, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``We're a generation completely confused about
our psyches,'' confesses an aging baby boomer in Susan Miller's
tedious new play, ``For Dear Life.'' Not only about their psyches,
but about cholesterol, calcium, oat bran muffins and human
existence, too.
   These are some of the many topics touched on in Miller's numbing
drama of self-absorption that opened Tuesday at the New York
Shakespeare Festival Public Theater.
   The play examines the marriage of Jake, a disc jockey who loves
and plays the pop standards of the 1930s and '40s, and Catherine, a
film critic who thinks she ought to be doing some ``real work''
instead _ like hauling water. Then she could ``fall into bed at
night with legitimate fatigue.''
   Baby boomers and the yuppie generation _ not exacty the most
popular people in America _ can be treated with some intelligence,
wit and even sympathy on stage. Two recent examples include
``Eastern Standard'' by Richard Greenberg and ``The Heidi
Chronicles,'' Wendy Wasserstein's look at one woman's odyssey
through feminism and beyond. Their much more carefully defined
characters may not be likable, but at least they are believable,
interesting and occasionally funny.
   Miller doesn't have much luck with her creations or their
conversation. Her dialogue is arch and more than a tad pretentious.
``I like your marriage. It works for me,'' admits Catherine's best
friend, a would-be filmmaker.
   Unfortunately, the marriage doesn't work for the playwright or
the audience. Miller tells her tale in a strange manner, setting the
play's first act in the present, and the other two at various points
in the future. Nobody appears to age and the sets don't change,
although in Act 2, Sam, the couple's 16-year-old son, appears. It's
an awkward device.
   The son isn't any more interesting that his parents, particularly
in Stephen Mailer's irritating and unconvincing performance. None of
the actors has a particularly successful time at it, and the rest of
the cast includes such usually fine performers as Laila Robins, Tony
Shalhoub, Christine Estabrook and Joseph Lambie. They are stranded
here, and Norman Rene's static direction doesn't help.
   The play has several fleeting moments of pleasure, particularly
when Jake is lost in reverie with those classic pop tunes he plays
on his radio show. When the voice of Fred Astaire or Ethel Waters or
Ella Fitzgerald fills the theater, you keep wishing that Jake would
just spin those wonderful old records and forget about ``For Dear
Life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CorneaSales     01-10 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cornea Sales,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Accused of Plot to Steal Corneas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people are accused of obtaining corneas
from 47 corpses, then selling them for profit as far away as Saudi
Arabia in a case a prosecutor describes as ``bizarre and perhaps
macabre.''
   In opening arguments in a Hillsborough Circuit Court trial
Monday, a prosecutor charged that two former employees of the
Florida Regional Bone and Tissue Bank Inc. sold corneas supplied to
Florida Regional through another eye bank, University Ophthalmic
Services Inc., set up by their wives.
   Robert and Irene Fisher of Hillsborough County and Robert and
Gailya Grant of Largo, in Pinellas County, each are charged with 47
counts of grand theft and one count of conspiracy. Also charged with
conspiracy is Charles Lee Gloss, who worked at Florida Regional, a
private, non-profit business.
   A sixth defendant, Judith Sawyer-Ackerman, pleaded no contest to
48 charges Friday and agreed to testify against the others. She will
be sentenced next month.
   Medical examiners supplying the corneas _ the transparent tissues
that cover and protect the eyeball _ assumed they were going to
Florida Regional, but the corneas were sold by University
Ophthalmic, many to a Saudi Arabian hospital for a $650 processing
fee each, according to prosecutors.
   Assistant State Attorney Judy Hoyer told jurors in her opening
presentation Monday that University Ophthalmic was ``the entity they
created in order to steal.''
   But a defense attorney told jurors that his clients ran a
non-profit business, and are in trouble because Florida Regional did
not like the competition.
   ``From the evidence, you're going to see Florida Regional getting
mad at University Ophthalmic and these people because Florida
Regional thought they were stabbing them in the back,'' said the
Fishers' attorney, Marc Lubet.
   Robert Fisher, 40, Robert Grant, 45, and Gloss, 29, worked for
Florida Regional in March 1986 when Irene Fisher, 38, and Gailya
Grant, 45, founded University Ophthalmic. Robert Fisher was Florida
Regional's director and Robert Grant was the program director in
Pinellas County.
   The Pinellas County Medical Examiner's Office was the University
Ophthalmic's best source for corneas.
   Directors at the medical examiner's office dealt exclusively with
Florida Regional and didn't suspect the corneas were being sold
instead of being turned over to the legitimate organization, the
state said.
   Gloss discovered the operation and confronted Robert Fisher, his
boss at Florida Regional, Hoyer said. Gloss accepted a check for
$200 and didn't tell anyone about the scheme, she said.
   The trial continued Tuesday and was expected to last for several
days.
   Florida Regional and the Florida West Coast Organ Procurement
Foundation Inc. sued the Fishers, Grants and Gloss in March 1987, a
month before the state filed criminal charges. The suit has not been
resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
