<HEAD>Sergeant's Trial Begins In Case Of Abandoned Marine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with top officers being reassigned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine sergeant pleaded innocent
Tuesday to military charges stemming from the abandonment of a
19-year-old Marine who died after being left in a California desert.
   Lance Cpl. Jason Rother was posted alone as a nighttime guide on
Aug. 30 for trucks carrying Marines to a major training exercise in
the Mojave Desert at the Marine base at Twentynine Palms, Calif. He
was mistakenly left behind at the conclusion of the exercise.
   The Minneapolis native was reported missing 40 hours after he was
last seen, and his skeletal remains were found Dec. 4 _ three months
and three major searches later.
   Sgt. Christopher P. Clyde is charged with dereliction of duty and
with disobeying an order not to allow special liberties without
prior approval of the battalion commander.
   He is accused of granting a special liberty to Sgt. Thomas
Turnell, Rother's squad leader, who is scheduled for a Jan. 24
court-martial on charges of dereliction of duty and unauthorized
absence in the case.
   Jury selection began later Tuesday. The presiding judge, Maj.
Kent Smith, estimated the trial will last two to three days.
   Company commander Capt. Michael Henderson and Rother's platoon
leader, 1st Lt. Christopher Johnson, were relieved of their commands
and reprimanded. Those officers are not facing courts-martial.
   Col. J.W. Ripley, the commanding officer of the 2nd Marine
Division, announced Tuesday that Lt. Col. E.J. Robeson, the
commanding officer of the 3rd Battalion, and Major T.L. Holm, the
3rd Battalion's executive officer, would be reassigned. The
announcement said the reassignments came after an investigation of
the death of Rother, who was in the 3rd Battalion.
</TEXT>
