<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-UnionArrests 3rdLd-Writethru a0786 01-10 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Union Arrests, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0786,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pemex Union Leader Arrested After Shootout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with additional arrests, more charges
to be filed, attorney general's news conference, background. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers stormed the fortified home of the oil
workers' union chief Tuesday, fought a gun battle and arrested him
and 17 other leaders of the nation's strongest and allegedly most
corrupt union, officials said.
   A federal agent was killed in the gunfight between security
forces and Joaquin Hernandez Galicia's bodyguards in the oil city of
Ciudad Madero in northeastern Mexico, Attorney General Enrique
Alvarez del Castillo said.
   Union members, among Mexico's highest paid workers, walked off
the job at six of the nation's nine oil refineries after the raid.
   ``This is not an attack on a union,'' Alvarez told a news
conference. ``It is the prosecution of crime committed by
individuals.''
   ``We had to move to clean up things,'' a presidential source said
on condition of anonymity. ``They had a plan to destabilize the
country by taking over some of the oil installations. They knew this
was coming.''
   Hernandez Galicia's power stems from the symbiotic relationship
between the unions and the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which
has ruled Mexico for 60 years. It is a relationship in which power
and profit are exchanged for votes and peace in the workplace.
   Challenging the union leader, who commands the loyalty of
hundreds of thousands of workers, is a bold move for President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari and a test of his vow to modernize
politics and the economy.
   The government news agency Notimex said soldiers sealed off the
area around Hernandez Galicia's home, fired into the air and blew
down the door with a bazooka shot.
   Alvarez said 16 more people were arrested later on illegal
weapons charges.
   He said police confiscated 200 Uzi submachine guns, 16 other
high-caliber weapons and 250,000 rounds of ammunition at Hernandez
Galicia's house.
   The attorney general said the Treasury Department had
investigated Hernandez Galicia and his associates for months and
that additional charges of murder and tax evasion would be filed.
   The union's nominal leader, Secretary-General and former Sen.
Salvador Barragan Camacho, was also wanted for questioning, Alvarez
reported.
   Salinas met with his defense minister, attorney general, navy
secretary and labor secretary ``to take measures to guarantee the
security of the Pemex installations and the supply of gasoline,''
the source reported.
   An estimated 6,000 oil workers and their supporters quit work in
Mexico City, headquarters of the state-owned oil monopoly Petroleos
Mexicanos, called Pemex. They marched to Zocalo Plaza shouting
``Freedom for Joaquin!''
   They were joined by busloads of workers from the refinery in
Tula, to the north, and more from other cities, workers said. Buses
arrived all afternoon carrying workers to demand freedom for ``La
Quina,'' the diminutive by which Hernandez Galicia is known.
   The 15,000-strong workforce at the Pemex refinery and
petrochemicals plant in the northern border city of Reynosa also
struck, said Gerasuro Salinas, editor of the newspaper El Manana.
Troops guarded installations but Salinas described the situation as
calm.
   Pemex accounts for 40 percent of Mexico's revenue and about half
the federal budget. It has 180,000 employees, most of them union
members.
   All 8,000 workers struck at the Pemex refinery in Salina Cruz in
Oaxaca state on the Pacific coast, said Lorenzo Jaime, editor at the
newspaper El Imparcial de Oaxaca. The refinery processes about
70,000 barrels of crude daily and serves as embarkation point for
crude shipments to the Far East, he said.
   Notimex said partial shutdowns hit refineries in Ciudad Madero,
Salamanca, La Cangrejera and Cadereyta. Troops occupied Pemex
facilities in Villahermosa, capital of oil-rich Tabasco state in the
southeast.
   Pemex said production was not affected in the Bay of Campeche,
Notimex reported. The oil monopoly appealed to the public to avoid
panic buying of gasoline, saying it had adequate inventories to meet
demand.
   Augustin Jimenez, editor of the newspaper Sol de Tampico, said
oil workers blocked all major highways leading into Tampico, but no
violence was reported.
   Soldiers occupied Pemex installations at Tampico and Ciudad
Madero, 220 miles northeast of Mexico City and 250 miles south of
Brownsville, Texas.
   At Pemex headquarters, spokesman Francisco Casanova Alvarez
reported work stoppages at Mexico City's Azcapotzalco refinery and
the refinery at Tula. At least two refineries continued operating,
he said.
   Former union Secretary-General Jose Sosa was among those arrested
with Hernandez Galicia, the attorney general's office said.
   Fidel Velazquez, head of the Mexican Labor Federation, the
country's largest, told a news conference: ``I am worried,
disgusted. ... I can't allow this to happen in Mexico.''
   A federation statement described the arrest as ``arbitrary and
with excessive display of force.''
   ``We reject what has happened because, if is not corrected, it
could open a stage in the life of the country no one wants: the
stage of authoritarianism that could lead, in turn, to anarchy and
reactionary violence,'' it said.
   Velazquez met with Salinas later to pledge his support and
guarantee labor peace, the presidential source said.
   A veteran journalist in Tampico said Hernandez Galicia declared
the union would act if government-owned petrochemical industries
were sold to private owners. Salinas, who took office Dec. 1, has
said he will continue a program of selling or closing unprofitable
and non-strategic state industries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
