<HEAD>Masked Gunmen Rob Writer-Producer of $500,000 in Jewelry and Cash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to add background on Alesia, UPDATE with
quotes on beating, names of other victims. Picks up 6th graf, `The butler...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wealthy writer-producer was beaten
and robbed of $500,000 in jewelry and cash by four masked gunmen who
tied up his butler and the servant's wife and waited hours for him
to arrive, police said Tuesday.
   Frank Alesia, 45, needed 37 stitches to close head wounds
suffered when the gunmen pounded his head on the floor to force him
to say where valuables were located, said Lt. Robert Curtis.
   The gunmen on Monday night stole a 1983 Toyota Tercel when they
made their getaway. The robbers wore ski masks and gloves, Curtis
said.
   Alesia wrote for the ``Laverne and Shirley'' television show, was
a producer and writer for the ``Captain Kangaroo'' show and has been
associated with the production of 16 feature films, said business
manager Ralph Goldman.
   Goldman did not know the titles of the features.
   Alesia, whose wife was out of town at the time, did not struggle
with the gunmen, the business manager said. ``It was just a
gratuitous beating,'' Goldman said.
   The other victims were identified as Wayne Welch, 41, the butler,
and his wife, Judith, 41, Curtis said.
   The butler took the dog for a walk Monday evening and when he
returned was confronted by a masked man who put a gun to his head,
police said. The masked man was joined by three other gunmen, Curtis
said.
   Alesia came home about 10 p.m. and was confronted by a gunman at
the door.
   Alesia eventually told the gunmen where the valuables were,
Curtis said. Most of the estimated $500,000 loss was in jewels.
   The robbers left shortly after 11 p.m. but it apparently took
some time for the victims to free themselves. Police were alerted by
a screaming woman who called on the emergency line at 12:24 a.m.
Tuesday.
