<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Newman Adv16   01-10 0988</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Newman, Adv 16,1018</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Monday Jan. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Don't Take Randy Newman Too Seriously</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warning: The opinions expressed on Randy Newman's
records should not be taken too seriously.
   So don't be too offended when Newman urges the United States to
``drop the big one'' on its allies, or informs us that God considers
the human race to be little more than a source of amusement.
   He doesn't really mean it.
   But if you're a little sensitive, don't listen too carefully to
his new album, ``Land of Dreams,'' because you probably won't like
the song in which Newman abandons his wife and kids and tells his
despondent son, ``I want you to hurt like I do.''
   Those lyrics probably will get Newman in trouble. A press
conference will be hastily assembled and Newman will have to explain
his ``poorly chosen'' words.
   Don't laugh. It's happened to him before. Back in the 1970s,
Newman had a fluke hit single with ``Short People,'' which contained
the refrain ``short people got no reason to live.'' Listeners were
outraged at the ``bigotry'' of the 6-foot-plus Newman, causing the
song to actually be banned on some radio stations.
   ``It's amazing how sensitive people are about that thing. Billy
Crystal was supposed to be upset. You know what I think? It's pretty
clear,'' said Newman, who went on to let his offended listeners off
the hook. ``It's not really their fault; they're not used to irony
in songs. They're supposed to take the words at face value.''
   Newman, of course, isn't entirely blameless. Not that he really
dislikes short people, or believes that a poor, black child should
``roll with the punches'' as he sings on the new album.
   What gets him in trouble is he expresses the most controversial
opinions without a hint of distance. He doesn't sing about racism;
he sings as a racist.
   But Newman pleads artistic license: ``I'm not saying it. He's
doing it in the song, but I disagree.''
   Just as he disagrees with the obscene phone caller in ``Suzanne''
and the slave trader in ``Sail Away.'' But Newman can't deny a
certain affection for these and other sordid characters.
   ``You can laugh at some of these people,'' he said. ``They're so
insensitive. They lack such self-knowledge. The audience will laugh
becuase it's so hard, so rough. It's sort of a liberating thing.
Hopefully, we are better.''
   As sung in ``Dixie Flyer,'' the lead track of ``Land of Dreams,''
Newman was born in Los Angeles in 1943 and lived for a few years in
New Orleans. He came from a musical family _ movie music that is.
His uncle, Alfred, was a soundtrack conductor.
   Newman's own musical background was more contemporary. Fats
Domino was a favorite, so was Ray Charles. But Newman, a piano
player himself, was not looking to be famous.
   ``I never thought I'd be anything but a writer,'' Newman said.
``I never thought of performing or recording.''
   Newman got his first break in 1962 when his composition, ``They
Tell Me It's Summer,'' appeared as the B-side of a single by the
Fleetwoods.
   After having songs covered by such artists as the O'Jays, Little
Peggy March and Irma Thomas, his career received another boost in
1966 when Judy Collins performed his ``I Think It's Going to Rain
Today'' on her popular ``In My Life'' album.
   By 1968, the demand for Newman to make an album of his own had
become too strong to resist. John Lennon called him to say all the
Beatles had his demos, and Dusty Springfield included two Newman
songs on her classic ``Dusty in Memphis'' LP.
   ``I think A&amp;M and Warners had heard the demos,'' Newman said. ``I
was pulled into it rather than having any great ambition.''
   Warner Bros. won out and Newman's self-titled debut album came
out later that year. No one, not even Bob Dylan, could have prepared
listeners for a song like ``Beehive State,'' in which Newman, as the
representative of Utah at a national convention, pleads for his
fellow delegates to remember a whole country exists between Los
Angeles and New York.
   ``It was for people in the East,'' he said. ``In the West maybe
they don't know Delaware.''
   And in ``Davy the Fat Boy,'' Davy's only friend makes a deathbed
promise to the boy's parents that he will take care of their beloved
son, but proceeds to put poor Davy in a sideshow.
   Newman has made critically acclaimed albums such as ``12 Songs''
and ``Sail Away,'' but has failed to acheive major commercial
success.
   While it's no longer true that ``all combined, my records have
sold as many copies as James Taylor's last album sold in Des
Moines,'' as Newman once joked, his sales hardly come close to
George Michael or Whitney Houston.
   ``I wouldn't mind selling more records if it didn't change my
life enormously,'' Newman said. ``Why not a million instead of
300,000? But it might affect the nature of the audiences. When I
play a place much over 10,000, there's too much inattention.''
   He has never failed to be noticed by his peers, however. Newman's
songs have been used by Ray Charles, Linda Ronstadt, Art Garfunkel
and Etta James. Harry Nilsson recorded an entire album of his
compositions, and Newman's music was even used as the basis of the
off-Broadway show ``The Middle of Nowhere.''
   ``It's tremendously nice when someone good thinks that I'm very
good,'' he said. ``People who do this have always liked me, showbiz
folks. Harry Nilsson doing an album of my songs, it's what always I
wanted.''
   And Newman hopes listeners also appreciate his unique music.
   ``I'm interested in people who are a little off. Let the audience
figure out how I feel about them. Let them enjoy these people who
are worse off than we are.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Monday Jan. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
