<FIRST>s e BC-WeekendTV-Hall Adv27-29   01-10 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Hall, Adv 27-29,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 27-29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Talk Show Host Arsenio Hall Looking for Cross Section of Guests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's called ``The Arsenio Hall Show,'' but its
star suggests it should be called ``The Rainbow Coalition Talk
Show.''
   The syndicated late-night talk show was recently launched into
competition on more than 135 stations against NBC's Johnny Carson
and David Letterman and fellow newcomer Pat Sajak on CBS.
   Not since the late 1960s and early 1970s, when all three networks
fielded talk shows, has there been such yakking at the witching
hour. In addition, about a dozen other syndicated or cable talk
shows, with stars from Kenny Rogers to Joan Rivers, are in
production or waiting in the wings.
   ``Everybody's talking about the new talk shows,'' said
comedian-actor Hall, 29. ``I think Pat Sajak should call his show
`A.M. Sajak.' I think the people he attracts will be asleep by 11:30
at night. Letterman's basically a comedy show. I don't care who the
guests are. I tune in to watch David. And Johnny's a legend. He'll
be around as long as he wants.
   ``I think the problem with most talk shows is that they're
`Caucasian Boys Clubs.' My show is going to be more reflective of
America. America's a melting pot and that makes for an interesting
mixture. I don't see that on the other shows. You can tune in every
night for a month and not see a black person.
   ``People will say I'm the black talk show host,'' he said. ``I
say ignore my color. If I'm good, watch it. If I'm not good, don't
watch it. Talk is what I do best and most. I think God put me here
to be a talk-show host.''
   A few days before ``The Arsenio Hall Show'' premiered on Jan. 3,
Hall was feeling the tension. His office at Paramount Studios had
the look of a showroom for Toys R Us.
   ``I'm trying to control the stress level,'' Hall said. ``I can't
move to an island, so I'm discovering adult toys.'' At the moment he
was manipulating the radio control for a racing car that was
speeding around the outer office. In one corner was a basketball
hoop. There was also a table tennis set.
   His private office had enough doodads to please a bored child on
a rainy day. Hall settled behind the big U-shaped black desk. He was
wearing a Cleveland Indians warmup jacket and hat perched backward
on his head.
   Hall is not new to the talk show format. A year and a half ago he
took over ``The Late Show'' on Fox Broadcasting Co. not long after
the departure of Joan Rivers. The ratings began to improve, but Hall
left to co-star with Eddie Murphy in the film ``Coming To America.''
   It was while he was a guest on ``The Tonight Show'' promoting the
movie that Hall made up his mind to accept Paramount's offer for a
new talk show. ``I made the decision during a commercial break,'' he
said. ``I'd told Paramount no at first. I didn't want to play
against Johnny Carson, the idol who had made me want to do what I
do. But I can't sit on the sidelines and be a fan all my life. I
can't live my life through Johnny Carson. If I fail, I fail. I'd
feel even worse if I'd never tried.''
   Although the talk shows are on the air at the same time in many
cities, Hall said he doesn't think they are competing for the same
audience.
   ``I don't think competition is a problem,'' he said. ``My show's
a different kind of show. My demographics are different. My job is
not to cure racism. My job is to present entertainment. It's not an
issue of blacks and whites. Sometimes it's between the young and the
old. I may not get Dolly Parton, but maybe I'll get the next Dolly
Parton.
   ``But this is not a minority talk show. I'm not doing `Soul
Train' at late night. I just want to be first with some new talent.
Something `new wave' with a cutting edge. It's a talk show for
people who don't have a talk show now. Johnny has his loyal fans,
but those fans have kids and maybe they'll watch me.''
   Hall tapes his show late every afternoon at Paramount Studios and
it's sent out by satellite. Paramount distributes ``Entertainment
Tonight'' in a similar manner.
   Hall started performing early in his hometown of Cleveland, and
at the age of 12 told his mother he wanted to do what Johnny Carson
does. His parents, however, insisted he go to college. ``I thought
it was a waste of time,'' he said, ``but now I see it's really
helped me.''
   He worried that he had missed his shot by going to college. ``I
saw Letterman get his show,'' he said. ``I saw Garry Shandling get
his break. Then Jay Leno took me under his wing. He was a great
inspiration for me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Jan. 27-29</NOTE>
</DOC>
