<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Young ADV20-22   01-10 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Young, ADV 20-22,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20-22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan. 20-22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Faron Young Pretends He's 75</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS1 of Jan. 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans think country music singer Faron
Young, who has had top billing over Elvis Presley and sold more than
30 million records, is more than 70 years old because he's been a
show business fixture for almost four decades.
   He's really just 56.
   ``I've been around so long that when I tell people I'm 56 years
old, they laugh and say, `And how many more?' The best thing is to
say you're 75 and then they say, `You look good for your age.'''
   Young has been singing about sin and sentimentality in a belting
baritone since 1951. He's released 60 albums and had classic country
music hits such as ``Hello Walls,'' ``It's Four in the Morning'' and
``Sweet Dreams.''
   His recording career tailed off in the mid-1980s. But he's back
again with the album ``Here's to You.'' He's also on the road
performing about 150 days a year and he appears regularly on The
Nashville Network on cable TV.
   Young, a swashbuckling whippersnapper in the mid-'50s, feels no
jealousy toward younger country stars such as Randy Travis and
George Strait who reign over the music charts like he did 30 years
ago.
   ``When those kids hit (it big) today, they ain't hurting me a
bit,'' Young said in an interview. ``They are widening the spectrum
of country music. The U.S. Mint runs 24 hours a day printing money.
There's plenty of it for all of us.''
   In his long career, Young has been brash and irreverent with a
turbulent private life rivaling that of rock 'n' roll pioneer Jerry
Lee Lewis. He's been arrested on charges including driving while
intoxicated, indecent exposure, assault and reckless driving.
   His more madcap song titles that fed his image as a wind-him-up,
irrepressible party-lover include ``Live Fast, Love Hard, Die
Young'' and ``I've Got Five Dollars (and It's Saturday Night).''
   He once said the secret of his success was ``drinking expensive
whiskey.''
   ``I don't drink like I used to, just two-three drinks a day,'' he
said recently. ``Now if I just behave myself ...''
   Just as Presley was coming on the national scene in the mid-'50s,
Young was the star of a music tour that included Presley as one of
the lesser known talents.
   ``He wasn't making but $100 a day, so when I checked into the
motel I'd give him the high sign and he'd come stay in my room with
me,'' Young recalled. ``He really couldn't afford it.''
   Years later, Presley called him and offered to take him on tour
at double Young's normal booking fee.
   ``I asked why and he said, `Because you helped ME one time.' So
then I opened HIS shows.''
   Young, a native of Shreveport, La., was the first singer to have
a hit with ``Sweet Dreams,'' a song closely associated with the late
country queen Patsy Cline who recorded the song, as did Emmylou
Harris.
   ``People say to me, `Boy, you really sing that Patsy Cline song
good,''' Young said. ``It was a well-written, tear-jerking country
song, and the melody was outstanding.''
   Similarly, Strait's recent record ``If You Ain't Lovin', You
Ain't Livin'' was a hit by Young 30 years ago.
   Besides being a country music trailblazer, Young has helped some
of the biggest stars in music get started. He loaned Willie Nelson
$1,500 when Nelson was a struggling, little-known songwriter. He
loaned Roger Miller the money to buy drums. He made Charley Pride a
part of his concert entourage when blacks were not welcome in
country music. He hired a young carpenter named Kris Kristofferson
to panel his office walls.
   Young thought about leaving the road in 1985, but a divorce
settlement required him to pay his wife of 30 years $3,400 a month
in alimony.
   Young, known as ``the singing sheriff'' because of a role in the
Western movie ``Hidden Gun,'' has no regrets.
   ``I came off a dairy farm and came into this industry and this
industry has been good to me. I'll never forget where I came from
and the people who helped me make it,'' he said.
   ``I couldn't have done anymore than I've done, really. I've made
motion pictures, had hit records, done TV. If I did it over, I
wouldn't change a thing. I've been good to everybody. I've got a big
mouth and I say what I think. But I'm the first guy to apologize.''
   How would he like to be remembered?
   ``I did the best I could.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan. 20-22</NOTE>
