<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   01-10 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,0870</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Videos reviewed this week: ``The Blob,'' ``Midnight Crossing,''
``And God Created Woman.''
   
   ``The Blob'' (RCA@Columbia Home Video. VHS-Beta, 89.95. Rated R)
   
   It's back! Yes! The Blob is back! That pulsating pool of pulsing
protoplasm.
   Talk about sentimental journeys! Now's your chance to scream out
warnings to the poor folks on your videocassette player:
   ``Watch out, Mister! Don't touch that thing with a stick!''
(Shhhhhlurp!)
   ``Watch out, lady! Don't get in that telephone booth!''
(Sssssssuhhhhk!)
   YOW!!!
   ``Watch out, kids! Don't neck in lovers' lane!'' (Ssshhhlurg!)
   YOW!!!
   This affectionate remake pays homage to the Original, an obscene
black, viscid ooze that gobbled up everything and everybody. Cripes,
it came off the movie screen in the town movie house. Talk about
your last picture shows!
   Formless, fatal and yucky, ``The Blob'' was a perfect symbol for
the era's angst, before we stopped worrying and learned to love the
Bomb. And, of course, a Misunderstood Teen-ager (young Steve
McQueen) saved the day.
   This time, the viscous visitor from space is an errant biological
warfare experiment by wicked scientists. It's a Miami Vice pink, for
some reason. And it falls on you from above and snags you with
tentacles _ a metaphor for the 1980s.
   Kevin Dillon gives a nicely controlled performance as the
Misunderstood Teen. The utterly perky Shawnee Smith is the
homecoming queen. The vastly talented Jeffrey DeMunn and Candy Clark
play the compassionate sheriff and the big-hearted waitress, both
horribly wasted (heh, heh) in their roles.
   ``The Blob'' should be a gory delight to the blood-thirsty
pre-teens that are its obvious target. But it's great fun for the
over-30 crowd who ought to know better. Trash it may be, but it's
really well-done trash.
   Welcome back, big feller.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Midnight Crossing'' (MCA Home Entertainment. VHS-Beta, $89.98.
Rated R)
   
   Flashback: Castro is coming out of the Cuban highlands and
Batista's casino operators are moving their cash out of the country.
Somehow a bunch of U.S. Navy men get hold of $2 million of it and
stash it on this island.
   Cut to the present: Daniel J. Travanti was one of the sailors.
The other one who knew where the treasure is has died, so Travanti
wants to go back and get it. (Why did they wait 20 years? Good
question.)
   His wife, an eye doctor played by Faye Dunaway, is blind. (``I
specialized in eye diseases. So how did I get glaucoma?'' Good
question.)
   He charters the yacht of his suspiciously deceased shipmate's son
(John Laughlin), whose perky, pouty wife (Kim Cattrall) works in
Capt. Frank Furillo's insurance agency. (Why? Good question.)
   By this point you've sunk 45 minutes in this loser and nothing's
happening.
   Wait a second! ... Hey, isn't this the perfect bunch to erupt in
jealousy, lust, murderous intrigue and pistols and spearguns and all
kinds of neat-o bloodiness played out beneath a cruel, cruel
Caribbean sun? Good question.
   Travanti sleepwalks through his role. Dunaway is at her most
brittle, shrewish and shrill. The juve leads are bland as custard.
Phony tension, childish intrigue, unbelievably stupid plot tricks.
Worse, the venerable Ned Beatty is written into the plot _ and just
as quickly written out.
   How did all these clever, handsome people make this bad movie?
Good question.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``And God Created Woman'' (Vestron Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98. Rated
R)
   
   ``And God Created Woman'' was a naughty 1957 New Wave movie by
Roger Vadim, who 20 years later has remade it. It was a long lunch.
   It's too bad, because the original had some heat to it. Sex
kitten Brigitte Bardot undressed en route to superstardom. These
days she's a recluse who campaigns for kindness to animals. There is
a lesson in this for us all.
   The new version stars the lithe and perky Rebecca De Mornay as a
jailhouse queen, a bloated Frank Langella as political aspirant and
Vincent Spano as a bewildered plot device who marries her to get her
out of prison.
   ``Sure,'' you say as the credits roll and dumb things start
happening, ``this guy slams the movie, but I bet it's going to get
plenty steamy with Miss De Mornay taking her clothes off and stuff
every other minute.''
   No such luck, pilgrim. Get over it. Vadim without an idea in his
head has tackled a vaguely feminist message and been trampled to
death by it. No wonder Jane Fonda divorced him. There is no
intelligence at work here whatsoever.
   Miss De Mornay gets 3.2 nude scenes on which to base her
character _ sort of a fallen woman with a heart of gold. Langella
tries to get elected. Vincent Spano wakes up and wishes it was all a
dream.
   What a waste of time. Bring back Bardot.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0526EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   01-10 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Symphony No. 6; overtures ``Egmont'' and ``Coriolanus,'' by
Ludwig van Beethoven (L'Oiseau-Lyre) _ The Academy of Ancient Music,
conducted by Christopher Hogwood
   
   Christopher Hogwood's original instrumentalists provide a
thoroughly fresh look at a programmatic favorite, Beethoven's
Pastoral Symphony. This is not a performance out of the academy but
a bright, brisk and pungent reading.
   The musicians play original instruments or accurate
reproductions, as the linear notes nicely point out in a welcome
list of personnel. The familiar lyrical themes of hill and dale and
storm and stream are heard anew. The strings have a vivid bite and
the winds provide a beautiful variety of tones. Loud chords are
punched out, violin trills shimmer.
   Hogwood conducts with a beautiful attention to detail and takes
generally brisk tempos. One wished for a greater sense of sweep,
however, and less abrupt transitions between passages.
   If you're looking for sheer sonic beauty, this orchestra does not
have the rich sound of a Berlin Philharmonic Pastoral Symphony. The
violins in the first movement on occasion blared in loud passages,
and the valveless horns in the third movement sounded blatty in loud
chords. But if nothing else, this recording is plain interesting.
   It could also help make a case for how original instruments
clarify musical figures. The storm rumblings of the celli and basses
in the fourth movement sounded more ominous because the bowing was
more incisive and therefore easier to hear. Sixteenth note trills in
the last movement were extremely accurate. The instruments had less
decay, reducing overlap between chords.
   Hogwood rounds out this fine compact disk with rhythmically
propelled renditions of the ``Coriolanus'' and ``Egmont'' overtures.
   _ By Dan Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``American Dream'' (Atlantic) _ Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young
   
   Rock reunions are usually depressing reminders of the ravaging
effects of age. David Crosby, Stephen Stills, Graham Nash and Neil
Young are the latest to prove that most memories should stay
memories.
   ``American Dream,'' their first album together in 18 years, is a
disaster of fairly epic proportions. It's boring enough to make one
forget the joyful sounds produced when these four voices meshed two
decades ago.
   The harmonies appear sporadically throughout ``American Dream,''
but they dress up a startling lack of worthwhile material.
   The inner jacket photo shows Young sitting down in the studio,
looking cranky as his three colleagues share a microphone. Even on a
bad day he's the most interesting of these four songwriters, but the
picture betrays a strange detachment from this project.
   Young's material highlights his lighter, more reflective side,
except for the title cut, which explores the world of television
evangelists. That's easily the most overdone song topic of 1988.
   But at least he's in this decade. Topics tackled by some of the
others include the Vietnam War and the environment, as well as the
old standby of ``loving the one you're with.''
   Nash is insufferable. When he isn't being preachy, he's
subjecting us to tedious, overwrought ballads. Stills is to be
commended for the pretty ``That Girl,'' the only worthwhile cut
among this record's 14.
   Crosby's long-awaited ``Compass,'' about the drug addiction that
landed him in jail, is simply excruciating. Check out this line: ``I
have seized death's door handle, like a fish out of the water
waiting for the mercy of the cat.'' Huh?
   Maybe with advancing age and declining careers these guys needed
the money. Don't give them yours.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Fierstein ADV20-22   01-10 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Fierstein, ADV 20-22,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20-22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan 20-22 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Gay Play Hits the Screens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2 of Jan. 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The play ``Torch Song Trilogy'' began its
award-winning history 10 years ago and only now is reaching movie
screens? Why did it take so long?
   The best explanation comes from Harvey Fierstein, who won two
Tony awards in 1982 for writing and starring in the play: ``I wanted
to wait until it could be done right. It took finding the right
producer, which I did about five years ago. Since Howard Gottfried
had done Paddy Chayefsky films like `Hospital' and `Network,' I felt
that if Chayefksy could work with him, so could I.
   ``Then my brother (Ronald, who is executive producer of the film)
and I went around to the studios looking for financial support that
would give us artistic control. Then we found New Line Cinema, which
agreed to give us that control.''
   Three more years passed before Fierstein found the director he
wanted, ``a director that had the humor as well as the drama and the
sensitivity for the story. A lot of directors were very frightened
of male-to-male intimacy, and they felt you either had a drama or a
comedy and you don't have big laughs in the middle of a scene where
the audience is also crying.''
   During his quest he discovered that the major studios did not
have much interest, even though ``Torch Song Trilogy'' has been an
international stage success.
   ``They liked the play, but they were afraid of the length; it ran
four hours in the theater,'' Fierstein said. ``They were scared that
it might become an `art film.' That's not what I wanted to make. I
wanted to make a `movie movie.'''
   With its unabashed treatment of gay lives, ``Torch Song Trilogy''
created a sensation from its birth at New York's La Mama Etc. in
1978. Fierstein took the leading role of Arnold Beckoff, a
homosexual seeking respect from the heterosexual world, including
his mother.
   Spurned by his bisexual lover (Brian Kerwin), Arnold enters into
a relationship with a young model (Matthew Broderick). They marry
and decide to adopt a troubled gay teen-ager (Eddie Castrodad), a
role Broderick originated on Broadway. All hell breaks loose when
Arnold's mother (Anne Bancroft) arrives from Florida.
   The play dealt with Arnold's promiscuity. But how could that be
treated in the era of AIDS?
   ``Obviously AIDS is something I thought about, especially since
my co-star for three years had AIDS and we lost five cast members of
`Torch Song' through AIDS.
   ``I didn't want to pay short shrift to AIDS, just shove it off.
But `Torch Song' has nothing to do with AIDS. I also wanted to make
sure that some of the issues in the movie didn't get clouded. ... I
wanted the mother to deal with her real feelings about her son and
the issue of his homosexuality without a virus clouding it.''
   Fierstein was only 24 when he started his career with ``Torch
Song Trilogy.'' Some aspects of the play are autobiographical: He
was performing drag at 16, when he weighed almost 250 pounds (he is
now 170). At his parents' insistence, he went to Brooklyn's Pratt
Institute, but he quickly returned to the theater after graduating.
   ``Torch Song'' emerged from one-act plays that eventually reached
five hours. The play almost folded off-Broadway until a New York
Times review saved it. Fierstein followed his two Tonys with another
for the book of ``La Cage aux folles.'' He also wrote ``Safe Sex,''
vignettes about AIDS, as well as the book for Peter Allen's new
musical ``Legs Diamond.''
   How closely does Arnold Beckoff follow the life of Harvey
Fierstein?
   ``There's no such thing as fiction,'' he said. ``There is some me
in Arnold and Arnold in me. There is a little bit of me in all the
characters. ... It all gets mixed up; you steal from all your
friends. You go into your friends' lives and you pull out what you
can use.''
   But Fierstein does not parallel Beckoff in one respect:
opposition of his family.
   ``My family has always known about me,'' he said. ``I came out at
13. I must be close to my brother; he's executive producer on this
film. My mother and I are very close. We don't have the problem that
Arnold has with his mother.
   ``We discuss everything. In fact she just called from Florida,
and what did she want? She wanted to know what to get my boyfriend
for Christmas.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan 20-22</NOTE>
</DOC>
