<DOCNO> AP890110-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--SonofHeaven ADV20-22   01-10 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Son of Heaven, ADV 20-22,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20-22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan. 20-22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Chinese Art Exhibit Is Big Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1 of Jan. 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Son of Heaven'' exhibition of Chinese art
was a major cultural success for Seattle and will now be seen by art
lovers in Columbus, Ohio _ the only other stop for the historic
display in the United States.
   The exhibition, one of the largest displays of Chinese art and
artifacts to be seen in this country, includes more than 225 items
associated with the kings and emperors of China.
   The displays include 2,500-year-old ceremonial cooking vessels
and temple bells, full-size terra-cotta warriors and horses from the
tomb of China's first emperor, delicate scroll paintings from the
15th century and an exquisitely carved and lacquered 18th century
throne and accessories.
   The show, a collaboration of the Chinese government and a U.S.
organizing committee, opened in Seattle on July 28 and closed Jan.
8. It begins a six-month run in Columbus on March 1.
   About 500,000 people attended the exhibit at the Seattle Center,
and exhibition president Larry Childs estimated the show made more
than $400,000 above its $5 million in expenses.
   Before the show opened, organizers had forecast attendance at 1
million. Childs and others say that was far too optimistic.
   ``Even though we had that ghastly 1 million number, we really
feel good about what we've been able to accomplish,'' said Claudia
Johnson, the show's marketing director.
   The exhibition frequently has been compared to the ``Treasures of
Tutankhamun,'' which drew 1.3 million to the same exhibit hall here
10 years ago. But Johnson notes ``Tut'' had been to four other
American cities as part of a four-year U.S. tour before coming to
Seattle, with a tremendous buildup of publicity.
   The Seattle run hasn't been entirely smooth. Childs and other
show officials acknowledged some disorganization before the
exhibition's start, including not having a marketing budget set
until two weeks before the opening. In August, there was a messy
firing and replacement of the show's executive director, Harvey
West. At the time, West said he had disagreed with Childs over some
aspects of the show's operation, and Childs said West had trouble
delegating authority.
   Later, there was a flap over waiving admission charges during the
Seattle Center's free Labor Day weekend arts festival, Bumbershoot.
``Son of Heaven'' officials eventually agreed to the free admission.
   There also were numerous small changes in lighting and other
presentations of the exhibits and in hours of the show.
   Childs said many of the changes were the type any show goes
through when opening. The Ohio exhibition, he said, will benefit
from what was learned during the Seattle run.
   For example, he said, advertising began in November, with special
efforts to target nearby cities, senior citizens groups and
students. More emphasis will be placed on the gift shop, which
turned out to be a strong moneymaker, and on sales of T-shirts,
hats, books and other ``Son of Heaven'' merchandise in department
stores.
   Because of the exhibition's size and the cost of staging it,
Seattle and Columbus have been the only cities to sign up as hosts.
But Childs says he's received a number of inquiries, including ones
from Denver, Baltimore, Toronto and Florida's Epcot Center.
   No negotiations are under way for further sites, he said, adding
that the Chinese haven't decided whether they want their treasures
to remain longer in this country.
   Costs for the Columbus exhibit have been estimated at $6.35
million, including remodeling Central High School, where the show
will be held. The Columbus Museum of Art will produce and manage the
exhibition.
   Proceeds from that show will go to the ``Son of Heaven''
Foundation, a non-profit organization, while proceeds from the
Seattle exhibition will be shared by two charities, the Resource
Center for the Handicapped and Vesper Society Group.
   Childs estimated the two Seattle charities will split $1 million
once the profits are divvied up at the end of the Columbus run.
   ``It's going to depend on how the show does in Ohio,'' he said.
``If nobody shows up in Ohio, it's going to be kind of interesting.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan 20-22</NOTE>
