<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-10 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0508</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan sent Congress his final
budget, a $1.15 trillion plan to continue military growth and
squeezed social programs with optimism the federal deficit will
disappear without a major tax increase.
   President-elect Bush praised the effort, but reiterated Monday
his intention to alter its design within weeks.
   Like his eight others, Reagan's ninth budget is out of balance.
But this deficit, at $92.5 billion, would be the smallest since the
year he took office.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration dumped the savings
and loan crisis into the lap of President-elect Bush, acknowledging
for the first time it does not have enough money to bail out the
troubled industry.
   The administration, in its proposed budget for fiscal year 1990,
outlined plans Monday to spend $64 billion from the Federal Savings
and Loan Insurance Corp. from 1989 through 1994.
   But the budget document acknowledged ``these proposals will not
resolve the entire problem'' and said Treasury Secretary Nicholas F.
Brady is working on a plan, ``including identifying additional
funding sources for FSLIC,'' to be presented to Bush within 60 days.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $4.5 billion more in
consumer debt than they paid off in November as consumers increased
their purchases for the holiday season, the government reports.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Monday the increase followed a
revised increase of $3.9 billion in October and a tiny $2 million
rise in September.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says it will sue to
block two proposed joint ventures between Westinghouse Electric
Corp. and a Swiss company.
   The ventures between Westinghouse and Asea Brown Boveri Inc. of
Zurich, Switzerland, would involve the manufacture and sale of
electric power generation, transmission and distribution products.
   Monday's announcement came just two weeks after Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh launched an effort to stem a ``fear of an antitrust
challenge.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major victory for Dow Chemical Co., the
Supreme Court upheld a lower court ruling dismissing hundreds of
personal injury lawsuits tied to the chemical giant's anti-nausea
drug Bendectin.
   The court, without comment, rejected on Monday an appeal by more
than 800 families who filed a federal lawsuit against Merrell Dow
Pharmaceuticals, the Cincinnati-based Dow unit that manufactures the
drug.
   Meanwhile, the justices agreed to decide whether Congress may
outlaw all sexually explicit telephone dial-up message services,
known as dial-a-porn. The high court will rule on the validity of a
1988 law that sought to ban all obscene and indecent messages
available through these services.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times Co. has agreed to sell its
cable television system for $420 million to a venture that will be
managed by a minority investment group.
   The price amounts to nearly $2,600 per subscriber, which industry
analysts said Monday made it one of the more expensive recent cable
system sales.
</TEXT>
