<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the National Mediation Board halted
talks between Eastern Airlines and its largest union and returned to
Washington.
   Chairman Walter Wallace couldn't be reached for comment, but an
Eastern executive said Monday Wallace gave as his reason the failure
of efforts to keep secret the talks with the Machinists union.
   Wallace arrived Friday for the talks at a hotel in Key Largo,
Fla. The sessions were aimed at ending a contract stalemate that has
clouded the future of the airline, which is a subsidiary of
Houston-based Texas Air Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British electronics giant General Electric Co. PLC
accused rival Plessey Co. of mounting ``a spoiling tactic'' by
joining an international consortium that is expected to make a
hostile bid for GEC.
   GEC had joined Siemens AG of West Germany in launching a hostile,
$3 billion offer for Plessey in November. Now GEC finds itself the
target of a possible counter-bid by a consortium that probably will
include Plessey.
   GEC said Monday it would fight the possible counter-bid and
pursue its efforts with Siemens to take over Plessey.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More U.S. companies changed their names in 1988
than at any time in the past 19 years, and more than half the
changes resulted from corporate mergers and takeovers, a
corporate-identity firm says.
   The number of companies changing names last year was 1,864, or 6
percent more than the 1,753 that changed names in 1987, the previous
record year, the firm Anspach Grossman Portugal Inc. said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTE Corp. announced a reorganization into
six operating groups and the appointment of Kent B. Foster as
president of the largest group, GTE Telephone Operations.
   GTE Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James. L. Johnson said
Monday the six operating groups will report to President and Chief
Operating Officer Charles R. Lee.
   Johnson said the new corporate structure was ``a natural step in
the evolution of a more streamlined and efficient GTE, and is
reflective of of the constantly changing business environment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials reacted cautiously to the
announcement that Pacific Resources Inc., Hawaii's second-largest
publicly held company, has agreed to be acquired by Australia's
largest company for nearly $400 million.
   Gov. John Waihee said Monday the state will look closely at the
agreement for Pacific Resources to be merged with Broken Hill
Proprietary Co. Ltd.
   Broken Hill wants to combine its own petroleum exploration and
development business with the refining and marketing operations of
Pacific Resources.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground for the fourth straight session
Monday as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.17 to
2,199.46, a new high since the 1987 crash.
   The dollar rose but, finished below its highs of the day because
of intervention by several central banks.
   Bond prices were mixed.
   Coffee, frozen pork-belly and soybean futures prices fell
sharply, precious metals were mixed, energy futures rose and
stock-index futures advanced.
</TEXT>
