<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     01-10 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices are continuing an upward
trend, helped by investor expectations that OPEC is abiding by its
production accord.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
settled 17 cents higher at $17.72 a barrel Monday. On Friday, the
contract closed up 13 cents at $17.55 following a volatile week.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, domestic heating
oil futures ended Monday higher. The February contract settled at
54.15 cents a gallon, up 0.55 cent.
   Meanwhile, unleaded gasoline futures closed mixed, with the
February contract up 0.24 cent at 47.96 cents a gallon.
   Energy analysts said bullish sentiment about OPEC's agreement to
cut production continued to push prices higher. The 13-member
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries announced in November
it would reduce its output to 18.5 million barrels a day starting
Jan. 1 from an amount estimated at more than 22 million barrels.
   Since then, prices have risen approximately $5 a barrel.
   Traders said futures prices got a lift Monday from reports that
most OPEC countries are abiding by the accord and have drastically
reduced their production. At least two reports suggested that Saudi
Arabia, the cartel's largest producer, cut its output by more than 2
million barrels a day the first week in January.
   ``Whichever (report) you take, the figures show they're down.
It's the direction that helped out,'' said Bob Baker, a futures
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Prices also got a lift from reports of continuing problems in the
North Sea following a fire in an oil facility there late last year,
traders said.
   ``Prices are moving up because it's a bull market and there is no
bearish news,'' said Jim Fiedler, an oil broker with E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EmployeeAttitudes     01-10 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Employee Attitudes,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 10 a.m. EST; time set by source.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Americans Ambivalent About Materialism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Working Americans ages 25 to 49 say they would
like the nation to return to a simpler way of life, but their own
concern with material success has not declined, a survey released
today shows.
   The telephone survey of 1,001 people who work full-time outside
the home was commissioned by Joseph E. Seagram &amp; Sons Inc. on behalf
of its Chivas Regal brand of liquor.
   Seventy-five percent of the respondents said they would ``like to
see our country return to a simpler lifestyle, with less emphasis on
material success.'' Only 17 percent disagreed.
   But in another question, only 16 percent said they themselves
were less concerned with material success than they were five years
ago. Thirty percent said they were more concerned, while 53 percent
said there was no change in their attitude.
   ``There's got to be some nostalgia going there,'' said Frank
Walton, president of Research &amp; Forecasts Inc., the New York-based
firm that prepared the survey, explaining the seeming contradiction
in the answers.
   ``People think, `I wish things were simpler. But if that means
less material rewards in my life, I'm not so sure,''' Walton said.
   All but 31 percent of the respondents said they had been involved
in some kind of public service work over the past five years.
Thirty-four percent claimed they donated 10 percent or more of their
income to charity in the previous year.
   Walton said it is likely that some people exaggerated how
charitable they were. But he said it nevertheless appeared from the
survey that Americans are somewhat more public-spirited than in
1978, when a Lou Harris poll found that 49 percent of Americans did
not claim involvement in community volunteer work.
   More than a third of the respondents said they thought they would
spend more time on public service in the next few years, while only
about a tenth thought they would spend less time.
   ``Clearly, there's a reservoir of good intentions that hasn't
been tapped,'' Walton said.
   The survey was conducted in mid-October. The margin of error on
most questions was about 3 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
