<SECOND>BC-China-Trade,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Exports Hit Record $40 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese exports topped $40 billion in 1988,
setting a record and far exceeding official targets, the People's
Daily reported Tuesday.
   The newspaper quoted preliminary figures released by the Ministry
of Foreign Economic Relations and Trade as showing exports totaling
a record $40.1 billion, with nearly 70 percent coming from
industrial finished products.
   The ministry said the figure was not final and likely would go up
slightly when more information came in from remote areas. It also
said import figures were not yet compiled.
   The preliminary export total is up more than 16 percent from
1987's $34.6 billion. Although the increase is higher than planned,
it is sharply lower than the 1987 increase of 28 percent.
   However, the official China Daily newspaper quoted an
unidentified ministry official as saying China's export performance
was remarkable in view of increased competition on the world market.
