<SECOND>PM-Scherer-Fink,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Scherer President Forms Investment Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter R. Fink, former president and chief
executive officer of R.P. Scherer Corp., has formed a new investment
company that could try to buy the capsule manufacturer, he said
today.
   Quantum Corp., an investment and management concern, was not set
up specifically to acquire R.P. Scherer, said Fink, who will be
president of the company.
   ``However, at this point, I would not rule out participation in
an endeavor of that type,'' he said.
   Fink resigned from R.P. Scherer in November after opposing the
sale of the company in an unsuccessful proxy battle with heirs of
the founder. He had been president and CEO since 1979.
   He will continue on the Scherer board of directors.
   Quantum is evaluating a range of investment opportunities,
including acquisitions and leveraged buyouts, Fink said. It also
will offer strategic management services, he said.
   The Scherer board had voted in September to consider a number of
financial alternatives including sale of the company.
   The proxy battle at R.P. Scherer pitted Fink against his
estranged wife, Karla Fink, daughter of the founder, and her
brother, John S. Scherer. The two are directors who control about 38
percent of the company between them.
   Karla Fink led the dissident shareholders ``Committee for the
Sale of R.P. Scherer Corp.'' It successfully backed election in a
proxy vote Aug. 17 of two new board members who favor considering
the sale of the company.
</TEXT>
