<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade with little fresh news to
influence the markets.
   Analysts said some of the early losses reflected follow-through
selling after Monday's steep decline in the soybean market, which
was linked to forecasts for rain in Argentina, the world's
fourth-largest soybean producer.
   But the showers there overnight were lighter than expected, said
Jerry Gidel, a grain-market analyst in Chicago with the G.H. Miller
division of the British-owned trading company LIT America Inc.
   ``There was some rain but it wasn't fantastic,'' Gidel said.
``Right now the grain markets are kind of sitting here trying to
figure out if the rain in Argentina is any big deal or not.''
   Gidel said the markets would soon begin focusing on the upcoming
crop report from the Agriculture Department. Friday's report will
include final 1988 crop production figures, estimates for 1989
planted acreage and new supply and demand statistics.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.47 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to \ cent lower with March at $2.89\ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to
1{ cents lower with March at $2.36{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent
lower to { cent higher with January at $8.06 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent higher with February at
73.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .38 cent higher
with January at 85.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent lower
to .03 cent higher with February at 46.20 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .02 cent to .20 cent lower with February at 42.25 cents
a pound.
   Livestock futures closed mixed on Monday while pork bellies
finished sharply lower.
