<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-EasternTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0019 01-10 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Executive Sees Quicker Asset Sales After Talks with Union
Break Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5-6th grafs pvs, Mediation Board... with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with comment from mediation board chairman. Picks up 7th graf pvs, Meanwhile
Monday ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines executive said the company may
have to speed up planned sales of assets after the chairman of the
National Mediation Board halted talks between the carrier and its
largest union.
   ``Clearly, the happenings of this last weekend will make us move
forward faster on some asset sales than perhaps we would have done
otherwise,'' Joseph B. Leonard, Eastern's senior vice president and
chief operating officer, said Monday.
   ``The end of talks is certainly a major disappointment with
serious implications about Eastern's future,'' he added.
   Machinists District 100 President Charles E. Bryan charged the
company sabotaged the mediation session with news leaks and was
``determined to force a strike.'' He called management actions
``unethical, without principle, deceptive.''
   Mediation Board Chairman Walter Wallace abruptly ended the talks
Monday and returned to Washington. He said today he stopped the
sessions because the failure to keep negotiations secret undermined
the collective bargaining process.
   ``Media in a fish bowl yields nothing,'' Wallace said in a
statement issued in Washington. ``In such situations, the parties
tend to make proposals and statements aimed at public relations
objectives rather than the bargaining process.'' He did not lay
blame on either side.
   ``The board will continue its efforts to bring the parties
together under proper circumstances where a solution of the labor
dispute can be achieved,'' he said.
   There was no indication of when more talks might be scheduled.
   Meanwhile Monday, the Internal Revenue Service gave Eastern until
Sept. 15 to make $105 million in payments to employee pension plans
that had been due last Sept. 15. Leonard said the company would
finance the payments by pending asset sales.
   Wallace had arrived Friday for the talks in Key Largo aimed at
ending a 15-month contract stalemate that has clouded the future of
the airline, a subsidiary of Houston-based Texas Air Corp., which
also owns non-union Continental Airlines.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Miami television stations
discovered the location of the talks and began covering them Friday.
Matell said employee bulletins about the talks that were put out
daily by Eastern and were obtained by reporters weren't a violation
of the news blackout.
   Leonard blamed the breakdown on the union's refusal to set a
deadline for negotiations. Eastern, which says it is losing $1
million a day, has been pressing for a federal declaration of an
impasse that would begin a 30-day cooling-off period. After that,
the union could strike and the company could impose its own work
conditions on the union members.
   ``These talks have dragged on ... draining Eastern's strengths
with each passing day. We desperately need the government to provide
a process to resolve this dispute within 30 days,'' Leonard said.
   The union has claimed Eastern wants to provoke a strike so it can
try to bust the union. The machinists also have opposed attempts to
sell parts of the airline, such as the recently agreed $365 million
sale of Eastern's Northeast shuttle to businessman Donald Trump,
saying the sales also are aimed at breaking the union.
   The machinists, representing 8,500 mechanics, baggage handlers
and other ground service workers that make up more than one-fourth
of Eastern's employees, were seeking a raise of $50 million a year.
The airline was seeking $150 million in concessions, mainly from
non-mechanics.
   Leonard said the machinists were seeking an 8 percent raise,
while Eastern had offered a job-security program guaranteeing no
layoffs and offering job training to enable the non-mechanics to
gain better-paying jobs.
   Bryan said the company's proposals were unchanged, while the
machinists' offer totaled only a 1.9 percent raise over three years.
He said work-rule changes offered by the union would save the
company money overall.
   Eastern reported $233.7 million in losses for the first three
quarters of 1988.
</TEXT>
