<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-DeficitCommission 1stLd-Writethru f0113 01-10 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deficit Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0113,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deficit Panel Gets Go-Ahead From Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, Bush's two, to make Ashley former representative;
Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The incoming Bush administration gave the
go-ahead today for a high-level advisory panel to begin work in
earnest on a plan to eliminate the huge federal budget deficit.
   Leaders of the National Economic Commission said they had
received word from Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady that the
bipartisan panel should plan on meeting a March 1 deadline for
submitting its report.
   Commission co-chairman Drew Lewis made the announcement as the
14-member advisory panel began an open hearing on the deficit
problem.
   There had been discussions with top Bush officials about whether
the president-elect might postpone the commission's report until
Sept. 1. Today's announcement is an apparent indication that Bush
intends to take the panel's recommendations seriously and will give
them weight in his own negotiations with Congress.
   The commission was created by Congress after the October 1987
stock market crash with supporters hoping that the panel, composed
of leaders from government, business and labor, would be able to
break the seven-year deadlock over the federal budget deficit.
   While Bush derided the commission during the presidential
campaign as a stalking horse for a tax increase, his comments since
winning the election have been more favorable, and he has emphasized
he considers reducing the budget deficit as his No. 1 economic
priority.
   Bush's two appointees to the commission, former Sen. Paul Laxalt,
R-Nev., and former Rep. Thomas Ashley, D-Ohio, a longtime friend,
both attended today's meeting.
   Lewis and commission co-chairman Robert Strauss also met today
with President Reagan at the White House to discuss the panel's work
to date.
   Lewis, a former transportation secretary in Reagan's Cabinet,
said Brady told him that the commission should plan on meeting the
March 1 deadline unless it hears otherwise from Bush once he takes
office Jan. 20.
   While the panel, made up equally of Republicans and Democrats,
has had sharp disagreements over whether taxes need to be raised,
Lewis said he felt it would be able to reach agreement on a deficit
reduction plan by March 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0274 </DOCNO>
