<FIRST>u f BC-Shamrock-Polaroid     01-10 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Shamrock-Polaroid,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Appeals Court Ruling on Polaroid Takeover Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy E. Disney's investment company said
Tuesday it has appealed a Delaware court ruling that dealt a serious
blow to Disney's hostile $2.6 billion effort to buy Polaroid Corp.
   Shamrock Holdings Inc., the investment vehicle for the Disney
family, appealed Monday to the Delaware Supreme Court a Chancery
Court decision upholding Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan.
   The lower court ruling last Friday was seen as a setback to
Disney's takeover effort because the ESOP holds 14 percent of the
instant-camera company and workers have announced their opposition
to the buyout bid. Management also has resisted Disney's advances.
   The matter is before the Delaware courts because Polaroid, while
based in Cambridge, Mass., is incorporated in Delaware.
   Disney, nephew of the late animator Walt Disney, owns 6.8 percent
of Polaroid and has been pressing a hostile buyout offer since July.
Disney's Shamrock is offering $42 dollars a share for Polaroid
stock, or a total of $2.6 billion.
   That offer, which has been extended periodically as the companies
wrangled in court, was extended again on Tuesday, until 5 p.m. EST
Jan. 19.
</TEXT>
