<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     01-10 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0347</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market slipped lower today in fairly
active trading after having posted gains in the previous four
sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which edged above the
psychologically important 2,200 mark in the first half-hour of
trading at 2,204.29, quickly retreated and was off 7.41 at 2,192.32
at 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outnumber advancing ones about 11 to 8 on the
NYSE, with 570 issues higher, 787 lower and 555 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 103.44 million shares as of 2
p.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said stock traders were keeping a close eye on the
behavior of the bond market and the currency market. Bond prices
were unchanged to slightly higher today, while the dollar rose again
in the foreign-exchange market.
   The stock market was somewhat sluggish because it was still
trying to digest a large set of stocks dumped on it Monday in a sell
program coordinated by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., said Philip Puccio,
manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read &amp; Co.
   Puccio said that according to one estimate, the sell program
accounted for about a third of the volume of trading Monday, or
about 55 million shares.
   But the asset manager rumored to be behind the sale, Renaissance
Investment Management Inc. of Cincinnati, declined to comment on its
involvement.
   ``We are variously accused or ascribed as having done things
beyond the power of mortal men at times,'' said Frank Terrizzi, the
firm's president.
   RJR Nabisco topped the list of most active issues on the New York
Stock Exchange, rising | to 94~.
   Eastman Kodak was down [ at 44], General Electric was down ] at
44\ and NWA, the parent of Northwest Airlines, was up 1\ at 54~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.42 at 157.73. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.13 at 312.41.
</TEXT>
