<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-G&amp;W     01-10 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-G&amp;W,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 11 Percent Profit Gain in 4th Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf &amp; Western Inc. said Tuesday its profit rose
11 percent in its fiscal fourth quarter and 8 percent for the year,
paced by record performances in its finance and
publishing-information businesses.
   The company, which also owns Paramount films and has sizeable
television operations, said it earned $144 million, or $1.21 a
share, in the three months ended Oct. 31 compared with $130 million,
or $1.05 a share, in 1987.
   Revenue for the quarter edged up 2.1 percent, to $1.49 billion
from $1.46 billion a year earlier.
   For the year, the company earned a record $384.7 million, or
$3.21 a share, from $356.1 billion, or $2.88 a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the year rose 8.5 percent, to $5.1 billion from $4.7
billion in 1987.
   Chairman Martin S. Davis said the company's finance arm,
Associates Corp. of North America, had record earnings for the 12th
consecutive year reflecting higher finance charge revenue, an
increase in mortgage lending and increased sales of insurance
products.
   Operating income also rose from publishing and information
services because of advances in consumer publishing and
international operations. The company owns Simon &amp; Schuster,
Prentice-Hall and Pocket Books.
   He said educational publishing matched last year's performance
despite higher development costs for new products aimed at the
secondary and elementary school markets. Operating income from
higher education rose because of strong sales of college textbooks.
   Entertainment operations contributed significantly to the
company's 1988 results, Davis said.
   Gains in television operations and higher box office results from
its Canadian theater chain more than offset a drop in motion picture
earnings and lower exhibition income resulting from the sale of a 50
percent interest in its U.S. theater operations, he said.
   He said the films ``Coming to America'' and ``Crocodile Dundee
II'' posted strong domestic box office performances, while foreign
film revenue rose as a result of the success internationally of the
films ``Fatal Attraction,'' ``The Untouchables,'' ``Beverly Hills
Cop II'' and ``Crocodile Dundee II.''
</TEXT>
