<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0035 01-10 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0035,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished slightly higher Tuesday on
the London Stock Exchange after an uneven day that saw sharp
movements in several speculative stocks.
   Dealers reported a good level of business, despite a significant
leveling off of excitement after Monday's rally, which was fueled
mostly by speculation of an imminent bid for Britain's General
Electric Co. PLC.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended with a
gain of 4.5 points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,836.0.
   At its lowest level in the session, the 100-share index was down
2.9 points at the beginning of the day but by midafternoon had risen
to show a 6.1 point gain.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 1.5 points at 1,503.5
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 2.33 points
to close at 1,033.53.
   Volume declined a bit to 563.5 million shares from Monday's 589.7
million shares.
   The potential bid for GEC, estimated at around 7 billion British
pounds, or about $12.4 billion, would be the largest takeover ever
seen on London's Stock Exchange.
   The bid speculation gained force over the weekend when Lazard
Brothers and Co. revealed a company had been formed to devise a
proposal ``which may or may not'' lead to an offer for GEC. Plessey
Co., itself the target of a 1.7 billion pound ($3 billion) bid from
GEC and West Germany's Siemens AG, is believed to be participating
in the consortium.
   GEC fell 1.5 pence (3 cents) to finish at 219.5 pence ($3.89) on
Tuesday. Plessey was unchanged at 226 pence ($4).
</TEXT>
