<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     01-10 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher In Europe, Gold Also Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished higher against most major
currencies in hectic European trading Tuesday as the market shrugged
off reported light central-bank intervention.
   Gold prices also rose.
   Currency dealers said the dollar began rising early in the
European day, after opening at lower levels in the wake of
intervention by the U.S. Federal Reserve and the West German
Bundesbank on Monday.
   Traders were hesitant to take the dollar above 1.8300 West German
marks for most of the day, but gathered their courage late in the
European session after noting that the Bundesbank had been absent
from the open market.
   The dollar's rise above 1.8300 marks was met by Fed intervention
at around the 1.8315-mark level, dealers said. They said the
intervention was largely ignored because it was followed by comments
from Beryl Sprinkel, the White House chief economic adviser, who
questioned the validity of central-bank intervention.
   ``People are seeing the Fed intervention as a market challenge,
rather than a barrier,'' said one trader.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.39 yen to a closing 125.70. Later, in London, it
was quoted higher at 126.30 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7643 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7650 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.8355 West German marks, up from 1.8245; 1.5645 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5555; 6.2555 French francs, up from 6.2300; 2.0589 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0575; 1,338.50 Italian lire, down from 1,339.75;
and 1.2012 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1955.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $404.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $402.75.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $405.10 an ounce,
compared with $402.75 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 5 cents to close at a bid
$407.23 an ounce.
   Silver bullion in London to a late bid price of $5.98 a troy
ounce, compared with Monday's $5.94.
</TEXT>
