<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Venezuela-OPEC     01-10 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-OPEC,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indonesian minister says possible overproduction not a problem yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overproduction by some members of OPEC
has not become a problem yet as the cartel voluntarily cuts output
to raise prices, Indonesia's oil minister said Tuesday.
   Responding to press reports of alleged overproduction by the
United Arab Emirates, Ginandjar Kartasasmita said OPEC has not
confirmed that the UAE is violating its quota even though he said
the reports should be taken seriously.
   ``Some members may have a reason for overproducing and (cutbacks)
may have to be done gradually. This is permitted by OPEC. What is
not permitted is to put this (overproduction) on the market,''
Kartasasmita told reporters.
   He said a meeting of an eight-member subcommittee of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries charged with
monitoring compliance with the new quota system would be obligatory
if overproduction occurred, but he indicated a meeting would not be
held before February.
   ``We are barely two weeks into the accord and we cannot know what
production will be for January,'' he said.
   OPEC agreed last November to limit production to 18.5 million
barrels a day starting Jan. 1.
   A scheduled meeting of the subcommittee, to which Venezuela and
Indonesia both belong, is set for March.
   Kartasasmita said OPEC will seek cutbacks from a group of
independent producers in a joint meeting Jan. 26 that need not
amount to the 15 to 20 percent reduction OPEC is imposing on its
members.
   ``We don't ask for that much. It's up to them to decide how much
they want to cut. We are not demanding anything, but any cut will
help,'' the minister said.
   He said that OPEC would not be able to reach its price aim of $18
per barrel without total member compliance and without cooperation
from non-OPEC producers.
   He said Indonesia is estimating its average price this year at
$14 a barrel as part of a government policy to wean the island
nation from its dependence on oil income.
   Kartasasmita arrived in Caracas Monday for a five-day official
visit which has included talks with Venezuelan Energy Minister Julio
Cesar Gil and Venezuelan president-elect Carlos Andres Perez.
   He said Indonesia supports Perez' proposal for a summit of OPEC
heads of state in 1990, the year of OPEC's 30th anniversary.
   The two countries are exploring technical cooperation in oil
between the Indonesian state oil company Pertamina and Petroleos de
Venezuela S.A. and increasing bilateral trade in non-oil goods.
   Kartasasmita plans to visit OPEC member Ecuador and independent
producers Colombia and Mexico following his scheduled Friday
departure from Venezuela.
   Perez, who will be inaugurated Feb. 2, is scheduled to visit
Iran, Iraq and United Arab Emirates next week to drum up support for
an OPEC summit.
   

