<FIRST>u f BC-Japan-Honda 1stLd-Writethru   01-10 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Honda, 1st Ld-Writethru,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honda Sees More Than Tenfold Increase in U.S.-Imported Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf Honda expects ..., to CORRECT that Honda does
not expect decline in sales in North America this year; picks up 6th graf,
Japanese automakers ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co. expects a more than tenfold increase
in two years in the number of autos it produces in the United States
and imports to Japan, Honda President Tadashi Kume said Tuesday.
   Last year, Japan's No. 3 automaker imported to Japan 5,385
two-door Accord coupes made at its Marysville, Ohio, plant. It was
the first time Honda imported cars it produced in the United States.
   Honda expects to import about 4,600 Accords this year from the
United States, ``but by 1991, when we plan to sell 800,000 autos in
the domestic (Japanese) market, we plan to import 50,000 cars from
Ohio,'' Kume told a news conference.
   Honda, which sells more cars in the United States than any other
Japanese manufacturer, will produce about 360,000 cars in the United
States this year, but increase production in Canada from 50,000 to
80,000, Kume said.
   Honda expects to sell 800,000 autos in the United States this
year, including imports, up from 769,000 in 1988, a U.S. spokesman
said.
   Japanese automakers still experience difficulties in selling cars
in the United States because of the high value of the yen, Kume
said. The yen has doubled in value against the U.S. dollar since
1985, making Japanese products more expensive overseas.
   Kume said Honda would increase the number of dealerships in the
United States to 1,300, but did not give the present number.
   Honda's total auto production in Japan this year is expected to
be 1.41 million, up 8.3 percent. About half of those are exported,
and this year Honda expects to sell 685,000 cars in Japan, 10.9
percent more than last year.
   Production of the five-door Concerto developed jointly with
Britain's Austin Rover Group will begin this fall, and the cars will
be sold in Britain and elsewhere in Europe, Kume said.
   He said the Japanese government's decision Tuesday to continue
limiting auto exports to the United States would not affect Honda,
which fell short of its quota last year.
   ``Whether (the quotas) are continued or abolished, I don't expect
a change in the number of vehicles shipped to the United States,''
he said.
   Honda is Japan's third-largest automaker after Toyota and Nissan.
Toyota produced 4.22 million cars in Japan and abroad in 1988 and
expects to make 4.41 million this year. Nissan produced about 2.73
million autos last year and plans to make some 2.91 million this
year.
   Honda, the world's largest manufacturer of motorcycles, began
making motorbikes in 1948 and diversified into building cars in
1963. Last year was also the first time Honda began importing to
Japan the 1,500-cubic centimeter Goldwing motorcycles it builds in
Marysville.
   It will sell 1 million motorcycles in Japan this year, up 9.8
percent, and export 560,000, a 12 percent increase, Kume said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
