<TEXT>
   The stock market slipped lower today in active
trading after having posted gains in the previous four sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which edged above the
psychologically important 2,200 mark in the first half-hour of
trading at 2,204.29, quickly retreated and was off 7.67 at 2,191.79
an hour before the close.
   Declining issues outnumber advancing ones about 3 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 560 issues higher, 848 lower and 531 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 119.77 million shares as of 3
p.m. EST.
   Analysts said stock traders were keeping a close eye on the
behavior of the bond market and the currency market. Bond prices
were unchanged to slightly higher in early trading today, while the
dollar remained stable in the foreign-exchange market.
   The stock market was somewhat sluggish because it was still
trying to digest a large set of stocks dumped on it Monday in a sell
program coordinated by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., said Philip Puccio,
manager of institutional trading at Dillon, Read &amp; Co.
   Puccio said that according to one estimate, the sell program
accounted for about a third of the volume of trading Monday, or
about 55 million shares.
   But the asset manager rumored to be behind the sale, Renaissance
Investment Management Inc. of Cincinnati, declined to comment on its
involvement.
   ``We are variously accused or ascribed as having done things
beyond the power of mortal men at times,'' said Frank Terrizzi, the
firm's president.
   Among active issues on the New York Stock Exchange, RJR Nasbisco
was up | at 94~, International Business Machines was down | at 121],
Eastman Kodak was unchanged at 44{ and NWA, the parent of Northwest
Airlines, was up 1{ at 55[.
   Sun Microsystems was among the most active over-the-counter
issues, declining } to 16. Digital Equipment unveiled workstations
that compete with Sun's.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.53 at 157.62. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.26 at 312.28.
