<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-IBM-Corning     01-10 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-Corning,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM To Buy 25 Percent Of Fiber Optics Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. will buy 25
percent of a fiber-optics company owned by Corning Glass Works, the
companies said Tuesday in a signal of the growing importance of
fiber to the computing world.
   The value of the deal was not disclosed.
   PCO Inc., a 175-employee company based in the Chatsworth area of
Los Angeles, specializes in devices that convert electronic signals
to light and vice versa.
   Until now, fiber optics have been used mainly for long-distance
telephone lines. IBM's investment signals the company's idea that
the speed permitted by fiber optics will be useful in the computer
field, spokesman Paul Bergevin said today.
   Corning, based in Corning, N.Y., made an additional investment in
PCO and will keep a 65 percent interest in the company. The
remaining 10 percent will be owned by PCO employees, founders and
other individuals.
   Instead of using wires, computer users are beginning to connect
clusters of personal computers and workstations with high-capacity
fiber-optic cables, said John Kessler, president of Kessler
Marketing Intelligence in Newport, R.I.
   ``That market grew about 100 percent between 1987 and 1988 and
will continue very heavy growth over the next five years,'' Kessler
said.
   A longer-range goal is to use fiber optics inside computers to
connect chips, and even to use light signals on chips, but PCO is
probably not well-equipped in that area, Kessler said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CableTV     01-10 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable TV,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compromise Predicted for Cable Operators, Local Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable operators and broadcasters, both fearing
phone company intrusion into their businesses, could reach a
compromise early this year on requiring cable systems to carry local
TV stations on their channels, the cable industry's chief spokesman
said Tuesday.
   ``The instant we get the signal from Congress, we will be at the
table, and we have every reason to believe the negotiations will not
need to be protracted,'' said James Mooney, president of the
National Cable Television Association.
   The Federal Communications Commission had required cable
operators to include all local broadcasters in their service areas
on their channels until 1985, when the regulations were struck down
by the courts as unconstitutional.
   At the time, some cable systems faced the prospect of having to
give up other programming because of a plethora of new broadcasters
consuming their channel capacity.
   The cable association and the National Association of
Broadcasters agreed on new ``must carry'' regulations that basically
would have reserved up to one-fourth of a cable system's channels
for local broadcasters, but it, too, was struck down by the courts.
   Because of the court's rulings and the FCC's reluctance to tackle
the issue again on its own, any compromise providing some kind of
legal mandate for cable access for local broadcasters will likely
require a congressional mandate, Mooney said.
   Legislation to do that was considered by the last Congress but it
ended up getting held hostage to President Reagan's vetos of bill
reinstating the ``Fairness Doctrine'' that the FCC repealed in 1987
and regulating the type and amount of advertising on shows aimed at
children.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee, already has introduced a new bill to reinstate
the Fairness Doctrine requiring broadcasters to cover issues of
public importance and reflect differing views on those issues in
their programing.
   Dingell said last week that he also was willing to tackle the
``must carry'' issue again when Congress begins work after the
inauguration.
   However, it is not clear yet whether the ``must carry'' cable
measure that broadcasters want will be handled alone or as part of a
package that includes the Fairness Doctrine and restrictions on
children's advertising, both of which broadcasters oppose.
   Industry officials said Dingell and other lawmakers may try to
pass the Fairness Doctrine and children's advertising measures first
to see how President-elect Bush reacts before considering the cable
access issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
