<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Autos 1stLd-Writethru   01-10 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Officials Announce Continuation of Auto Restraints</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mitsuzuka in grafs 2-3.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will continue voluntary restraints in its auto
exports to the United States for the eighth straight year, the
Japanese trade minister said Tuesday.
   Although Japanese car exports to the United States have been
below the self-imposed quota of 2.3 million autos annually, Japan
will keep the restraints in place, Minister of International Trade
and Industry Hiroshi Mitsuzuka said.
   The government is not convinced that auto exports have
permanently declined, Mitsuzuka told a news conference.
   Japanese auto exports to the United States in fiscal 1987, which
ended in March 1988, were 2.21 million, and shipments from
April-November were 10.4 percent below a year earlier, Mitsuzuka
said.
   ``However, if we removed the quota, we are concerned that there
are companies which are aggressively marketing in the United States,
and a declining tendency doesn't seem to be stabilized yet,'' he
said.
   He left open the possibility that the quota could be removed in
the middle of the forthcoming fiscal year if the ministry decides
that the decline is not reversing.
   Japanese automakers had little reaction, saying tersely that they
would accept the measures.
   ``The decision to extend the voluntary restraints was made by the
two governments in consideration of current U.S.-Japan trade and
economic relations,'' said Shoichi Toyoda, president of Toyota Motor
Corp., Japan's largest automaker, and chairman of the Japan
Association of Auto Manufacturers. ``It is a decision we will abide
with.''
   Nissan and Honda, the country's No. 2 and No. 3 auto
manufacturers, have fallen short of their export quotas, but Toyota
has been fulfilling its estimated 450,000-500,000 car share annually.
   The automakers do not release their actual quota figures.
   Free trade is desirable and the quota system has lost its
original significance, but the matter must ``be studied in the frame
of U.S.-Japan relations as a whole. ... We believe the government
made its conclusion taking this into consideration,'' said Nissan
President Yutaka Kume.
   Some U.S. lawmakers insist that Japanese cars built in the United
States should also be counted as imports. But Mitsuzuka told
reporters that by 1991, the local content of U.S.-made Japanese cars
would be 75 percent, ``and we regard them as American-made cars.''
   Japanese makers produced 733,000 cars in the United States from
January-November 1988, up 23.2 percent from same period of 1987,
according to the Foreign Ministry.
   Last year Japanese news reports said the trade ministry would
lift the export quota because it was outdated, but that idea was
abandoned because of concern about giving Washington the wrong
impression at a time of rising protectionist sentiment in the United
States.
   The quota system dates from 1981, when Japan was under strong
pressure from the U.S. government and American automakers to cut
Japanese exports and allow the U.S. auto industry to retrench and
restructure. Japan agreed to limit its annual exports to the United
States to 1.68 million vehicles through 1983, then to 1.85 million
in 1984.
   When U.S. President Ronald Reagan decided not to ask for
continued restraints in 1985, Japan set the ceiling at 2.3 million
and has maintained that figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
