<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   01-10 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices edged lower Tuesday as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks crept above the 2,200 barrier for a
fourth straight session only to finish below the mark again.
   The Dow Jones industrials closed at 2,193.21, a decline of 6.25
points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
621 up, 816 down and 543 unchanged.
   Traders said the market seemed to be catching its breath after
having advanced in every session of 1989 except the first, setting
three post-crash highs in the process.
   The stock market is only slightly below where it stood right
before the stock market crash of Oct. 19, 1987. The session before
its 508-point plunge, the Dow Jones industrial average had closed at
2,246.74.
   There was no major economic news affecting the stock market
Tuesday, although stocks got continued support from bonds and the
dollar.
   The dollar rose in spite of reports of continued dollar-selling
by the Federal Reserve, which is trying to restrain the currency's
rise. The dollar's strength helped buoy bonds, which finished
slightly higher.
   Nevertheless, high interest rates, particularly for short-term
instruments, remain an attractive alternative to stocks.
   The Dow Jones industrials cracked 2,200 during the trading day on
Thursday, Friday, Monday and again Tuesday before retreating each
time.
   ``There's always been a slight tendency of the market to view
century marks as psychological barriers,'' said Robert S. Robbins, a
market strategist and technical analyst at Robinson-Humphrey Co. in
Atlanta.
   The stock market was somewhat sluggish because it was still
trying to digest stocks dumped on it Monday in a big sell program
coordinated by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., said Philip Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon, Read &amp; Co.
   The asset manager rumored to be behind the sale, Renaissance
Investment Management Inc. of Cincinnati, declined to comment on its
involvement.
   ``We are variously accused or ascribed as having done things
beyond the power of mortal men at times,'' said Frank Terrizzi, the
firm's president.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 140.42 million
shares, down from 163.18 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 166.10 million shares.
   Among active issues on the New York Stock Exchange, RJR Nasbisco
rose | to 94~, International Business Machines fell ~ to 121[,
Eastman Kodak was unchanged at 44{ and NWA, the parent of Northwest
Airlines, rose 1} to 55].
   Sun Microsystems was among the most active over-the-counter
issues, declining { to 16\. Digital Equipment unveiled workstations
that compete with Sun's.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the overall market fell $5.200 billion, or
0.19 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.30 to 157.85.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 0.71 to 324.33, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index fell 0.60 to 280.38.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
0.69 to 384.59. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 312.95, down 0.59.
</TEXT>
