<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-10 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Dive On Arbitrage and Harvest-Linked Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices dropped sharply Tuesday on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange amid heavy arbitrage selling and
rumors of large export shipments from the Ivory Coast, the world's
largest cocoa producer.
   On other markets, coffee futures rallied; precious metals
declined; energy, grain, soybean, livestock and meat futures were
mixed; and stock-index futures retreated.
   Cocoa settled $56 to $73 lower with the contract for delivery in
March at $1,352 a metric ton.
   The decline _ the fourth in as many sessions _ was partly a
result of arbitrage selling linked to the dollar's gain in value
against the British pound, analysts said.
   When the dollar increases in value against the pound, as it did
on Tuesday, cocoa traders can profit by selling cocoa futures for
dollars in New York and buying the same amount of cocoa futures for
pounds on the London Terminal Market.
   Further selling was prompted by rumors of a large number of
shipment declarations by the Ivory Coast, which until recently had
been withholding its top-quality cocoa from the market in hopes of
forcing prices higher, analysts said.
   ``The market turned bearish on sentiments that near-term
availability of Ivorian cocoa could be up substantially from what it
has been recently,'' said Sandra Kaul, an analyst in New York with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   She said the world cocoa harvest was at its peak with production
expected to outweigh demand for the fifth straight year.
   A rumored deal among the Ivory Coast, the French government and a
large French trade house to withhold Ivorian cocoa from the market
is increasingly being perceived as a bearish factor, since it will
only add to the surplus overhanging the market, analysts said.
   New York Coffee futures managed a modest rally after two days of
steep losses. Coffee settled 1.98 cents to 2.59 cents higher with
March at $1.5048 a pound.
   Gold futures extended their slide to five days and silver made
new life-of-contract lows on New York's Commodity Exchange in quiet
selling linked to the dollar's strength.
   But analysts said gold's refusal so far to test the
psychologically important level of $400 a troy ounce was encouraging
for bullish players. Gold for spot delivery on the exchange finished
the day at $403.80.
   ``With the market that close (to $400), it would be easy enough
to challenge it,'' said Craig Sloane, an analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   Gold futures settled $1 to $1.10 lower with February at $405.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 4.7 cents to 4.8 cents lower with March at
$5.995 a troy ounce.
   Wheat and soybean futures ended mostly lower while corn futures
finished narrowly mixed in a quiet session on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   The markets opened mostly lower, then rallied early in the
session in reaction to lighter-than-expected rain in Argentina, the
world's fourth-largest soybean producer.
   Wheat settled { cent to 2 cents lower with March at $4.46} a
bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.89{
a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 1\ cents higher with March at
$2.39 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 4 cents lower with
January at $8.02{ a bushel.
   Energy futures finished narrowly mixed amid a lack of new
supply-demand developments on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 4 cents lower
with February at $17.69 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent lower to
.03 cent higher with February at 53.86 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .06 cent lower to .15 cent higher with February at
47.91 cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
buoyed by higher cash markets, while pork futures finished mixed in
a choppy session marked by weakening supply-demand factors, analsyts
said.
   Live cattle settled .35 cent to .47 cent higher with February at
74.02 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .65 cent higher
with January at 85.27 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower
to .43 cent higher with February at 46.17 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.10 cents lower to .15 cent higher with February at
42.60 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 index settled .50 point lower at 283.20. Each point is
worth $500.
</TEXT>
