<FIRST>u f AM-Texaco-Canada     01-10 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texaco-Canada,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Preparing To Announce Winner Of Texaco Canada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. may announce the winning bid for its
lucrative Canadian subsidiary, Texaco Canada Inc., as early as this
week although company officials continued to refuse comment on the
deal Tuesday.
   Texaco spokesman Peter Maneri said the company could neither
confirm nor deny that Monday was the closing date for accepting bids.
   Analysts have said the sale of Texaco Canada could fetch up to $4
billion for its parent company, or more than $5.5 billion if an
offer is made to all shareholders. Texaco owns 78 percent of Texaco
Canada, the fifth-largest oil company in Canada.
   Maneri said the company had signed an agreement to keep the
bidding confidential and could not disclose details of the proposed
sale.
   ``We have said the bidding is progressing satisfactorily,''
Maneri said. ``But we're not confirming or denying anything else.
We're just not commenting.''
   Among the Texaco Canada assets up for sale, according to Texaco
Canada spokesman Brian Hay, are approximately 100,000 barrels per
day of natural gas and crude oil properties mainly in Alberta; a
95,000 barrel-per-day refinery in Nanticoke; a 15,000 barrel-per-day
refinery in Halifax; and 1,800 service stations located across
Canada with 10-12 percent of the retail market.
   On Tuesday, Texaco Canada shares closed at $38 a share in
composite trading on the American Stock Exchange, down slightly from
$38.25 on Monday. Last Thursday, Texaco Canada's stock reached the
$38 mark, its highest level in a year, after climbing 87{ cents.
   Meanwhile on the New York Stock Exchange, Texaco Inc.'s shares
closed at $53.12{, up from $53 on Monday.
   Texaco began accepting bids for the Toronto-based oil company
last August. Analysts speculate that since then the field of
possible bidders has narrowed considerably.
   Imperial Oil of Toronto, owned 69 percent by Exxon Corp., has
been widely named as a possible bidder. Calgary-based Husky Oil _
jointly controlled by petrochemical giant Nova Corp. of Calgary and
Union Faith of Hong Kong _ has a long-standing interest in Texaco
Canada. Neither company would comment on whether a bid was made.
   Bond Corp., owned by Australian tycoon Alan Bond, and Royal
Dutch-Shell Group of the Netherlands have also been touted as
possible suitors.
   ``Any of the national oil companies of other countries
(Venezuela, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia) that are being talked about
might be a fit,'' said oil analyst Wilf Gobert of Peters and Co. in
Calgary.
</TEXT>
