<HEAD>TW Services Rejects Coniston Offer to Ease Conditions of Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TW Services Inc. said Tuesday it had rejected an
offer by Coniston Partners to ease the conditions on Coniston's $1.4
billion bid for the food services company.
   TW Services said its chairman, Frank L. Salizzoni, sent a letter
to the New York-based investment firm, refusing to take any action
on the company's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense and refusing
to waive a requirement that a takeover must be approved by the TW
Services board.
   Last week, Coniston said it would no longer insist on winning
approval from the board before continuing with its offer if TW
Services dropped the poison pill, either voluntarily or by court
order.
   In his letter, Salizzoni reiterated TW Services' skepticism about
the sincerity of the Coniston bid and said the company would not
consider any action on the poison pill ``until such time as your
`offer' has become firm and it is absolutely clear you are committed
to acquiring the company.''
   Augustus K. Oliver, a principal of Coniston, called TW Services'
response ``an unfortunate continuation of the same attitude that the
board has expressed so far to our offer.''
   ``It's something we find very difficult to understand,
particularly in the fact that almost 88 percent of the stock has
been tendered to us,'' Oliver said.
