<FIRST>u f AM-KmartSuit     01-10 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K mart Suit,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>K mart Loses $73 Million Breach of Contract Judgment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discount retailer K mart Corp. breached
its contract with a wholesaler clothing buyer and must pay $73
million in damages, a federal jury decided Tuesday.
   After four months of testimony, the six-person jury deliberated
for 8{ hours before returning the verdict to U.S. District Judge
Ronald R. Lagueux.
   ``We were disappointed,'' said Robert Stephenson, a spokesman at
K Mart headquarters in Troy, Mich. ``We plan to appeal the verdict
on the basis that the judge made a number of substantial errors in
judgment during the trial.''
   Fashion House charged that K mart ignored a 1983 agreement
requiring the retailer to purchase 85 percent of its name brand and
designer label apparel through the wholesaler.
   K mart canceled the four-year contract in April 1986, shortly
after Fashion House filed suit against it for unpaid commissions.
   Robert W. Steele, a K Mart attorney, told the jury the contract
was canceled not because of the impending lawsuit, but because
Fashion House repeatedly failed to obtain the name brand merchandise
the retailer wanted.
   He said the stock K mart received came in broken lots, odd sizes
and unattractive colors, and that the retailer lost $45 million in
its Designer Depot stores, which Fashion House stocked almost
exclusively.
   Fashion House attorney Richard Sharfman said that by 1984 K mart
had already begun to ignore the terms of the contract and was
purchasing more than 15 percent of its clothing directly from
manufacturers.
   Steele did not address the argument of K mart's breach of
contract by buying directly from the manufacturers, but called the
plantiff's request for $80 million in damages ``an outrageous
exercise in greed.''
   The jury awarded Fashion House $30.7 million for unpaid
commissions, $28.7 million for wrongful termination of contract, and
ordered K Mart to pay $13.6 million in interest on the award.
   ``The jury has vindicated Fashion House'', Sharfman said.
   He had argued that his client's buying acumen helped turn K mart
around in the early 1980s, bringing in the brand names that helped
boost apparel sales and profits.
   K Mart had $25.6 billion in sales in fiscal 1987. In late
December it owned 2,265 K Mart stores, 1,231 Walden Books, 266
Payless drugstores and 133 Builders Square stores.
   The Pawtucket-based Fashion House, which dealt almost soley with
K Mart, went out of business in 1986, Sharfman said. At its peak in
1983, it had $188 million in sales and 100 employees in New York and
Pawtucket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PanAm     01-10 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Puts Profitable Unit Up for Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp., strapped by losses from its main
airline subsidiary, announced Tuesday that it has put another,
profitable unit up for sale.
   Pan Am said its board of directors has decided to sell the
company's World Services subsidiary, which markets security,
maintenance and other services to government agencies and other
airlines.
   World Services had revenue of $550 million and pretax profit of
$23 million in 1987, Pan Am said in a statement. Financial analysts
estimate the unit's potential sale value at around $200 million.
   The flagship airline unit, Pan American World Airways, continues
to drain the company's finances. World Airways' net loss of $54.7
million in the first nine months of last year contributed heavily to
the parent's net loss of $21 million on revenue of $3.2 billion in
the same period.
   The sale of World Services ``will sharply improve Pan Am's
working capital position,'' said Robert Joedicke, an airline analyst
for investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``This is their
negative cash flow period.''
   Pan Am's Northeast shuttle service and Pan Am Express, a commuter
airline, also are considered profitable operations. But they are
more closely tied to World Airways than is the World Services unit.
   Eastern Airlines recently sold its shuttle service, which
competes with Pan Am's, to real estate developer Donald Trump for
$365 million in cash.
   Some analysts wondered whether the World Services move
represented a new Pan Am strategy to sell performing assets rather
than strip away parts of loss-making World Airways, such as routes
and airport facilities.
   But Pan Am spokesman Jeffrey Kriendler said the decision to sell
the unit is based on the recognition that ``our primary business is
the airline business.'' The company considers the Pan Am Shuttle and
Pan Am Express to be part of that business, he said.
   Kriendler said the sale of World Services has been under
discussion by Pan Am management for several months, as a way to help
finance its planned investments for the near future. Those
investments include $61 million for improvements at World Airways'
main terminal at Kennedy International Airport in New York, $25
million for refurbishing aircraft interiors, $20 million for
improvements in information systems and other programs, Pan Am said
in the statement.
   To finance the projects, Pan Am also will use the $115 million
payment it got recently from Airbus Industrie, a European aircraft
consortium. Pan Am decided to scrap a firm order for 16 Airbus A320s
in exchange for the payment.
   The 16 planes originally intended for Pan Am were included in a
$3.5 billion deal announced last Wednesday by regional airline
Braniff Inc., which will acquire 50 A320s and take options on 50
more. The deal nearly tripled the size of Braniff's fleet.
   Analysts expect potential buyers of World Services to be service
companies rather than airlines, with aerospace company Lockheed
Services rumored to be one of the interested parties.
   Last July, United Airlines sold its United Airlines Services
Corp. to Flight Safety International, which runs training programs,
for an undisclosed amount.
   ``It's a wide open kind of thing; there are lots of concerns that
could be interested,'' said Edward Starkman, an airline analyst for
PaineWebber Inc.
   Kriendler confirmed that the World Services unit would likely be
sold to a non-airline company.
</TEXT>
