<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms     01-10 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Extends Deadline For Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. said Tuesday it was
extending indefinitely its previous deadline of Wednesday for
receiving new bids from two companies that have offered to buy the
food processor.
   Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark., has been trying to take
over Holly Farms since October and has offered $60 a share for Holly
Farms stock.
   Holly Farms has tried to resist Tyson's advances by agreeing to a
merger with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., but that agreement has been
put on hold by a Delaware court.
   Holly Farms announced last week that its board of directors would
consider additional offers from Tyson and ConAgra at a meeting
Wednesday. Other bidders are free to make offers too, but Holly
Farms said no others are expected.
   Ted Bailey, a Holly Farms spokesman, said consideration of new
bids has been delayed because of request by Tyson for additional
business information on Holly Farms.
   ``A revised schedule for the submission of final bids will be
announced after the (board) meeting,'' Bailey said.
   Tyson's latest bid is worth some $1.06 billion in cash, while
Holly Farms' proposed merger with ConAgra calls for a stock swap
worth about $1 billion.
   ConAgra has refused to say if it will counter Tyson's bid.
   Tyson Foods is the nation's largest poultry processor while Holly
Farms is a diversified company depending heavily on fresh fryer
sales.
