<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 1833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CableProspects Bjt   01-10 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable Prospects, Bjt,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable TV System Sales Show Demand Still Strong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estimated $2 billion price being paid for two
large cable television systems shows the market for cable remains
surprisingly strong despite the recent spate of systems for sale.
   Media analysts and brokers say the market is likely to remain
bullish because the industry's days of heaviest construction
spending are over and deregulation has given cable systems more
freedom to raise basic rates.
   Also supporting system prices is the trend of advertisers
spending more on cable and the expectation that more homes will sign
up for cable service.
   For the moment, these concerns appear to be outweighing the
perceived risks that telephone companies may be allowed to compete
in the cable business and that Congress could step in to break up
the bigger cable system operators.
   Some of the new owners are also bringing a new frame of reference
to the cable business that is likely to fuel more efficient growth,
analysts say.
   ``We have a business that was driven by engineers that is just
now starting to be run by managers and marketers,'' said John Waller
III, president of the media brokerage firm Waller Capital Corp.
   That is likely to be a plus, he said, especially as systems make
technological improvements that make it easier for subscribers to
take additional services, such as pay-per-view programming.
   In the latest deals in the cable business, Cooke Cablevision Inc.
and the New York Times Co. announced separately Monday that they
have agreed to sell cable television systems in transactions
estimated to value nearly $2 billion.
   The New York Times Co. said it is selling its system in southern
New Jersey for $420 million to a concern that will be managed by a
minority investment group. With 162,000 subscribers, the price came
to about $2,600 per subscriber.
   Investor Jack Kent Cooke, who controls Cooke Cablevision,
declined to reveal the sales price of his cable systems, which have
about 700,000 subscribers and are being sold to a consortium of
cable companies.
   But published reports citing unidentified sources in the
purchasing group put the sale price at $2,100 to $2,200 per
subscriber, or about $1.5 billion.
   The reason Cooke got less per subscriber for his holdings than
the Times did, analysts said, is that his properties are scattered
over 19 states.
   The number and value of cable system sales has risen as the
industry consolidates and some owners capitalize on the values being
placed on systems.
   Paula Greer, who works for the media research firm Paul Kagan
Associates Inc. of Carmel, Calif., said 407 deals were announced in
the first 11 months of 1988 worth $13.2 billion, up from 399 deals
worth $9.5 billion at the same point in 1987.
   The average price per subscriber was $1,971 in the 1988 period,
up 16.5 percent from the $1,692 per subscriber average reported in
the same 1987 period, she said.
   Ms. Greer said the market for cable systems appears to have
leveled off at a price-per-subscriber of between $2,000 and $2,500
for the better systems.
   ``We have reached a plateau and probably will stay there halfway
through next year as people get comfortable with it,'' she said.
   Michael Kupinski, media analyst for A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc. in
St. Louis, said the industry can look forward to revenue growth of
12 percent a year over the next few years with 5 percent coming from
higher rates, 5 percent from subscriber growth and 2 percent from
growth in ancillary services, such as advertising.
   He said basic rates rose by an average of 18 percent in 1987 and
11.5 percent in 1988, the first two years since deregulation. But he
said operators are apt to limit future rises because of ``public and
congressional concern over dergulated cable rates.''
   Nielsen Media Research estimated that 53.8 percent of the 90.4
million American television households subscribed to cable last
November.
   Kupinski said ``although the easy subscriber growth from wiring
the nation is behind the industry,'' operators should be able to
expand the number of subscribers further with more aggressive
marketing.
   Kupinski said advertising on cable systems rose 41 percent to
$230 million in 1987 from the previous year, and said cable's low
cost relative to commercial television, improved ratings and its
attractive audience makeup should push ad revenue up 25 percent a
year to nearly $1 billion by 1993.
   On the downside, the analysts say, are uncertainty about whether
the former Bell System telephone copmpanies will be allowed to
compete in the cable business, creating more competition for cable
systems.
   They also said it is uncertain whether a consumer backlash over
higher rates will prompt Congress to require some of the bigger
multi-system owners to divest some of their holdings.
   But Kupinski noted even if size limits on cable companies were
introduced, ``cable companies would be expected to seek acquaitions,
concentrating on properties near existing operations.''
</TEXT>
