<FIRST>r f AM-HasbroMarketing     01-10 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hasbro Marketing,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hasbro Agrees to Sell Competitor's Toys Overseas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hasbro Inc.'s agreement to market a
competitor's toys overseas is a case where everybody wins, a toy
industry analyst says.
   Hasbro and View-Master Ideal Group announced an agreement this
week under which Hasbro will sell View-Master products in most of
Western Europe, as well as in Australia and New Zealand.
   ``It's one of those rare deals where no one is the loser,'' said
Sean McGowan, toy industry analyst for Balis Zorn Gerard Inc. of New
York.
   The agreement probably will yield less than $10 million this year
for Hasbro, which has annual sales of about $1.3 billion, said
Alfred J. Verrecchia, executive vice president.
   Although it is a very small proportion of Hasbro's business,
``It's added sales volume without any real increase in cost,''
Verrecchia said. ``It should be profitable for us.''
   View-Master benefits from Hasbro's broader overseas sales force,
which should boost its revenues while helping the company cut costs
to reverse losses, said Marvin Schmalzreid, View-Master's chief
financial officer.
   View-Master, based in Beaverton, Ore., lost almost $7 million, or
$1.48 a share, in the nine months ended last Sept. 30.
   Under the deal, Hasbro will distribute the Magna Doodle magnetic
drawing toy, which is View-Master's most popular product, and gets
to choose what other product it wants to distribute, Schmalzreid
said.
   View-Master makes the View-Master 3D Viewer, a staple of the toy
industry for 50 years. It also makes chemistry sets, Dunk-It
child-sized basketball sets and various games.
   The agreement comes almost a year after both companies briefly
discussed a merger, then broke off talks.
   Under the deal, Hasbro will buy View-Master products and resell
them. Hasbro will make additional payments based on sales volume.
</TEXT>
