<FIRST>u f AM-Unisys-Indictment     01-10 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unisys-Indictment,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Indictment Charges Dismissed, Predecessor Sperry Charges Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed charges
holding Unisys Corp. responsible for a predecessor's actions but
retained the case against the original firm, Sperry Corp., and a
retired Air Force colonel, according to documents filed Tuesday.
   The charges against Unisys were dismissed by the U.S. District
Court in Montgomery, Ala., Dec. 29, two months after Unisys and
Sperry were indicted.
   The government alleged the former Sperry Federal Information
Systems Division had falsely billed the government for $501,600 for
work that was never performed as part of a eight-year, $526 million
contract to modernize the Air Force's computer network.
   U.S. District Judge Joel Dubina left intact the indictment
against Sperry and retired Ar Force Col. Robert L. Hedges, 51, of
Montgomery, who oversaw the computer project for the Air Force
before his retirement in 1984.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Al Agricola said federal prosecutors were
unsure how to prosecute Sperry because the company no longer exists,
having been absorbed in a 1986 merger with Burroughs Corp.
   The court noted that although Unisys will not be held liable for
Sperry's actions, the company may have to pay fines.
   Hedges is charged with negotiating a consulting job with Sperry
while he was overseeing the contract from Gunter Air Force Base in
Montgomery, according to U.S. Attorney Jim Wilson.
   Hedges, who was under contract to Unisys at the time of the
indictment, is no longer employed by the company, according to
company officials.
   Unisys spokeswoman Charlotte LeGates said the corporation was
``gratified that the court confirmed the important distinction
between Unisys and a predecessor company in connection with events
that preceded the merger.''
   A copy of the court's opinion dismissing the Unisys charges was
filed Tuesday with the Securities and Exchange Commission, according
to LeGates.
   ``In this case, Unisys Corp., which was not even formed until
over two years after the alleged criminal conduct, could not be
culpable therefore and, thus, should not be held criminally
liable,'' the judge ruled.
   The judge said Sperry was incorporated in Delaware and, under the
laws of that state, Sperry ``would survive the merger for purposes
of pending criminal actions.''
   LeGates said company officials were unclear as to the amount of
fines and whether Unisys would have to pay a fine levied against
Sperry.
   She said Unisys would continue to contest the federal charges,
but Rod Nachman, a Montgomery attorney representing Unisys, said
Dubina's order closes the case as far as his client.
   Agricola said the statute of limitations has expired in the case
and no new indictments can be issued. He said Sperry has not been
arraigned and no trial date has been set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
