<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 2334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BankruptcyFiling     01-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bankruptcy Filing,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scottsdale Firm Files for Chapter 11 Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residential Resources Mortgage Investments Corp.,
a real estate investment trust, filed for reorganization under
federal bankruptcy laws Tuesday and announced the resignations of
its top officers.
   The filing under Chapter 11 of the federal bankrupty code allows
Residential Resources to reorganize its finances while being
protected from creditors' claims.
   The firm, which went public in late June, ran short of cash
because of rising interest rates and shackles imposed under certain
loan agreements, according to a statement issued by Morgen-Walke
Associates, a public relations firm representing Residential
Resources.
   The release said Residential Resources fell $13 million behind in
the collateral requirements of one lender and suffered a $6 million
loss when another lender sold part of the collateral for its loan
agreements with Residential Resources.
   Edward Nebb, a Morgen-Walke employee, declined to identify the
lenders.
   All of Residential Resource's top executives have resigned, and
the company is being run by an outside board of directors, Nebb said.
   The firm's officers were: chairman and president James C.
Marshall; vice president Joseph M. Corrigan; and chief financial
officer Roger F. McMahon.
   Residential Resources' stock was traded on the American Stock
Exchange. Based on Monday's price of about $7.50 per share,
Residential Resources was worth about $50 million. However, the
Washington-based National Association of Real Estate Investment
Trusts said the firm had a book value of $800 million, with
shareholders' equity worth $68 million.
   A real estate investment trust, or REIT, is an investment vehicle
in which small investors participate in a portfolio of real estate
assets managed by a trust such as Residential Resources.
   Residential Resources sidestepped the usual investment pattern
for a real estate trust firm, said Chris Lucas of the association.
   Lucas said the Arizona company had invested in the residual
interest in collateralized mortgage obligations and the equally
risky, principal-only, mortgage-backed securities.
   ``They did a lot of different things than even the REITs that
invest in CMO-residuals do, and Residential Resources has been much
more highly leveraged than most CMO-residual REITs,'' he said.
   CMOs are bonds secured by collateral on pools of home mortgages.
   ``They are a volatile instrument,'' Lucas said. ``Potentially,
they return big yields, but along with that comes a higher risk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890110-0313 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-10-89 0029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Interco     01-10 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Interco,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Measures Lead to Lower Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc., citing a $2.8 billion
restructuring plan it adopted to fight a hostile takeover bid, said
Monday its 1988 third-quarter earnings dropped 75.8 percent.
   Interco reported net earnings for the three months ending Nov. 30
of $10.5 million, or 29 cents per share, compared with $43.4
million, or $1.05 per share, for the same period the previous year.
   The furniture and apparel retailer and manufacturer said its
pretax earnings were reduced by $21.8 million in interest charges
and $14 million in restructuring costs.
   Interco has estimated that costs associated with the
restructuring _ undertaken to thwart the hostile takeover bid by
brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington, D.C. _ will exceed
$65 million.
   The company said its sales from continuing operations totaled
$683.3 million, compared with $680.8 million a year earlier.
   Interco, which last week sold its Londontown Corp. clothing
subsidiary for $178 million, still holds 10 apparel companies, five
retail stores, four footwear companies and four furniture
subsidiaries.
   The company plans to sell off all but its Converse Inc. and
Florsheim Shoe Co. subsidiaries, Broyhill Furniture Industries Inc.
and Lane Co. furniture companies and possibly the Central Hardware
home-improvement stores.
   Interco reported earnings of $76.08 million, or $2.02 per share,
for the nine months ended Nov. 30, down from $108.39 million, or
$2.57 per share, in the year-earlier period.
   Sales totaled $1.95 billion, up from $1.91 billion in the same
period of 1987.
</TEXT>
