<FIRST>r f BC-HollyFarms     01-10 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Holly Farms,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Sets Bidding Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. set a deadline of Wednesday
for bids for the company in hopes of ending the battle for the
chicken processor.
   In a letter to Tyson Foods Inc. and ConAgra Inc., Holly Farms
said its board would meet Wednesday to consider buyout offers and
make a recommendation to stockholders.
   Ted Bailey, a Holly Farms vice president, told the Omaha
World-Herald in a story printed Monday the deadline was an effort
``to bring this process to a conclusion.''
   ConAgra, of Omaha, and Tyson, of Springdale, Ark., have made
separate proposals for Holly Farms.
   Last fall, Tyson offered to buy Holly Farms for $54 a share, or
$977 million. Later, to ward off the hostile offer, Holly Farms
agreed to be acquired by ConAgra in a stock swap valued at $1
billion.
   Tyson increased its offer Friday to $60 a share, or $1.06 billion.
   The winner would emerge as the nation's top chicken processor.
Tyson holds the lead, with 14.1 percent of the market, and ConAgra
is second, with 9.5 percent. Holly Farm's share is 6.6 percent.
   Under Holly Farm's agreement with ConAgra, the Omaha company
would exchange between 1.875 and two shares of its stock for each of
Holly Farm's common shares. The proposal is valued at $59.25 a share.
   ConAgra also would have been given the opportunity to buy nearly
half of Holly Farm's assets _ a transaction valued at more than $400
million _ if the acquisition were not completed.
   Tyson filed a lawsuit in Delaware Chancery Court last month
challenging that provision, called an asset lockup option. The court
agreed with Tyson, blocking the asset lockup, as well as $15 million
Holly Farms agreed to pay as a termination fee if the acquisition
weren't completed.
   In its letter, Holly said its board would consider Tyson's
$60-a-share offer ``together with any further proposal that either
Tyson or ConAgra might wish to make.''
   A spokesman for ConAgra in Omaha declined to say whether the
company will make a new offer.
   Holly urged stockholders not to make any decision until after its
board had met and made its recommendation.
   Bailey said companies other than ConAgra and Tyson ``would have a
right to make a legitimate offer,'' but he said he didn't expect any
other offers.
</TEXT>
