<FIRST>r f BC-UtilityMerger     01-10 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Utility Merger,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>PacifiCorp Completes Merger With Utah Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PacifiCorp announced the completion of its
merger with Utah Power &amp; Light, saying UP&amp;L shareholders would be
notified next week about swapping their shares for stock in the new
company.
   The merger announced Tuesday creates the third largest electric
utility west of the Mississippi River. PacifiCorp will now have two
energy services division _ Pacific Power &amp; Light Co., headquartered
in Portland, and UP&amp;L, headquartered in Salt Lake City _ serving
about 1.2 million customers.
   The cost of the merger is between $18 million and $20 million,
but PacifiCorp estimates it will save more than $50 million the
first year and $500 million in the first five years of combined
operation.
   The two companies first announced their intentions to merge Aug.
12, 1987. Final regulatory approval, needed from the seven Western
states they serve and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, was
received Dec. 19.
   ``We haven't been standing still during the months it's taken to
complete the merger,'' said Gleason, adding the new utility would
``hit the ground running.''
   During the 18-month effort to combine the two companies,
employees from both worked on 16 separate task forces to streamline
the organizations and lower costs, said David Bolender, president of
PacifiCorp's existing electric utility, Pacific Power &amp; Light Co.
   Calculating the average price per share during a 10-day span from
Dec. 19-Jan. 3 at slightly more than $35.71, Utah Power shareholders
will receive 0.909 shares of PacifiCorp stock for each Utah Power
share, the statement said.
   Instructions on the exchange process will be sent to Utah Power
shareholdrs beginning next week, according to the statement.
   Pacific Power will retain its name in the six states it serves:
Oregon, California, Idaho, Wyoming, Washington and Montana. UP&amp;L
will continue to operate under its own name in its present Utah,
Wyoming and Idaho service areas.
   Together, the utility businesses will contribute annual revenues
in excess of $2 billion, or about 70 percent, to PacifiCorp's
consolidated revenue.
   Gleason said PacifiCorp, which was an early leader in electric
utility diversification, will continue to expand into other
businesses. Other activities with which PacifiCorp has become
involved since the 1970s include mining, telecommunications and
financial services.
</TEXT>
